{{About|urban rail transportation in China|urban rail transport in Hong Kong|Rapid transit in Hong Kong|urban rail transportation in Taiwan (the Republic of China)|rail transport in Taiwan{{!}}Rail transportation in Taiwan}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2020}}
[[File:ÖPNV-Systeme in China.png|400px|thumb|Map of cities in [[Greater China]] ([[China|mainland China]], the [[Special administrative regions of China|SARs]], and [[Taiwan]]) with [[rapid transit]], [[commuter rail]] and [[light rail]] systems. The two higher-resolution maps to the left show the [[Yangtze River Delta]] (YRD) and [[Pearl River Delta]] (PRD) regions.|alt=]]
'''Urban rail transit in China''' encompasses a broad range of [[urban area|urban]] and [[suburban]] electric passenger rail [[mass transit]] systems including [[Passenger rail terminology#Metro/subway|subway]], [[light rail]], [[tram]] and [[Maglev (transport)|maglev]].<ref name="中国城市轨道交通China Urban Mass Transit">{{cite web | url=http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/cn_sgfw/2008-06/03/content_108950.htm |script-title=zh:中国城市轨道交通 |trans-title=China Urban Mass Transit | access-date=18 February 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120404031812/http://www.chinaculture.org/gb/cn_sgfw/2008-06/03/content_108950.htm | archive-date=4 April 2012 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Some classifications also include non-rail [[bus rapid transport]]. 

As of December 2024, [[China]] has the world's longest [[urban rail transit]] system{{Failed verification|date=May 2025}} with {{convert|11000.88|km|mi|abbr=on}} of urban rail nationwide{{Failed verification|date=May 2025}} in 310 metro lines in 47 cities{{Failed verification|date=May 2025}}, accounting for [[List of metro systems#List|9 of the 10 longest]] metro systems, with the exceptions of the [[Moscow Metro]].<ref>{{Cite web |last= |date=21 June 2022 |title=China dominates list of the world's top 10 longest metro networks |url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/metros/china-dominates-list-of-the-worlds-top-10-longest-metro-networks/61865.article |access-date=2022-07-06 |website=Railway Gazette International |language=en}}</ref>

Half of the top 10 busiest metro systems are in China,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sh.eastday.com/m/20160106/u1ai9170020.html|title=中国27城开通轨交:运营线路上海最长 为579.2公里|website=sh.eastday.com|access-date=28 January 2016|archive-date=8 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308175255/http://sh.eastday.com/m/20160106/u1ai9170020.html}}</ref> and the [[Shanghai Metro]], though started operating in 1993, is now the longest metro system worldwide.<ref name="longest" /><ref name="BBC">Archived at [https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211205/dNCaK4d0GA0 Ghostarchive]{{cbignore}} and the [https://web.archive.org/web/20140104110759/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dNCaK4d0GA0&gl=US&hl=en Wayback Machine]{{cbignore}}: {{cite web| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dNCaK4d0GA0| title = LONGEST UNDERGROUND NETWORK IN THE WORLD - SHANGHAI SUBWAY - BBC NEWS | website=[[YouTube]]| date = 4 January 2014 }}{{cbignore}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/shanghai-now-the-worlds-longest-metro.html|title=Shanghai now the world's longest metro|date=4 May 2010|work=Railway Gazette|access-date=9 April 2014|archive-date=10 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410014003/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/shanghai-now-the-worlds-longest-metro.html}}</ref>
{{TOClimit|3}}
{{-}}

==History==
Several Chinese cities had urban electric tramways [[Republic of China (1912–1949)|in the early 20th century]], most of which were dismantled in the 1950s–1970s. The only surviving tramways are in [[Dalian]] (Dairen) and [[Changchun]] (see [[trams in Dalian]] and [[trams in Changchun]]). [[Nanjing]] (Nanking) had {{ill|Ningsheng Railway|lt=an urban railway|zh|宁省铁路}} from 1907 to 1958. 

The [[Beijing Subway|first subway in China]] was built in [[Beijing]] in 1969 (but it was only handed to civilian control in 1981 and trial operations ended later in the same year; before which credentials were required). The [[Tianjin Metro]] followed in 1984. The [[MTR Corporation Limited]] from across the border in [[Hong Kong]] has investment, consulting and management stakes in the rapid transit systems of several mainland Chinese cities (having completed [[MTR#Modified Initial System|their first section of subway]] and entered into revenue operation in 1979 in New Kowloon, at the time when the territory was [[British Hong Kong|under British rule]]).

The rapid growth of the [[Economy of China|Chinese economy]] since the 1980s has created a huge surge in demand for urban transport. This prompted cities across China to pursue and draft proposals for subway networks, with [[Shanghai Metro|Shanghai]] and [[Guangzhou Metro|Guangzhou]] opening their first sections of subway in the 1990s, inspiring more cities to propose subway networks. In 1995, the Central Government, alarmed by the high cost and financial debt from these ambitious subway plans, put out a "notice on the suspension of approval of urban underground rapid rail transit projects" barring new subway systems outside of Beijing, Tianjin, Guangzhou and Shanghai from being built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sztqb.sznews.com/html/2010-04/14/content_1035002.htm |script-title=zh:深圳地铁"十年怀胎"终圆梦---深圳特区报|website=sztqb.sznews.com|access-date=11 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106183158/http://sztqb.sznews.com/html/2010-04/14/content_1035002.htm|archive-date=6 January 2016}}</ref> At the time [[Nanjing Metro|Nanjing]], [[Wuhan Metro|Wuhan]], [[Chongqing Rail Transit|Chongqing]], [[Dalian Metro|Dalian]] and [[Shenzhen Metro|Shenzhen]] had advanced proposals waiting to be approved. [[Wuhan Metro|Wuhan]], [[Chongqing Rail Transit|Chongqing]], [[Dalian Metro|Dalian]] managed to circumvent the moratorium on subway construction by constructing and opening lower cost elevated lines, [[light metro]]s, and [[monorail]]s in the early 2000s. [[Changchun Rail Transit|Changchun]] was the first city constructing real [[light rail]] system in China, which began operation in 2002. Its first transit line, [[Line 3 (Changchun Rail Transit)|Line 3]], is a light rail line not fully grade separated, still having four level crossings as of 2023. It's also the only rapid transit system combined light rail and rapid transit lines in China, which can directly transfer to each other.{{fact|date=January 2024}}

Rapid urbanization of China led to severe congestion and pollution in urban areas leading to the suspension being lifted. Initially, [[light metro]] lines using small profile and shorter rolling stock were constructed to reduce costs. It was assumed that as ridership grows the line will operate trains at a low headway to increase capacity. This design paradigm was known in China as "small rolling stock, high density" operation.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Lu Fang (鲁放) |author2=Han Baoming (韩宝明) |author3=Li Dewei (李得伟) |author4=Zhang Qi (张琦) |script-title=zh:城市轨道交通小编组高密度运行的合理实施[J] |journal=城市轨道交通研究 [Urban Rail Transport Research Institute] |volume=2009 |issue=8 |pages=4–7}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Chen Haoran (陈浩然) |script-title=zh:用于城市轨道交通的小编组、高密度列车运行方案[J] |journal=中国铁路 |volume=2001 |issue=5| pages=44–46}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=Chen Haoran (陈浩然) |script-title=zh:采用小编组、高密度列车运行方案——是降低工程造价及运营费用的有效途径[J] |journal=中国铁路 |volume=2002 |issue=1 |pages=39–45}}</ref> However, after a few years operating, many of these lines such as Guangzhou Metro [[Line 3 (Guangzhou Metro)|Line 3]], [[Line 6 (Guangzhou Metro)|Line 6]], Shanghai Metro [[Line 6 (Shanghai Metro)|Line 6]], and [[Line 8 (Shanghai Metro)|Line 8]] were severely overcapacity. Guangzhou Metro [[Line 3 (Guangzhou Metro)|Line 3]] was able to reconfigure from 3-car trains into 6-car trains to slightly relieve overcapacity. This led many cities such as Beijing, Guangzhou, Wuhan and Chengdu to use higher capacity designs on newer lines.{{fact|date=January 2024}}

Since the mid-2000s, the growth of rapid transit systems in Chinese cities has rapidly accelerated, with most of the world's new subway mileage in the past decade opening in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itdp.org/rapid-transit-trends/|title=Rapid Transit Trends Show Record Growth in 2016, with Huge Increases in China, Brazil – Institute for Transportation and Development Policy|date=17 February 2017|work=Institute for Transportation and Development Policy|access-date=9 April 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="longest">{{cite news|url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/metros/chinese-metro-boom-shows-no-sign-of-abating.html?channel=525|title=Chinese metro boom shows no sign of abating|date=19 November 2014|work=International Rail Journal|access-date=23 November 2014|archive-date=8 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208185120/http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/metros/chinese-metro-boom-shows-no-sign-of-abating.html?channel=525}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2018/01/17/in-response-to-growth-chinese-cities-choose-metros/|title=In response to growth, Chinese cities choose metros|date=17 January 2018|work=The Transport Politic|access-date=20 January 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itdp.org/2018/07/30/china-drives-rapid-transit-growth/|title=China's Metro Boom Continues to Drive Rapid Transit Growth – Institute for Transportation and Development Policy|date=30 July 2018|work=Institute for Transportation and Development Policy|access-date=20 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> From 2009 to 2015, China built 87 mass transit rail lines, totaling {{convert|3100|km|abbr=on}}, in 25 cities at the cost of [[RMB|¥]]988.6 billion.<ref>{{cite web |language=zh-hans |url=http://business.sohu.com/20100323/n271038342.shtml |script-title=zh:谁的地铁，谁做主？ |publisher=[[Sohu]] Business |date=23 March 2010}}</ref> In 2016, the Chinese government lowered the minimum population criteria for a city to start planning a metro system from 3 million to 1.5 million residents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-transport-investment/china-to-let-more-cities-build-metro-systems-economic-information-daily-idUSKCN0Y70I1|title=China to let more cities build metro systems – Economic Information Daily|date=16 May 2016|work=Reuters|access-date=9 September 2017}}</ref> As part of its [[Five-year plans of China|13th Five Year Plan]], the Chinese government published a transport whitepaper titled "Development of China's Transport". The plan envisions a more sustainable transport system with priority focused on high-capacity public transit particularly [[urban rail transit]] and [[bus rapid transit]]. All cities with over 3 million residents will start or continue to develop urban rail networks. [[Regional rail]] networks will be constructed internally connect and integrate urban agglomerations such as the [[Jingjinji]], [[Yangtze River Delta]] and [[Pearl River Delta]] areas.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/nation/China-to-build-more-highspeed-railways-in-five-years-white-paper/shdaily.shtml|title=China to build more high-speed railways in five years: white paper|website=shanghaidaily.com|date=29 December 2016 |access-date=31 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghaidaily.com/nation/A-transport-system-to-lead-the-world/shdaily.shtml|title=A transport system to lead the world|website=shanghaidaily.com|date=29 December 2016 |access-date=31 December 2016}}</ref> In 2017, some 43 smaller third-tier cities in China have received approval to develop subway lines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yicaiglobal.com/news/over-40-chinese-third-tier-cities-plan-build-subway-systems|title=Over 40 Chinese Third-Tier Cities Plan to Build Subway Systems|website=Yicai Global|access-date=9 September 2017|archive-date=10 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170910041641/https://www.yicaiglobal.com/news/over-40-chinese-third-tier-cities-plan-build-subway-systems}}</ref>


