'''WikiLeaks''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|w|ɪ|k|i|l|iː|k|s}}) is a non-profit media organisation and publisher of leaked documents. It is funded by donations{{refn|name=intNP|<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cardoso|first1=Gustavo|last2=Jacobetty|author-link1=Gustavo Cardoso|first2=Pedro|title=Aftermath: The Cultures of the Economic Crisis|chapter=Surfing the Crisis: Cultures of Belonging and Networked Social Change|date=2012|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|editor-last1=Castells|editor-first1=Manuel|editor-link1=Manuel Castells|editor-last2=Caraça|editor-first2=João|editor-last3=Cardoso|editor-first3=Gustavo|editor-link3=Gustavo Cardoso|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199658411|pages=177–209|quote=WikiLeaks is also based on an openness culture, as it is a crowd-sourced, crowd-funded non-profit organization operating internationally.|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/aftermath-9780199658411|access-date=9 May 2023|archive-date=29 May 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529044951/https://global.oup.com/academic/product/aftermath-9780199658411|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=PoSk19>{{cite book |last1=Pogrebna |first1=Ganna |author-link1=Ganna Pogrebna |last2=Skilton |first2=Mark |title=Navigating New Cyber Risks: How Businesses Can Plan, Build and Manage Safe Spaces in the Digital Age |date=2019 |publisher=[[Palgrave MacMillan]] |location=[[Cham, Switzerland]] |isbn=9783030135270 |page=2 |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-13527-0 |s2cid=197966404 |quote=WikiLeaks is an international non profit organization that receives and subsequently shares on its website confidential documents from large organizations or governments. |url=https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-030-13527-0 |access-date=7 May 2023 |archive-date=8 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230508105040/https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-030-13527-0 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Braccini|first1=Alessio Maria|last2=Federici|first2=Tommaso|editor-last1=Baskerville|editor-first1=Richard|editor-last2=De Marco|editor-first2=Marco|editor-last3=Spagnoletti|editor-first3=Paolo|chapter=New Internet-Based Relationships Between Citizens|url=https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-642-33371-2|title=Designing Organizational Systems: An Interdisciplinary Discourse|date=2013|quote=Julian Assange had introduced a new term into the lexicon of several generations. This term was 'WikiLeaks' and described an international non-profit organisation, committed to publishing secret information, news leaks, and classified media provided by anonymous sources.|publisher=[[Springer Nature]]|location=Berlin|isbn=978-3-642-33370-5|pages=157–179|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-33371-2|access-date=7 May 2023|archive-date=9 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230509041342/https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-642-33371-2|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hindman |first1=Elizabeth Blanks |last2=Thomas |first2=Ryan J |title=When Old and New Media Collide: The Case of WikiLeaks|quote=WikiLeaks was founded in 2006 as an international non-profit organization specializing in the publication of 'classified, censored or otherwise restricted material of political, diplomatic or ethical significance' obtained via anonymous sources|journal=[[New Media & Society]]|publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]]|date=June 2014 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=541–558 |doi=10.1177/1461444813489504|s2cid=30711318  |issn = 1461-4448}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dodds |first1=Klaus J.|author-link=Klaus Dodds |title=The WikiLeaks Arctic Cables|quote=With a keen sense of timing, given the Greenlandic and Danish governments' hosting of the 7th Arctic Council ministerial meeting, seven 'sensitive' US diplomatic cables were leaked by WikiLeaks, an international non-profit organisation that publishes materials from anonymous sources, news leaks, and whistleblowers|journal=[[Polar Record]]|location=Cambridge|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|date=2012 |volume=48 |issue=2 |pages=199–201 |doi=10.1017/S003224741100043X|bibcode=2012PoRec..48..199D |s2cid=129682201 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Benkler|first=Yochai|author-link=Yochai Benkler|title=A Free Irresponsible Press: Wikileaks and the Battle over the Soul of the Networked Fourth Estate|journal=[[Harvard Civil Rights–Civil Liberties Law Review]]|date=2011|volume=46|issue=2|location=Cambridge|publisher=[[Harvard Law School]]|pages=311–397|via=[[Harvard Library]]|url=https://dash.harvard.edu/handle/1/10900863|quote=Wikileaks is a nonprofit that depends on donations from around the world to fund its operation. A second system that came under attack on a model parallel to the attack on technical infrastructure was the payment system... Like the Sunlight Foundation and similar transparency-focused organizations, Wikileaks is a nonprofit focused on bringing to light direct, documentary evidence about government behavior so that many others, professional and otherwise, can analyze the evidence and search for instances that justify public criticism.|access-date=9 May 2023|archive-date=19 December 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231219105808/https://dash.harvard.edu/handle/1/10900863|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Fuchs |first1=Christian |title=Social Media: A Critical Introduction |date=2014 |publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]] |location=London/Thousand Oaks |chapter=WikiLeaks: Can We Make Power Transparent? |quote=WikiLeaks (www.wikileaks.org) is a non-commercial and non-profit Internet whistleblowing platform that has been online since 2006. Julian Assange founded it. It is funded by online donations. |isbn=978-1-4462-5730-2 |pages=210–233 |url=https://sk.sagepub.com/books/social-media-a-critical-introduction |access-date=9 May 2023 |archive-date=9 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230109165510/https://sk.sagepub.com/books/social-media-a-critical-introduction |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Beckett |first1=Charlie |title=Wikileaks: News in the Networked Era |date=2012 |publisher=[[Wiley (publisher)|Wiley]] |location=Cambridge |isbn=978-0-745-65975-6 |page=26 |url=https://www.wiley.com/en-ie/WikiLeaks:+News+in+the+Networked+Era-p-9780745659756|quote=WikiLeaks is independent of commercial, corporate, government or lobbygroup control or ownership. It is a non-membership, non-profit organisation funded by donations}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Flesher Fominaya|first1=Cristina|title=Social Movements in a Globalized World|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|date=2020|page=177|location=London|isbn=9781352009347|edition=Second|url=https://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/social-movements-in-a-globalized-world-9781352009347/|quote=As a non-profit organization, Wikileaks is funded by crowdfunding donations, which were subsequently blocked by PayPal, Mastercard, a Swiss Bank and Bank of America in protest over their political activity, a troubling example of 'the ability of private infrastructure companies to restrict speech without being bound by the constraints of legality, and the possibility that government actors will take advantage of this affordance in an extra-legal public-private partnership for censorship'.|access-date=9 May 2023|archive-date=13 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713051528/https://www.bloomsbury.com/uk/social-movements-in-a-globalized-world-9781352009347/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Daly|first1=Angela|title=The Privatization of the Internet, WikiLeaks and Free Expression|journal=[[International Journal of Communication]]|date=2014|volume=8|pages=2693–2703|ssrn=2496707|location=Los Angeles|publisher=[[USC Annenberg Press]]|url=https://cadmus.eui.eu/handle/1814/35102|via=[[European University Institute]]|quote=In late 2010, the online nonprofit media organization WikiLeaks published classified documents detailing correspondence between the U.S. State Department and its diplomatic missions around the world, numbering around 250,000 cables.|access-date=9 May 2023|archive-date=12 May 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230512045335/https://cadmus.eui.eu/handle/1814/35102|url-status=live}}</ref>}} and media partnerships. It has published classified documents and other media provided by anonymous sources.<ref name="The New York Times">{{cite news |url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/w/wikileaks/ |title=WikiLeaks |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=17 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130094619/http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/w/wikileaks/index.html |archive-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> It was founded in 2006 by [[Julian Assange]].<ref name="McGreal">{{cite news |last=McGreal |first=Chris |title=Wikileaks reveals video showing US air crew shooting down Iraqi civilians |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/apr/05/wikileaks-us-army-iraq-attack |access-date=15 December 2010 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=5 April 2010 |place=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626230310/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/apr/05/wikileaks-us-army-iraq-attack |archive-date=26 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Kristinn Hrafnsson]] is its [[editor-in-chief]].<ref name="Associated Press">{{cite news|url=https://www.apnews.com/df4b97d353c34ce4baa02f671dd6321b|title=WikiLeaks names one-time spokesman as editor-in-chief|work=[[Associated Press]]|access-date=26 September 2018|language=en-US|archive-date=13 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190913194734/https://www.apnews.com/df4b97d353c34ce4baa02f671dd6321b|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Bridge">{{cite news|last=Bridge|first=Mark|url=https://www.thetimes.com/uk/politics/article/loss-of-internet-forces-assange-to-step-down-from-wikileaks-editor-role-q8ndg5jkc|title=Loss of internet forces Assange to step down from Wikileaks editor role|work=The Times|date=27 September 2018|access-date=11 April 2019|url-access=subscription|archive-date=15 February 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215173449/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/loss-of-internet-forces-assange-to-step-down-from-wikileaks-editor-role-q8ndg5jkc|url-status=live}}</ref> Its website states that it has released more than ten million documents and associated analyses.<ref name="WikiLeaks">{{cite web |title=What is Wikileaks |url=https://wikileaks.org/What-is-WikiLeaks.html |access-date=14 April 2020 |website=WikiLeaks |archive-date=23 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023100920/https://wikileaks.org/What-is-Wikileaks.html |url-status=live }}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref> WikiLeaks' most recent publication of original documents was in 2019 and its most recent publication was in 2021.<ref name="Gizmodo-2022b2">{{Cite web |date=22 November 2022 |title=WikiLeaks' Website Is Falling Apart |url=https://gizmodo.com/wikileaks-julian-assange-1849813101 |access-date=24 December 2022 |website=Gizmodo |language=en |archive-date=15 April 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240415224936/https://gizmodo.com/wikileaks-julian-assange-1849813101 |url-status=live }}</ref> From November 2022, numerous documents on the organisation's<!-- This article uses Australian English, do not change "organisation" to "organization"—you will be reverted. --> website became inaccessible.<ref name="Gizmodo-2022b2"/><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Burgess |first=Matt |title=Apple Tracks You More Than You Think |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-iphone-privacy-analytics-security-roundup/ |access-date=24 December 2022 |issn=1059-1028 |archive-date=4 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231104084414/https://www.wired.com/story/apple-iphone-privacy-analytics-security-roundup/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2023, Assange said that WikiLeaks is no longer able to publish due to his imprisonment and the effect that US government surveillance and WikiLeaks' funding restrictions were having on potential whistleblowers.<ref name="Glass-2024" />

WikiLeaks has released [[List of material published by WikiLeaks|document caches]] and media that exposed serious violations of [[human rights]] and [[civil liberties]] by various governments. It released footage of the [[July 12, 2007, Baghdad airstrike|12{{nbsp}}July 2007 Baghdad airstrike]], titling it ''Collateral Murder'', in which Iraqi [[Reuters]] journalists and several other civilians were killed by a U.S. helicopter crew.<ref name="RSF-Julliard-2010a">{{Cite web |title=Reporters Sans Frontières – Open letter to Wikileaks founder Julian Assange: ''A bad precedent for the Internet's future'' |url=http://en.rsf.org/united-states-open-letter-to-wikileaks-founder-12-08-2010,38130.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815072941/http://en.rsf.org/united-states-open-letter-to-wikileaks-founder-12-08-2010,38130.html |archive-date=15 August 2010 |access-date=1 May 2022}}</ref> It published thousands of US military field logs from the [[United States documents leak of the War in Afghanistan|war in Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq War documents leak|Iraq war]], [[United States diplomatic cables leak|diplomatic cables from the United States]] and [[Saudi Arabia]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Hubbard |first=Ben |date=20 June 2015 |title=Cables Released by WikiLeaks Reveal Saudis' Checkbook Diplomacy |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/world/middleeast/cables-released-by-wikileaks-reveal-saudis-checkbook-diplomacy.html |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=13 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513172356/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/21/world/middleeast/cables-released-by-wikileaks-reveal-saudis-checkbook-diplomacy.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Zorthian |first=Julia |date=19 June 2015 |title=WikiLeaks Begins Releasing Leaked Saudi Arabia Cables |url=https://time.com/3928584/wikileaks-saudi-arabia-cables/ |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=21 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421043839/http://time.com/3928584/wikileaks-saudi-arabia-cables/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Syria Files|emails from the governments of Syria]]<ref>{{cite news |date=5 July 2012 |title=Syria files: Wikileaks releases 2m 'embarrassing' emails |publisher=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-18724328 |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=22 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722084345/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-18724328 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |date=5 July 2012 |title=WikiLeaks Announces Massive Release With The 'Syria Files': 2.4 Million Emails From Syrian Officials And Companies |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2012/07/05/wikileaks-announces-its-largest-release-yet-in-the-syria-files-2-4-million-emails-from-syrian-officials-and-companies/#752b7eae5081 |magazine=[[Forbes]] |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=10 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120710135536/http://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2012/07/05/wikileaks-announces-its-largest-release-yet-in-the-syria-files-2-4-million-emails-from-syrian-officials-and-companies/#752b7eae5081 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Turkey]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Yeung |first=Peter |date=20 July 2016 |title=President Erdogan emails: What is in the Wikileaks release about Turkey's government? |work=[[The Independent]] |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/wikileaks-turkey-erdogan-emails-government-coup-a7145891.html |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=22 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190422000012/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/wikileaks-turkey-erdogan-emails-government-coup-a7145891.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Doctorow |first=Cory |date=29 July 2016 |title=Wikileaks' dump of "Erdogan emails" turn out to be public mailing list archives |publisher=BoingBoing |url=https://boingboing.net/2016/07/29/wikileaks-dump-of-erdogan.html |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=21 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421055645/https://boingboing.net/2016/07/29/wikileaks-dump-of-erdogan.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="fp071216">{{cite magazine |last=Gramer |first=Robbie |date=7 December 2016 |title=Latest Wikileaks Dump Sheds New Light on Erdogan's Power In Turkey |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/12/07/latest-wikileaks-dump-sheds-light-erdogan-turkey-berat-albayrak-redhack-hackers-oil/ |magazine=Foreign Policy |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=3 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503230755/https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/12/07/latest-wikileaks-dump-sheds-light-erdogan-turkey-berat-albayrak-redhack-hackers-oil/ |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks has also published documents exposing corruption in [[Kenya]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Dahir |first=Abdi Latif |date=13 April 2019 |title=It all started in Nairobi: How Kenya gave Julian Assange's WikiLeaks its first major global scoop |url=https://qz.com/africa/1594656/the-kenyan-roots-of-julian-assanges-wikileaks/ |access-date=20 April 2019 |publisher=Quartz Africa |archive-date=3 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703193227/https://qz.com/africa/1594656/the-kenyan-roots-of-julian-assanges-wikileaks/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rice |first=Xan |date=31 August 2007 |title=The looting of Kenya |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/31/kenya.topstories3 |access-date=20 April 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-date=31 January 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131213722/http://www.guardian.co.uk/kenya/story/0,,2159757,00.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and at [[Samherji]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=PPLAAF |date=7 March 2022 |title=The Fishrot scandal |url=https://pplaaf.org/cases/fishrot.html |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=pplaaf.org |language=en |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529044956/https://www.pplaaf.org/cases/fishrot.html |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Vault 7|cyber warfare and surveillance tools]] created by the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Menn |first=Joseph |date=29 March 2017 |title=A scramble at Cisco exposes uncomfortable truths about U.S. cyber defense |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-defense-idUSKBN17013U |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=8 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190508062146/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-cyber-defense-idUSKBN17013U |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shane |first1=Scott |last2=Rosenberg |first2=Matthew |last3=Lehren |first3=Andrew W. |date=7 March 2017 |title=WikiLeaks Releases Trove of Alleged C.I.A. Hacking Documents |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/07/world/europe/wikileaks-cia-hacking.html |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=7 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170307212004/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/07/world/europe/wikileaks-cia-hacking.html |url-status=live }}</ref> and surveillance of the French president by the [[National Security Agency]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Regan |first1=James |last2=John |first2=Mark |date=23 June 2015 |title=NSA spied on French presidents: WikiLeaks |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-wikileaks/nsa-spied-on-french-presidents-wikileaks-idUSKBN0P32EM20150623 |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=21 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421044759/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-france-wikileaks/nsa-spied-on-french-presidents-wikileaks-idUSKBN0P32EM20150623 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rubin |first1=Alyssa J. |last2=Shane |first2=Scott |date=24 June 2015 |title=Hollande Condemns Spying by U.S., but Not Too Harshly |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/25/world/europe/wikileaks-us-spying-france.html |access-date=20 April 2019 |archive-date=21 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421044759/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/25/world/europe/wikileaks-us-spying-france.html |url-status=live }}</ref> During the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election campaign]], WikiLeaks [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak|released emails]] from the [[Democratic National Committee]] (DNC) and from [[Podesta emails|Hillary Clinton's campaign manager]], showing that the party's national committee had effectively acted as an arm of the Clinton campaign during the [[United States presidential primary|primaries]], seeking to undercut the campaign of [[Bernie Sanders]]. These releases resulted in the resignation of the chairwoman of the DNC and caused significant harm to the [[Hillary Clinton 2016 presidential campaign|Clinton campaign]].<ref name="Baum-Gussin-2016">{{cite news |title=Why it's entirely predictable that Hillary Clinton's emails are back in the news |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/11/01/why-its-entirely-predictable-that-hillary-clintons-emails-are-back-in-the-news/ |access-date=12 November 2016 |archive-date=20 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620102022/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/11/01/why-its-entirely-predictable-that-hillary-clintons-emails-are-back-in-the-news/ |url-status=live }}</ref> During the campaign, WikiLeaks promoted false conspiracy theories about Hillary Clinton, the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and the [[murder of Seth Rich]].<ref name="Ohlheiser-2016">{{Cite news |last=Ohlheiser |first=Abby |date=4 November 2016 |title=No, John Podesta didn't drink bodily fluids at a secret Satanist dinner |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2016/11/04/no-john-podesta-didnt-drink-bodily-fluids-at-a-secret-satanist-dinner/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=14 January 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210114152001/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-intersect/wp/2016/11/04/no-john-podesta-didnt-drink-bodily-fluids-at-a-secret-satanist-dinner/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Seitz-Wald-2016">{{Cite news |title=WikiLeaks Fuels Conspiracy Theories About DNC Staffer's Death |publisher=[[NBC News]] |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/wikileaks-fuels-conspiracy-theories-about-dnc-staffer-s-death-n627401 |access-date=8 November 2016 |quote=WikiLeaks ... is fueling Internet conspiracy theories by offering a $20,000 reward for information on a Democratic National Committee staffer who was killed last month ... in what police say was robbery gone wrong ... Assange implied this week in an interview that Rich was the source of the leak and even offered a $20,000 reward for information leading to the arrest of his murderer. Meanwhile, the Russian government funded propaganda outlet RT had already been covering Rich's murder two weeks prior. RT and other Russian government propaganda outlets have also been working hard to deny the Russian government was the source of the leak, including by interviewing Assange about the Rich murder. ... The original conspiracy theory can be traced back to a notoriously unreliable conspiracy website |archive-date=12 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210212185833/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/wikileaks-fuels-conspiracy-theories-about-dnc-staffer-s-death-n627401 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="bloomberg">{{cite news |last1=Chafkin |first1=Max |last2=Silver |first2=Vernon |date=10 October 2016 |title=How Julian Assange turned WikiLeaks into Trump's best friend |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-10-11/how-julian-assange-turned-wikileaks-into-trump-s-best-friend |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109132018/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-10-11/how-julian-assange-turned-wikileaks-into-trump-s-best-friend |archive-date=9 November 2016 |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]}}</ref>

WikiLeaks has won numerous awards and been commended by media organisations, civil society organisations, and world leaders for exposing state and corporate secrets, increasing transparency, assisting [[freedom of the press]], and enhancing democratic discourse while challenging powerful institutions. The organisation has been the target of campaigns to discredit it, including aborted ones by [[Palantir Technologies|Palantir]] and [[HBGary]]. WikiLeaks has also had its donation systems interrupted by [[payment processor]]s. As a result, the [[Wau Holland Foundation]] helps process WikiLeaks' donations.

The organisation has been criticised for inadequately curating content and violating personal privacy. WikiLeaks has, for instance, revealed [[Social Security number]]s, [[Medical record|medical information]], [[credit card numbers]] and details of [[suicide attempt]]s.<ref name="Brustein-2016">{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-29/why-wikileaks-is-losing-its-friends |title=Why Wikileaks Is Losing Its Friends |first=Joshua |last=Brustein |date=29 July 2016 |publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |access-date=6 January 2017 |archive-date=21 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721161843/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-29/why-wikileaks-is-losing-its-friends |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Satter-2016">{{Cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b70da83fd111496dbdf015acbb7987fb/private-lives-are-exposed-wikileaks-spills-its-secrets |title=Private lives are exposed as WikiLeaks spills its secrets |first1=Raphael |last1=Satter |first2=Maggie |last2=Michael |date=23 August 2016 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |language=en-US |access-date=6 January 2017 |archive-date=7 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107170443/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/b70da83fd111496dbdf015acbb7987fb/private-lives-are-exposed-wikileaks-spills-its-secrets |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="Peterson-2016">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/07/28/a-twitter-spat-breaks-out-between-snowden-and-wikileaks/ |title=Snowden and WikiLeaks clash over leaked Democratic Party emails |first=Andrea |last=Peterson |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=28 July 2016 |archive-date=22 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822082253/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/07/28/a-twitter-spat-breaks-out-between-snowden-and-wikileaks/ |url-status=live }}</ref> News organisations, activists, journalists and former members have also criticised WikiLeaks over allegations of anti-Clinton and pro-Trump bias and a lack of internal transparency. Some journalists have alleged it had associations with the Russian government. Journalists have also criticised the organisation for promotion of conspiracy theories, and what they describe as exaggerated and misleading descriptions of the contents of leaks. The US [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] and [[United States Congress]] characterised the organisation as a "[[Non-state actor|non-state]] hostile [[Intelligence agency|intelligence service]]"  after the release of CIA tools for hacking consumer electronics in [[Vault 7]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=U.S. prosecution of alleged WikiLeaks 'Vault 7' source hits multiple roadblocks |url=https://news.yahoo.com/us-prosecution-of-alleged-wiki-leaks-vault-7-source-hits-multiple-roadblocks-235450811.html |access-date=16 October 2022 |website=news.yahoo.com |date=6 October 2021 |language=en-US |archive-date=7 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211007113847/https://news.yahoo.com/us-prosecution-of-alleged-wiki-leaks-vault-7-source-hits-multiple-roadblocks-235450811.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
{{TOC limit|4}}

== History ==
=== Founding ===

[[File:Julian Assange August 2014.jpg|thumb|upright=.75|[[Julian Assange]] is a founding member of the WikiLeaks staff.]]

The inspiration for WikiLeaks was [[Daniel Ellsberg]]'s release of the [[Pentagon Papers]] in 1971. Assange built WikiLeaks to shorten the time between a leak and its coverage by the media. WikiLeaks was established in [[Australia]] with the help of Daniel Mathews<ref>{{Cite news |date=22 August 2013 |title=Assange blames party 'teething problems' after candidate quits |language=en-AU |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-08-22/assange-blames-party-teething-problems/4904366 |access-date=15 September 2023 |archive-date=19 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230919103932/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-08-22/assange-blames-party-teething-problems/4904366 |url-status=live }}</ref> and its servers were soon moved to [[Sweden]] and other countries that provided greater legal protection for the media.<ref name="yahoo041021" /> Assange described WikiLeaks as an activist organisation and said that "The method is transparency, the goal is justice".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pontin |first1=Jason |title=Secrets and Transparency |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/2011/01/26/197387/secrets-and-transparency/ |website=MIT Technology Review |access-date=21 February 2024 |language=en |date=26 January 2011 |archive-date=21 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240221075504/https://www.technologyreview.com/2011/01/26/197387/secrets-and-transparency/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Sontheimer |first1=Michael |title=SPIEGEL Interview with WikiLeaks Head Julian Assange |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/world/spiegel-interview-with-wikileaks-head-julian-assange-a-1044399.html |website=Der Spiegel |access-date=25 February 2024 |language=en |date=20 July 2015 |archive-date=3 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803102508/https://www.spiegel.de/international/world/spiegel-interview-with-wikileaks-head-julian-assange-a-1044399.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The ''wikileaks.org'' [[domain name]] was registered on 4 October 2006.<ref name="yahoo041021" /> The website was established and published its first document in December 2006.<ref name="TIME">{{cite news |title=WikiLeaks' War on Secrecy: Truth's Consequences |date=2 December 2010 |last=Calabresi |first=Massimo |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2034276-3,00.html |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|quote=Reportedly spurred by the leak of the Pentagon papers, Assange unveiled WikiLeaks in December 2006. |access-date=19 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520104123/http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0%2C8599%2C2034276-3%2C00.html |archive-date=20 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="Khatchdourian">{{cite news|last1=Khatchadourian|first1=Raffi|title=No Secrets|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2010/06/07/no-secrets|access-date=23 August 2025|work=The New Yorker|date=7 June 2010|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722005319/http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2010/06/07/100607fa_fact_khatchadourian?currentPage=all|archive-date=22 July 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> It described its founders as a mixture of Asian dissidents, journalists, mathematicians, and start-up company technologists from the [[United States]], [[Taiwan]], [[Europe]], [[Australia]], and [[South Africa]].<ref name="aboutwikileaks">{{cite web |date=28 February 2012 |title=About WikiLeaks |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/wiki/WikiLeaks:About |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410065353/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/WikiLeaks%3AAbout/ |archive-date=10 April 2014 |access-date=5 December 2012 |publisher=WikiLeaks}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref><ref name="Schmidt-2007" /> In January 2007 WikiLeaks organiser James Chen<ref>{{Cite news |date=6 February 2007 |title=Whistle blown on Wiki site for whistle-blowers |language=en |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-internet-wikileaks-idUSL3145651420070206 |access-date=21 March 2023 |archive-date=21 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230321222400/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-internet-wikileaks-idUSL3145651420070206 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Wikileaks to serve as online Deep Throat - UPI.com |url=https://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2007/01/15/Wikileaks-to-serve-as-online-Deep-Throat/67551168897384/ |access-date=21 March 2023 |publisher=UPI |language=en |archive-date=13 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211013142614/https://www.upi.com/Odd_News/2007/01/15/Wikileaks-to-serve-as-online-Deep-Throat/67551168897384/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Williamson |first=Elizabeth |date=15 January 2007 |title=Freedom of Information, the Wiki Way |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |language=en-US |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/14/AR2007011400760.html |access-date=21 March 2023 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=30 May 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120530152639/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/14/AR2007011400760.html |url-status=live }}</ref> told [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'']] that "We are serious people working on a serious project... three advisors have been detained by Asian government, one of us for over six years."<ref name="Schmidt-2007">{{Cite magazine |last=Schmidt |first=Tracy Samantha |date=22 January 2007 |title=A Wiki for Whistle-Blowers |language=en-US |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=https://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1581189,00.html |access-date=21 March 2023 |issn=0040-781X |archive-date=21 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230321222400/https://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1581189,00.html |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks said that its "primary interests are oppressive regimes in Asia, the former Soviet bloc, sub-Saharan Africa and the Middle East" but it "also expects to be of assistance to those in the West who wish to reveal unethical behaviour in their own governments and corporations".<ref name="The Sydney Morning Herald-2007">{{Cite web |date=11 January 2007 |title=Chinese cyber-dissidents launch WikiLeaks, a site for whistleblowers |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/chinese-cyber-dissidents-launch-wikileaks-a-site-for-whistleblowers-20070111-gdp7x1.html |access-date=2 July 2023 |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |archive-date=2 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702151200/https://www.smh.com.au/national/chinese-cyber-dissidents-launch-wikileaks-a-site-for-whistleblowers-20070111-gdp7x1.html |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks was usually represented in public by Julian Assange, who has described himself as "the heart and soul of this organisation".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/world/24assange.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |title=WikiLeaks Founder on the Run, Trailed by Notoriety |date=23 October 2010 |last1=Burns |first1=John F. |last2=Somaiya |first2=Ravi |access-date=19 December 2010 |archive-date=23 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190523070331/https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/world/24assange.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/rudd-government-blacklist-hacker-monitors-police/story-e6frg8yx-1225718288350 |title=Rudd Government blacklist hacker monitors police |work=The Australian |place=Sydney |last=Guilliatt |first=Richard |date=30 May 2009 |access-date=17 June 2010 |archive-date=27 May 2012 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120527015312/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/defence/rudd-government-blacklist-hacker-monitors-police/story-e6frg8yx-1225718288350 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Advisory board ====
Assange formed an informal advisory board in the early days of WikiLeaks, with journalists, political activists and computer specialists as members.<ref name="WiredUK-1357">{{Cite magazine |title=Exposed: Wikileaks' secrets |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/exposed-wikileaks-secrets |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] UK |language=en-GB |issn=1357-0978 |access-date=13 March 2022 |archive-date=29 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429142257/http://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2009/10/start/exposed-wikileaks-secrets |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2007 WikiLeaks said the board was still forming but that it included representatives from expatriate Russian and Tibetan refugee communities, reporters, a former US intelligence analyst and cryptographers."<ref name="The Sydney Morning Herald-2007" /> Members of the advisory board included [[Phillip Adams (writer)|Phillip Adams]], Julian Assange, [[Wang Dan (dissident)|Wang Dan]], [[Suelette Dreyfus]], CJ Hinke, Tashi Namgyal Khamsitsang, [[Ben Laurie]], [[Xiao Qiang]], [[Chico Whitaker]], [[Wang Youcai]], and [[Cryptome#John Young|John Young]].<ref name="WiredUK-1357" /><ref name="Wikileaks-2007a">{{Cite web |date=22 November 2007 |title=Wikileaks:Advisory Board – Wikileaks |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Advisory_Board |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071122093707/http://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks:Advisory_Board |archive-date=22 November 2007 |access-date=13 February 2023}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref>

WikiLeaks' advisory board did not meet. According to ''[[Wired UK]]'', most of the board members to whom they spoke said they had little involvement with WikiLeaks.<ref name="WiredUK-1357" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Adams |first=Phillip |author-link=Phillip Adams (writer) |date=8 September 2023 |title=I fear for my dear friend, Julian Assange |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/weekend-australian-magazine/i-fear-for-my-dear-friend-julian-assange/news-story/9ad8840204b1f05ad592875363dc4cb4 |website=[[The Australian]]}}</ref> Some said they did not know they were mentioned on the site, nor how they got there.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kushner |first=David |title=Inside WikiLeaks' Leak Factory |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/04/wikileaks-julian-assange-iraq-video/ |access-date=19 October 2022 |website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |language=en-US |archive-date=2 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170502071058/http://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/04/wikileaks-julian-assange-iraq-video?page=3 |url-status=live }}</ref> Computer security expert Ben Laurie said he had been a member of the board "since before the beginning", but he was not "really sure what the advisory board means."<ref name="WiredUK-1357" /> Former board member Phillip Adams criticised the board, saying that Assange "has never asked for advice. The advisory board was pretty clearly window dressing, so he went for people identified with progressive policies around the place."<ref name="theaustralian2010">{{Cite web |date=8 December 2010 |title=Advisory board 'window-dressing' |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/wikileaks-advisory-board-pretty-clearly-window-dressing/news-story/4a4f5c7bc8c50389cd131d92de99ed01 |access-date=19 October 2022 |website=[[The Australian]] |language=en |archive-date=20 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221020002339/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/wikileaks-advisory-board-pretty-clearly-window-dressing/news-story/4a4f5c7bc8c50389cd131d92de99ed01 |url-status=live }}</ref> Assange responded by calling the advisory board "pretty informal".<ref name="theaustralian2010" />

When asked to join their initial advisory board, the promininent critic of secrecy [[Steven Aftergood]] declined; he said to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' that "they have a very idealistic view of the nature of leaking and its impact. They seem to think that most leakers are crusading do-gooders who are single-handedly battling one evil empire or another."<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Tracy Samantha |date=22 January 2007 |title=A Wiki for Whistle-Blowers |newspaper=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1581189,00.html |access-date=13 April 2016 |issn=0040-781X |archive-date=8 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408164618/http://content.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1581189,00.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Early years ===
In January 2007 John Young was dropped from the WikiLeaks network after questioning plans for a multimillion-dollar fundraising goal.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Older, quieter than WikiLeaks, Cryptome perseveres |url=https://apnews.com/article/9972d0583f424d5b8b2f921d5abc8ef5 |access-date=19 March 2023 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=9 March 2013 |language=en |archive-date=19 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319210023/https://apnews.com/article/9972d0583f424d5b8b2f921d5abc8ef5 |url-status=live }}</ref> He accused the organisation of being a CIA conduit and published 150 pages of WikiLeaks emails.<ref name="WiredUK-1357" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Wikileaks: How the organization functions and operates |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/wikileaks-how-the-organization-functions-and-operates/ |access-date=19 March 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en |archive-date=19 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319210020/https://www.zdnet.com/article/wikileaks-how-the-organization-functions-and-operates/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Wikileaks' estranged co-founder becomes a critic (Q&A) |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/privacy/wikileaks-estranged-co-founder-becomes-a-critic-q-a/ |access-date=19 March 2023 |website=CNET |language=en |archive-date=19 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319210020/https://www.cnet.com/news/privacy/wikileaks-estranged-co-founder-becomes-a-critic-q-a/ |url-status=live }}</ref> According to ''Wired'', the emails document the group's attempts to create a profile for themselves and arguments over how to do so. They also discuss political impact and positive reform and include calls for transparency around the world.<ref name="WiredUK-1357" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Wikileaks Leak |url=https://cryptome.org/wikileaks/wikileaks-leak.htm |access-date=19 March 2023 |website=cryptome.org |archive-date=19 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319210028/https://cryptome.org/wikileaks/wikileaks-leak.htm |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2010 WikiLeaks shut down its website while management appealed for donations.<ref name="digdeep">{{cite news |last=Butselaar |first=Emily |date=29 January 2010 |title=Dig deep for WikiLeaks |work=[[The Guardian]] |place=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/libertycentral/2010/jan/29/wikileaks-shut-down |url-status=live |access-date=30 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827012108/http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/libertycentral/2010/jan/29/wikileaks-shut-down |archive-date=27 August 2011}}</ref> Previously published material was no longer available, although some could still be accessed on unofficial [[mirror website]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=WikiLeaks&nbsp;– Mirrors |url=http://wikileaks.ch/Mirrors.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101207060201/http://www.wikileaks.ch/mirrors.html |archive-date=7 December 2010 |access-date=18 December 2010 |publisher=WikiLeaks}}</ref> WikiLeaks stated that it would resume full operation once the operational costs were paid.<ref name="digdeep" /> WikiLeaks said the work stoppage was "to ensure that everyone who is involved stops normal work and actually spends time raising revenue".<ref name="leakonomy" /> The organisation planned for funds to be secured by 6 January 2010, and on 3 February that WikiLeaks announced that its fundraising goal had been achieved.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Facchinetti |first=Roberta |title="Transparency" from Pentagon Papers to Wikileaks: a linguistic revolution |url=https://termcoord.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/MA-thesis-Transparency.pdf |access-date=13 May 2021 |archive-date=13 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210513231207/https://termcoord.eu/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/MA-thesis-Transparency.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

In February 2010 WikiLeaks helped propose the [[Icelandic Modern Media Initiative]] legislation to establish a "journalism safe haven" in [[Iceland]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=12 February 2010 |title=Iceland to be 'journalism haven' |language=en-GB |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/8504972.stm |access-date=16 April 2023 |archive-date=13 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713050832/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/8504972.stm |url-status=live }}</ref> In June, the parliament voted unanimously for the resolution.<ref>{{Cite news |date=12 November 2010 |title=WikiLeaks registers company in Iceland |language=en-AU |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-11-13/wikileaks-registers-company-in-iceland/2335098 |access-date=16 April 2023 |archive-date=29 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129040916/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-11-13/wikileaks-registers-company-in-iceland/2335098 |url-status=live }}</ref>

WikiLeaks originally used a [[wiki]] format website, and was changed when it relaunched in May 2010. The blogger [[Ryan Singel]] claimed that after the website relaunched, its cryptographic security had degraded.<ref name="wikigone" /><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Singel |first=Ryan |date=30 June 2010 |title=With World Watching, Wikileaks Falls Into Disrepair {{!}} WIRED |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/06/wikileaks-submission/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225122212/https://www.wired.com/2010/06/wikileaks-submission/ |archive-date=25 December 2014 |access-date=24 October 2023 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref>

In October 2010 the server WikiLeaks used to host its encrypted communications was compromised by hackers that a WikiLeaks spokesperson described as "very skilled". The spokesperson said that "the server got attacked, hacked, and the private keys got out"; they said it was the first breach in WikiLeaks' history.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=Wikileaks Hacked By "Very Skilled" Attackers Prior To Iraq Doc Release |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2010/10/22/wikileaks-hacked-by-very-skilled-attackers/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131346/https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2010/10/22/wikileaks-hacked-by-very-skilled-attackers/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In November 2010, WikiLeaks said that its website was compromised hours before releasing [[United States diplomatic cables leak|US diplomatic cables]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks 'hacked' before release |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2010/11/28/wikileaks-hacked-before-release |access-date=29 January 2024 |publisher=Al Jazeera English |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131346/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2010/11/28/wikileaks-hacked-before-release |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=30 November 2010 |title=WikiLeaks says its been hacked, crashed pages include U.S. diplomatic cables |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/blogs/technology-blog/story/2010-11-30/wikileaks-says-its-been-hacked-crashed-pages-include-u-s-diplomatic-cables |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131347/https://www.latimes.com/archives/blogs/technology-blog/story/2010-11-30/wikileaks-says-its-been-hacked-crashed-pages-include-u-s-diplomatic-cables |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=28 November 2010 |title=Wikileaks 'hacked ahead of secret US document release' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-11858637 |access-date=29 January 2024 |work=BBC News |language=en-GB |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131346/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-11858637 |url-status=live }}</ref> In December 2010 Spamhaus reported issued a malware warning for "WikiLeaks.info", a "very loosely" affiliated website that "WikiLeaks.org" redirected to. The website said they could "guarantee that there is no malware on it".<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks.info rebuts malware warnings |url=https://www.cnet.com/culture/wikileaks-info-rebuts-malware-warnings/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=CNET |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131346/https://www.cnet.com/culture/wikileaks-info-rebuts-malware-warnings/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Leyden |first=John |title=WikiLeaks mirror site rails against malware warning |url=https://www.theregister.com/2010/12/16/wikileaks_mirror_malware_warning_row/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=The Register |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131346/https://www.theregister.com/2010/12/16/wikileaks_mirror_malware_warning_row/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Wikileaks Mirror Malware Warning |url=https://www.spamhaus.org/news/article/665 |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=spamhaus.org |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131350/https://www.spamhaus.org/news/article/665 |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== 2010 internal dissent ===

A series of resignations of key members of WikiLeaks began in September 2010, started by Assange's decision to release the [[Iraq War logs]] the next month, internal conflicts with other members and his response to sexual assault allegations.<ref>{{Cite web |title="A new WikiLeaks" revolts against Assange – DN.se |work=Dagens Nyheter |date=9 December 2010 |url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/a-new-wikileaks-revolts-against-assange/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101211004535/http://dn.se/nyheter/varlden/a-new-wikileaks-revolts-against-assange-1.1224764 |url-status=live |archive-date=11 December 2010 |access-date=7 February 2023 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hosenball |first=Mark |date=26 August 2010 |title=Is WikiLeaks Too Full of Itself? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/wikileaks-too-full-itself-217216 |access-date=7 February 2023 |website=[[Newsweek]] |language=en |archive-date=7 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207053247/https://www.newsweek.com/wikileaks-too-full-itself-217216 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Moses |first=Asher |date=10 December 2010 |title=Anger at 'slave trader' Assange: WikiLeaks loyalists decide to break away |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/anger-at-slave-trader-assange-wikileaks-loyalists-decide-to-break-away-20101210-18s0w.html |access-date=7 February 2023 |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |archive-date=7 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207235452/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/anger-at-slave-trader-assange-wikileaks-loyalists-decide-to-break-away-20101210-18s0w.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="wikileaksrevolt" /> According to Herbert Snorrason, "We found out that the level of redactions performed on the Afghanistan documents was not sufficient. I announced that if the next batch did not receive full attention, I would not be willing to cooperate."<ref name="wikileaksrevolt" /> Some members of WikiLeaks called for Assange to step aside.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Crampton |first=Caroline |date=6 September 2010 |title=WikiLeaks turns on Julian Assange |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/2010/09/wikileaks-assange-organisation |access-date=21 January 2024 |website=New Statesman |language=en-US |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529044953/https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/2010/09/wikileaks-assange-organisation |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 25 September 2010 after being suspended by Assange for "disloyalty, insubordination and destabilisation", [[Daniel Domscheit-Berg]], the German spokesman for WikiLeaks, told ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' that he was resigning. He said "WikiLeaks has a structural problem. I no longer want to take responsibility for it, and that's why I am leaving the project."<ref name="spiegel20100927">{{cite news |date=27 September 2010 |title=WikiLeaks Spokesman Quits |work=Spiegel International |place=Hamburg |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,719619,00.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130022133/http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0%2C1518%2C719619%2C00.html |archive-date=30 November 2010}}</ref><ref name="wikileaksrevolt">{{cite news |author=Poulsen, Kevin |author2=Zetter, Kim |date=27 September 2010 |title=Unpublished Iraq War Logs Trigger Internal WikiLeaks Revolt |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |place=New York |url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/09/wikileaks-revolt/ |url-status=live |access-date=14 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020030321/http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/09/wikileaks-revolt |archive-date=20 October 2013}}</ref> Assange accused Domscheit-Berg of leaking information to ''[[Newsweek]]'', with Domscheit-Berg saying that the WikiLeaks team was unhappy with Assange's management and handling of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|Afghan war]] document releases.<ref name="wikileaksrevolt" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hosenball |first=Mark |date=26 August 2010 |title=Is WikiLeaks Too Full of Itself? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/wikileaks-too-full-itself-217216 |access-date=6 February 2023 |website=[[Newsweek]] |language=en |archive-date=6 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230206140307/https://www.newsweek.com/wikileaks-too-full-itself-217216 |url-status=live }}</ref> Domscheit-Berg said he wanted greater transparency in WikiLeaks finances and the leaks released to the public.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jon |first=Stephenson |date=29 March 2011 |title=Interview with Daniel Domscheidt-Berg of Open Leaks |url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/HL1103/S00288/interview-with-daniel-domscheidt-berg-of-open-leaks.htm |access-date=25 March 2015 |website=Scoop Independent News |archive-date=2 April 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402144636/http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/HL1103/S00288/interview-with-daniel-domscheidt-berg-of-open-leaks.htm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Rosen |first=Jeffrey |date=15 April 2011 |title=Daniel Domscheit-Berg's "Inside WikiLeaks" |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/daniel_domscheit_bergs_inside_wikileaks/2011/03/25/AFdc37jD_story.html |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621104755/https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/daniel_domscheit_bergs_inside_wikileaks/2011/03/25/AFdc37jD_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Zetter">{{Cite magazine |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=WikiLeaks Defector Slams Assange In Tell-All Book |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/02/wikileaks-book/ |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=1059-1028 |archive-date=13 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713050502/https://www.wired.com/2011/02/wikileaks-book/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

According to various sources, Domscheit-Berg had copied and then deleted over 3,500 unpublished whistleblower communications. Some communications<ref>{{cite news |date=12 February 2011 |title=WikiLeaks defector blasts Assange in book – CNN |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/02/10/germany.openleaks.wikileaks/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022023545/http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/02/10/germany.openleaks.wikileaks/index.html |archive-date=22 October 2013}}. Edition.cnn.com. Retrieved 22 November 2011.</ref> contained hundreds of documents,<ref name="Spiegel-chs-2011">{{Cite news |date=13 August 2011 |title=Chaos Computer Club: Hacker distanzieren sich von OpenLeaks |language=de |work=Der Spiegel |url=https://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/chaos-computer-club-hacker-distanzieren-sich-von-openleaks-a-780103.html |access-date=26 July 2022 |issn=2195-1349 |archive-date=6 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230206140313/https://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/chaos-computer-club-hacker-distanzieren-sich-von-openleaks-a-780103.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Spiegel-cis-2011">{{Cite news |date=21 August 2011 |title=Streit mit Assange: Ex-Sprecher vernichtete WikiLeaks-Dateien |language=de |work=Der Spiegel |url=https://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/streit-mit-assange-ex-sprecher-vernichtete-wikileaks-dateien-a-781458.html |access-date=26 July 2022 |issn=2195-1349 |archive-date=26 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220726070624/https://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/streit-mit-assange-ex-sprecher-vernichtete-wikileaks-dateien-a-781458.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="firedoglakeAug2011">{{cite news |last=Gosztola |first=Kevin |author-link=Kevin Gosztola |date=21 August 2011 |title=OpenLeaks Founder Destroys Cache of Unreleased WikiLeaks Documents |website=Dissenter.firedoglake.com |url=http://dissenter.firedoglake.com/2011/08/21/openleaks-founder-destroys-cache-of-unreleased-wikileaks-documents/ |access-date=17 July 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111202063844/http://dissenter.firedoglake.com/2011/08/21/openleaks-founder-destroys-cache-of-unreleased-wikileaks-documents/ |archive-date=2 December 2011}}</ref> including the US government's [[No Fly List]],<ref name="wlcentral">{{cite news |last=Marsh |first=Heather |date=21 August 2011 |title=Former WikiLeaks spokesman destroyed unreleased files |website=Wlcentral.org |url=http://wlcentral.org/node/2172 |access-date=18 January 2017 |archive-date=25 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325200001/http://wlcentral.org/node/2172 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Bank of America]] leaks,<ref name="twitterboa">{{cite web |date=21 August 2011 |title=We can confirm that the DDB |url=https://twitter.com/wikileaks/statuses/105244480457801728 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |access-date=6 February 2023 |archive-date=21 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921061625/https://twitter.com/wikileaks/statuses/105244480457801728 |url-status=live }}</ref> insider information from 20 neo-Nazi organisations,<ref name="wlcentral" /><ref name="twitterneo">{{cite web |date=21 August 2011 |title=We can confirm that the DDB ... |url=https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/105245148065181698 |publisher=[[Twitter]] |access-date=6 February 2023 |archive-date=1 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201103117/https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/105245148065181698 |url-status=live }}</ref> documents sent by [[Renata Ávila Pinto|Renata Avila]] about torture and government abuse of a Latin American country<ref name="martes">{{cite web |last=Renata |first=Avila |date=15 August 2011 |title=Open Letter |url=http://nothingispermanent.blogspot.com.au/2011/08/open-letter.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201071005/http://nothingispermanent.blogspot.com.au/2011/08/open-letter.html |archive-date=1 February 2016 |access-date=28 September 2012 |website=Nothingispermanent.blogspot.com.au}}</ref> and US intercept information for "over a hundred Internet companies".<ref name="BBC_14616899">{{cite news |date=22 August 2011 |title=Ex-Wikileaks man 'deleted files' |work=[[BBC News]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-14616899 |url-status=live |access-date=3 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020210919/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-14616899 |archive-date=20 October 2013}}</ref> Assange stated that Domscheit-Berg had deleted video files of the [[Granai airstrike|Granai massacre]] by a US Bomber. WikiLeaks had scheduled the video for publication before its deletion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dorling |first1=Philip |date=5 March 2013 |title=WikiLeaks has more US secrets, Assange says |language=en |work=The Age |url=https://www.theage.com.au/national/wikileaks-has-more-us-secrets-assange-says-20130305-2fihd.html |access-date=16 June 2021 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529044953/https://www.theage.com.au/national/wikileaks-has-more-us-secrets-assange-says-20130305-2fihd.html |url-status=live }}</ref> According to [[Andy Müller-Maguhn]], it was an eighteen-gigabyte collection.<ref name="Greenberg-2013">{{Cite book |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=This machine kills secrets: Julian Assange, the cypherpunks, and their fight to empower whistleblowers |title-link=This Machine Kills Secrets |date=2013 |publisher=Plume book |isbn=978-0-14-218049-5 |location=New York, [New York]}}</ref>

Domscheit-Berg said he took the files from WikiLeaks because he did not trust its security. In Domscheit-Berg's book he wrote he was "waiting for Julian to restore security, so that we can return the material to him".<ref name="Zetter-2011">{{cite news |last=Zetter |first=Kim |date=10 February 2011 |title=WikiLeaks Defector Slams Assange in Tell-All Book Threat Level |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2011/02/wikileaks-book/all/1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209220641/http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2011/02/wikileaks-book/all/1 |archive-date=9 February 2014}}. Wired.com (10 February 2011). Retrieved 22 November 2011.</ref><ref name="Greenberg-2023">{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=Ex-WikiLeaker Claims Defectors Took Control Of Leaks From Assange |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/02/09/ex-wikileaker-claims-defectors-took-control-of-leaks-from-assange/ |access-date=6 February 2023 |website=[[Forbes]] |language=en |archive-date=6 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230206170848/https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/02/09/ex-wikileaker-claims-defectors-took-control-of-leaks-from-assange/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Rosenbloom |first=Joseph |title=Blowing the whistle on Assange |work=Boston.com |url=https://archive.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2011/02/19/a_former_wikileaks_aide_blows_the_whistle_on_assange/ |access-date=7 February 2023 |archive-date=7 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207182825/https://archive.boston.com/ae/books/articles/2011/02/19/a_former_wikileaks_aide_blows_the_whistle_on_assange/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Architect and Domscheit-Berg encrypted the files and gave them to a third party who did not have the key.<ref name="Greenberg-2013" /> In August 2011 Domscheit-Berg said he permanently deleted the files "to ensure that the sources are not compromised."<ref>{{cite news |date=22 August 2011 |title=Assange Battle Escalates: Ex-Wikileaks Spokesman Destroyed Unpublished Files – SPIEGEL ONLINE – News – International |newspaper=Der Spiegel |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,781581,00.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110830185102/http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0%2C1518%2C781581%2C00.html |archive-date=30 August 2011}}. Spiegel.de. Retrieved 22 November 2011.</ref> He said that WikiLeaks' claims about the Bank of America files were "false and misleading"<ref name="Moughty-2022">{{Cite web |title=Ex-WikiLeaks Spokesman Destroyed Thousands of Unpublished Docs |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/frontline/article/ex-wikileaks-spokesman-said-to-have-destroyed-thousands-of-unpublished-docs/ |access-date=26 July 2022 |website=Frontline |language=en-US |archive-date=24 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924161027/http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/foreign-affairs-defense/wikisecrets/ex-wikileaks-spokesman-said-to-have-destroyed-thousands-of-unpublished-docs/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and they were lost because of an IT problem.<ref name="Spiegel-chs-2011" />

The Architect left with Domscheit-Berg, taking the code<ref name="Bustillos-2023">{{Cite web |title=Here Comes OpenLeaks: How It Won't Be WikiLeaks |url=https://www.theawl.com/2012/05/here-comes-openleaks-how-it-wont-be-wikileaks/ |access-date=6 February 2023 |website=The Awl |language=en |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045455/https://www.theawl.com/2012/05/here-comes-openleaks-how-it-wont-be-wikileaks/ |url-status=live }}</ref> behind the submission system with him.<ref name="Fowler-2011">{{Cite web |date=3 October 2011 |title=Wikileaks site in limbo without architect – ABC Radio |url=https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/am/wikileaks-site-in-limbo-without-architect/3208034 |access-date=6 February 2023 |website=AM – ABC Radio |language=en-AU |archive-date=6 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230206165916/https://www.abc.net.au/radio/programs/am/wikileaks-site-in-limbo-without-architect/3208034 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Zetter-2011" /><ref name="Greenberg-2023" /> WikiLeaks submissions stayed offline until 2015.<ref name="Greenberg-2015">{{Cite magazine |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Finally Brings Back Its Submission System for Your Secrets |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/05/wikileaks-finally-brings-back-submission-system-secrets/ |access-date=7 February 2023 |issn=1059-1028 |archive-date=11 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230211180513/https://www.wired.com/2015/05/wikileaks-finally-brings-back-submission-system-secrets/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="wikileaks-2015">{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – Some notes on the new WikiLeaks next-generation submission system beta |url=https://wikileaks.org/Some-notes-on-the-new-WikiLeaks.html |access-date=7 February 2023 |website=Wikileaks |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045455/https://wikileaks.org/Some-notes-on-the-new-WikiLeaks.html |url-status=live }}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref> Herbert Snorrason resigned after he challenged Assange on his decision to suspend Domscheit-Berg and was bluntly rebuked.<ref name="wikileaksrevolt" /> Iceland MP [[Birgitta Jónsdóttir]] also left WikiLeaks, citing lack of transparency, lack of structure, and poor communication flow.<ref name="McMahon-2011">{{cite news |author=McMahon, Tamsin |date=17 January 2011 |title=Q&A: Former WikiLeaks spokeswoman Birgitta Jonsdottir |work=National Post |place=Toronto |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/qa-former-wikileaks-spokeswoman-birgitta-jonsdottir |url-status=live |access-date=14 February 2011 |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20110220142821/http://news.nationalpost.com/2011/01/15/qa-former-wikileaks-spokeswoman-birgitta-jonsdottir/ |archive-date=20 February 2011}}</ref> [[James Ball (journalist)|James Ball]] left WikiLeaks over disputes about Assange's handling of finances, and Assange's relationship to [[Israel Shamir]], an individual who has promoted antisemitism and holocaust denial.<ref name="Ball-2011">{{Cite news |last=Ball |first=James |date=2 September 2011 |title=Why I felt I had to turn my back on WikiLeaks |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/02/why-i-had-to-leave-wikileaks |access-date=19 March 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=20 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720181719/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/02/why-i-had-to-leave-wikileaks |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Ball |first=James |date=8 November 2011 |title=Israel Shamir and Julian Assange's cult of machismo |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2011/nov/08/israel-shamir-julian-assange-cult-machismo |access-date=19 March 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=25 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210225143328/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2011/nov/08/israel-shamir-julian-assange-cult-machismo |url-status=live }}</ref> According to the British newspaper, ''[[The Independent]]'', at least a dozen key supporters of WikiLeaks left the website during 2010.<ref name="TaylorJ-2010">{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Jerome |date=25 October 2010 |title=Secret war at the heart of Wikileaks |work=[[The Independent]] |place=London |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/online/secret-war-at-the-heart-of-wikileaks-2115637.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140312085337/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/online/secret-war-at-the-heart-of-wikileaks-2115637.html |archive-date=12 March 2014}}</ref> Several staffers who broke with Assange joined with Domscheit-Berg to start [[OpenLeaks]],<ref name="Bustillos-2022">{{Cite web |title=Daniel Domscheit-Berg And WikiLeaks' Insecure Future |url=https://www.theawl.com/2011/05/daniel-domscheit-berg-and-wikileaks-insecure-future/ |access-date=26 July 2022 |website=The Awl |language=en |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045457/https://www.theawl.com/2011/05/daniel-domscheit-berg-and-wikileaks-insecure-future/ |url-status=live }}</ref> a new leak organisation and website with a different management and distribution philosophy.<ref name="spiegel20100927" /><ref>{{cite news |last=Nordstrom |first=Louise |date=10 December 2010 |title=Former WikiLeaks worker: Rival site under way |work=[[The Washington Times]] |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/dec/10/former-wikileaks-worker-rival-site-under-way/ |url-status=live |access-date=13 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025045922/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/dec/10/former-wikileaks-worker-rival-site-under-way/ |archive-date=25 October 2013}}</ref>

[[Sarah Harrison (journalist)|Sarah Harrison]], who stayed with WikiLeaks, later told [[Andrew O'Hagan]] she did not agree with the way he did it, but Domscheit-Berg had a basic point. She added that "you can tell he was probably just trying to say something true and got hated for it. That's the way it is with Julian: he can't listen. He doesn't get it."<ref name="O'Hagan-2014">{{Cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Andrew |date=6 March 2014 |title=Ghosting |language=en |volume=36 |work=London Review of Books |issue=5 |url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v36/n05/andrew-o-hagan/ghosting |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0260-9592 |archive-date=13 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230513001705/https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v36/n05/andrew-o-hagan/ghosting |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Actions against WikiLeaks ===
{{See also|Surveillance of Julian Assange}}
In early 2010 Assange said that he obtained documents showing that two State Department agents tailed him on a flight from Iceland to Norway. Icelandic journalists were unable to verify Assange's allegations, which were denied by the State Department. Assange did not release the alleged documents.<ref name="Columbia Journalism Review-2" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Gilson |first=Dave |title=The MoJo vs. WikiLeaks Smackdown Continues |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/04/mojo-wikileaks-assange-smackdown/ |access-date=23 October 2023 |website=Mother Jones |language=en-US |archive-date=1 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231101041152/https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/04/mojo-wikileaks-assange-smackdown/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011a" /><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011b">{{Cite web |last=Domscheit-Berg |first=Daniel |date=10 February 2011 |title=Julian Assange: Chief Marketing Officer of WikiLeaks |url=https://gizmodo.com/julian-assange-chief-marketing-officer-of-wikileaks-5756379 |access-date=1 November 2023 |website=Gizmodo |language=en |archive-date=1 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231101055542/https://gizmodo.com/julian-assange-chief-marketing-officer-of-wikileaks-5756379 |url-status=live }}</ref> Assange also said that a volunteer was arrested in March and questioned about WikiLeaks. According to Assange, police said that authorities had spied on and photographed a private WikiLeaks meeting. WikiLeaks later admitted that the interrogation did not happen as originally suggested. According to the deputy head of news for [[RÚV|RUV]], the arrest was unrelated to WikiLeaks but the volunteer mentioned WikiLeaks to the police and said the laptop he had with him was owned by WikiLeaks.<ref name="Columbia Journalism Review-2" /> [[Daniel Domscheit-Berg]] wrote that<blockquote>The rumors that he was being followed originated in part from his overactive imagination. But they also had the advantage of giving him the aura of someone in dire peril, increasing the collective anticipation of every new leak. Julian didn't need a marketing department. Marketing was something he himself knew best.<ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011a" /><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011b" /></blockquote>After [[Julian Assange]] was granted [[Right of asylum|asylum]] and entered the [[Ecuadorian embassy in London]] in 2012, new [[CCTV]] cameras were installed and security personnel working for UC Global and Promsecurity recorded his activities and interactions, including with his legal team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Collyns |first1=Dan |last2=Kirchgaessner |first2=Stephanie |last3=Harding |first3=Luke |date=15 May 2018 |title=Revealed: Ecuador spent millions on spy operation for Julian Assange |newspaper=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/15/revealed-ecuador-spent-millions-julian-assange-spy-operation-embassy-london |access-date=15 May 2018 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045456/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/may/15/revealed-ecuador-spent-millions-julian-assange-spy-operation-embassy-london |url-status=live }}</ref> In a 2017 email, the [[surveillance]] was justified with suspicions that Assange was "working for the [[Russian Intelligence Service|Russian intelligence services]]."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Irujo |first=José María |date=8 November 2019 |title=The US trail of the man whose security firm spied on Julian Assange |url=https://english.elpais.com/elpais/2019/11/08/inenglish/1573211318_746915.html |access-date=28 November 2022 |website=El País English Edition |language=en-us |archive-date=27 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221127233737/https://english.elpais.com/elpais/2019/11/08/inenglish/1573211318_746915.html |url-status=live }}</ref> New cameras and microphones were installed in December 2017, and Morales arranged for the United States to have immediate access to the recordings.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Irujo |first=José María |date=26 September 2019 |title=Spanish security company spied on Julian Assange in London for the United States |url=https://english.elpais.com/elpais/2019/09/25/inenglish/1569384196_652151.html |access-date=17 December 2022 |website=El País English Edition |language=en-us |archive-date=4 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210304042654/https://english.elpais.com/elpais/2019/09/25/inenglish/1569384196_652151.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Campaigns to discredit WikiLeaks ====
{{See also|Reception of WikiLeaks#Response from corporations|l1=Response from corporations}}
Writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'' in 2010, [[Nick Davies]] said there was "some evidence of low-level attempts to smear Wikileaks", including false online accusations involving Assange and money.<ref name="guardian250710">{{Cite news |last=Davies |first=Nick |author-link=Nick Davies |date=25 July 2010 |title=Afghanistan war logs: Story behind biggest leak in intelligence history |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/25/wikileaks-war-logs-back-story |issn=0261-3077 |access-date=26 July 2023 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045457/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/25/wikileaks-war-logs-back-story |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2010, Wikileaks published a 2008 US military report that said leaks to WikiLeaks "could result in increased threats to DoD personnel, equipment, facilities, or installations". The report suggested a plan to identify and expose WikiLeaks' sources to "deter others from using WikiLeaks" and "destroy the center of gravity" of Wikileaks by attacking its trustworthiness.<ref name="guardian250710"/><ref>{{Cite web |date=19 March 2010 |title=WikiLeaks website 'threatens US troops' |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/wikileaks-website-threatens-us-troops-20100320-qmjn.html |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en |access-date=26 July 2023 |archive-date=26 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230726094504/https://www.smh.com.au/world/wikileaks-website-threatens-us-troops-20100320-qmjn.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Chacksfield |first=Marc |date=15 March 2010 |title=WikiLeaks leaks US Government's WikiLeaks plans |url=https://www.techradar.com/news/internet/wikileaks-leaks-us-government-s-wikileaks-plans-676874 |access-date=23 September 2022 |website=TechRadar |language=en |archive-date=23 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220923004208/https://www.techradar.com/news/internet/wikileaks-leaks-us-government-s-wikileaks-plans-676874 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Clint Hendler writing in the ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'', many reactions to the document were "overwrought" and "the spin" by WikiLeaks was "a step too far".<ref name="Columbia Journalism Review-2">{{Cite web |title=Thin Ice |url=https://www.cjr.org/behind_the_news/thin_ice.php |access-date=23 October 2023 |website=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en |archive-date=12 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212024527/https://www.cjr.org/behind_the_news/thin_ice.php |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2010 the [[Bank of America]] employed the services of a collection of [[information security]] firms, known as Team Themis, when the bank became concerned about information that WikiLeaks was planning to release about it. Team Themis included private intelligence and security firms HBGary Federal, [[Palantir Technologies]] and Berico Technologies.<ref name="Greenberg">{{Cite news |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |date=11 February 2011 |title=Palantir Apologizes For WikiLeaks Attack Proposal, Cuts Ties With HBGary |work=[[Forbes]] |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/02/11/palantir-apologizes-for-wikileaks-attack-proposal-cuts-ties-with-hbgary/ |access-date=20 October 2016 |archive-date=22 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922204013/http://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/02/11/palantir-apologizes-for-wikileaks-attack-proposal-cuts-ties-with-hbgary/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="wired140211">{{cite magazine |last1=Anderson |first1=Nate |date=14 February 2011 |title=Spy Games: Inside the Convoluted Plot to Bring Down WikiLeaks |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/02/spy/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |access-date=26 October 2019 |archive-date=1 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901185139/https://www.wired.com/2011/02/spy/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Owen |first=Thomas |date=16 February 2011 |title=Palantir's third black eye: i2 lawsuit settled |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUS121866071120110217 |access-date=20 October 2016 |archive-date=21 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161021070709/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUS121866071120110217 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2011 hacktivist group [[Anonymous (hacker group)|Anonymous]] released emails from [[HBGary|HBGary Federal]] showing that Team Themis proposed a plan which suggested "[spreading] disinformation" and "disrupting" [[Glenn Greenwald]]'s support for WikiLeaks.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Wray |first1=James |last2=Stabe |first2=Ulf |title=Data intelligence firms proposed a systematic attack against WikiLeaks |url=http://www.thetechherald.com/articles/Data-intelligence-firms-proposed-a-systematic-attack-against-WikiLeaks/12751/ |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126010658/http://www.thetechherald.com/articles/Data-intelligence-firms-proposed-a-systematic-attack-against-WikiLeaks/12751/ |archive-date=26 November 2018 |access-date=30 January 2012 |publisher=Thetechherald.com}}</ref> Team Themis planned to expose the workings of WikiLeaks using disinformation and cyberattacks. The plans were not implemented and, after the emails were published, Palantir CEO [[Alex Karp]] issued a public apology to "progressive organizations ... and Greenwald" for his company's role.<ref name="Harris">{{Cite web |last=Harris |first=Shane |date=31 January 2012 |title=Killer App |url=http://www.washingtonian.com/articles/people/killer-app/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201028133450/https://www.washingtonian.com/2012/01/31/killer-app/ |archive-date=28 October 2020 |access-date=14 March 2012 |website=Washingtonian}}</ref><ref name="wired140211" /><ref name="unlock">{{cite news |last=Hardy |first=Quentin |date=31 May 2014 |title=Unlocking Secrets, if Not Its Own Value |website=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/01/business/unlocking-secrets-if-not-its-own-value.html?nytmobile=0 |access-date=20 October 2016 |archive-date=22 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170922050624/https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/01/business/unlocking-secrets-if-not-its-own-value.html?nytmobile=0 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Other ====
{{See also|Reception of WikiLeaks#Response from the financial industry|WikiLeaks#Financial blockade|WikiLeaks#Hosting}}
In December 2010 PayPal suspended the WikiLeaks account after they received a letter from the US State Department that characterised WikiLeaks' activities as illegal in the US.<ref name="bbc0812102">{{cite news |date=8 December 2010 |title=PayPal says it stopped Wikileaks payments on US letter |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-11945875 |access-date=22 June 2021 |archive-date=21 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210621165228/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-11945875 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mastercard]] and [[Visa Inc.#Visa Europe|Visa Europe]] also stopped accepting payments to WikiLeaks after pressure from the US.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Becker |first1=Jo |last2=Erlanger |first2=Steven |last3=Schmitt |first3=Eric |title=How Russia Often Benefits When Julian Assange Reveals the West's Secrets |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/01/world/europe/wikileaks-julian-assange-russia.html |website=The New York Times |access-date=15 March 2024 |date=31 August 2016 |archive-date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726034108/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/01/world/europe/wikileaks-julian-assange-russia.html |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Bank of America]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]] and Swiss bank [[PostFinance]] had previously stopped dealing with WikiLeaks. Datacell, the IT company that enabled WikiLeaks to accept credit and debit card donations, said Visa's action was the result of political pressure.<ref name="bbc0812102"/><ref name="wired0712122">{{cite news |last=Zetter |first=Kim |date=12 July 2012 |title=WikiLeaks Wins Icelandic Court Battle Against Visa for Blocking Donations &#124; Threat Level |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2012/07/wikileaks-visa-blockade/ |url-status=live |access-date=19 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130702005703/http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2012/07/wikileaks-visa-blockade/ |archive-date=2 July 2013}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref> WikiLeaks referred to these actions as a banking blockade.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Banking Blockade |url=https://wikileaks.org/Banking-Blockade |access-date=20 March 2023 |website=wikileaks.org |language=en |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320112940/https://wikileaks.org/Banking-Blockade |url-status=live }}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref> In response to the companies' actions, the hacker group [[Anonymous (hacker group)|Anonymous]] launched a [[Operation Payback#Operation Avenge Assange|series of cyberattacks]] against the companies, and against the [[Law enforcement in Sweden#Swedish Prosecution Authority|Swedish Prosecution Authority]] for its [[Assange v Swedish Prosecution Authority|attempted extradition of Assange]].<ref name="Weaver-2010">{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Matthew |last2=Adams |first2=Richard |date=7 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks US embassy cables: live updates |work=The Guardian |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/blog/2010/dec/07/wikileaks-us-embassy-cables-live-updates |access-date=7 December 2010 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529125644/https://www.theguardian.com/news/blog/2010/dec/07/wikileaks-us-embassy-cables-live-updates |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Addley-2010">{{cite news |last1=Addley |first1=Esther |last2=Halliday |first2=Josh |date=9 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks supporters disrupt Visa and MasterCard sites in 'Operation Payback' |work=guardian.co.uk |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/dec/08/wikileaks-visa-mastercard-operation-payback |access-date=9 December 2010 |archive-date=8 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508002128/http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/dec/08/wikileaks-visa-mastercard-operation-payback |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks spokesman Kristinn Hrafnsson said: <blockquote>[Anonymous] is not affiliated with Wikileaks. There has been no contact between any Wikileaks staffer and anyone at Anonymous. Wikileaks has not received any prior notice of any of Anonymous' actions. We neither condemn nor applaud these attacks. We believe they are a reflection of public opinion on the actions of the targets.<ref>{{cite web |date=2010-12-09 |title=Statement on DDOS attacks |url=https://wikileaks.org/Statement-on-DDOS-attacks.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230810220948/https://wikileaks.org/Statement-on-DDOS-attacks.html |archive-date=August 10, 2023 |access-date=2010-12-09 |publisher=WikiLeaks}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref></blockquote>
Cyber-attacks and legal restrictions forced WikiLeaks to change [[Internet hosting service|server hosts]] several times by 2010.<ref name="amazon2">{{cite news |last=Gross |first=Doug |date=2 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks cut off from Amazon servers |publisher=[[CNN]]|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/US/12/01/wikileaks.amazon/index.html?eref=edition |url-status=live |access-date=2 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029192138/http://edition.cnn.com/2010/US/12/01/wikileaks.amazon/index.html?eref=edition |archive-date=29 October 2013}}</ref><ref name="Hennigan2">{{cite news |last=Hennigan |first=W.J. |date=2 December 2010 |title=Amazon says it dumped WikiLeaks because it put innocent people in jeopardy |work=Technology blog, Los Angeles Times |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2010/12/amazon-wikileaks-servers.html |url-status=live |access-date=23 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001220315/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/technology/2010/12/amazon-wikileaks-servers.html |archive-date=1 October 2013}}</ref><ref name="Ladurantaye">{{cite news |last=Ladurantaye |first=Steve |date=8 December 2010 |title=Canadian firm caught up in Wiki wars |work=The Globe and Mail |place=Toronto |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/technology/canadian-firm-caught-up-in-wiki-wars/article1830732/ |url-status=live |access-date=9 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727052959/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/technology/canadian-firm-caught-up-in-wiki-wars/article1830732/ |archive-date=27 July 2011}}</ref>

=== 2011–2015 ===
In December 2011 WikiLeaks launched ''Friends of WikiLeaks'', a social network for supporters and founders of the website. ''Friends of WikiLeaks'' was designed for users to never have more than 12 friends, half local and half international. The site was in beta status.<ref>{{cite web |date=19 December 2011 |title=Wikileaks launches Social Network |url=http://www.netzwelt.de/news/89988-wikileaks-enthuellungsplattform-gruendet-soziales-netzwerk.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324015155/http://www.netzwelt.de/news/89988-wikileaks-enthuellungsplattform-gruendet-soziales-netzwerk.html |archive-date=24 March 2014 |access-date=24 August 2012 |publisher=Netzwelt.de}}</ref>

In July 2012 WikiLeaks took credit for a fake ''[[New York Times]]'' website and article falsely attributed to [[Bill Keller]].<ref name="Pilkington-2012">{{Cite news |last=Pilkington |first=Ed |date=29 July 2012 |title=WikiLeaks claims responsibility for fake Bill Keller column, citing donation ban |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/29/bill-keller-fake-column-wikileaks |access-date=20 March 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045458/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jul/29/bill-keller-fake-column-wikileaks |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Oremus">{{Cite news |last=Oremus |first=Will |date=30 July 2012 |title=Wikileaks Temporarily Fools Internet With Fake New York Times Op-Ed |language=en-US |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |url=https://slate.com/technology/2012/07/wikileaks-fake-nyt-bill-keller-op-ed-fools-internet-hurts-credibility.html |access-date=20 March 2023 |issn=1091-2339 |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320112941/https://slate.com/technology/2012/07/wikileaks-fake-nyt-bill-keller-op-ed-fools-internet-hurts-credibility.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks says it created fake Bill Keller column – Poynter |date=30 July 2012 |url=https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2012/wikileaks-says-it-created-fake-bill-keller-column/ |access-date=20 March 2023 |language=en-US |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320112949/https://www.poynter.org/reporting-editing/2012/wikileaks-says-it-created-fake-bill-keller-column/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Gross |first=Doug |date=30 July 2012 |title=Fake New York Times op-ed a WikiLeaks hoax {{!}} CNN Business |url=https://www.cnn.com/2012/07/30/tech/web/fake-nyt-editorial/index.html |access-date=20 March 2023 |website=[[CNN]] |language=en |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320112938/https://www.cnn.com/2012/07/30/tech/web/fake-nyt-editorial/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The hoax prompted criticism from commenters and the public, who said it hurt WikiLeaks' credibility. [[Glenn Greenwald]] wrote in ''[[Salon.com|Salon]]'' that it might have been satire but <blockquote>it doesn't strike me as a good idea for a group that relies on its credibility when it comes to the authenticity of what they publish{{snd}} and which thus far has had a stellar record in that regard{{snd}} to be making boastful claims that they published forged documents. I understand and appreciate the satire, but in this case, it directly conflicts with, and undermines, the primary value of WikiLeaks.<ref name="Oremus" /><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Haggin |first=Patience |date=2012-07-30 |title=WikiLeaks Creates Elaborate New York Times Hoax, Fooling Readers |language=en-US |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=https://newsfeed.time.com/2012/07/30/wikileaks-creates-elaborate-new-york-times-hoax-fooling-readers/ |access-date=2023-03-20 |issn=0040-781X |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320112944/https://newsfeed.time.com/2012/07/30/wikileaks-creates-elaborate-new-york-times-hoax-fooling-readers/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |author-link=Glenn Greenwald |date=2012-07-29 |title=The curative powers of the Internet |url=https://www.salon.com/2012/07/29/the_curative_powers_of_the_internet/ |access-date=2023-03-20 |website=[[Salon.com|Salon]] |language=en |archive-date=20 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230320112940/https://www.salon.com/2012/07/29/the_curative_powers_of_the_internet/ |url-status=live }}</ref></blockquote> WikiLeaks said it wanted to bring attention to the banking blockade.<ref name="Pilkington-2012" />

In January 2013, shortly after [[Aaron Swartz]] died, WikiLeaks said that Swartz had helped WikiLeaks and had talked to Julian Assange in 2010 and 2011. WikiLeaks also said it had "strong reasons to believe, but cannot prove", he may have been a source, breaking WikiLeaks' rules about source anonymity. Journalists suggested that Wikileaks may have made the statements to imply that Swartz was targeted by the US Attorney's Office and Secret Service in order to get at WikiLeaks.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Carmody |first=Tim |date=19 January 2013 |title=WikiLeaks claims Aaron Swartz was an ally and possible source, breaking anonymity |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/1/19/3893268/wikileaks-tweets-aaron-swartz-was-ally-and-possibly-source |access-date=11 March 2023 |website=The Verge |language=en-US |archive-date=11 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210411044410/http://www.theverge.com/2013/1/19/3893268/wikileaks-tweets-aaron-swartz-was-ally-and-possibly-source |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks says Aaron Swartz may have been a 'source' |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/privacy/wikileaks-says-aaron-swartz-may-have-been-a-source/ |access-date=11 March 2023 |website=CNET |language=en |archive-date=11 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311180653/https://www.cnet.com/news/privacy/wikileaks-says-aaron-swartz-may-have-been-a-source/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2013 the organisation assisted [[Edward Snowden]] leave Hong Kong. [[Sarah Harrison (journalist)|Sarah Harrison]], a WikiLeaks activist, accompanied Snowden on the flight. According to US investigators, WikiLeaks played an active role in assisting Snowden to disclose a [[2010s global surveillance disclosures|cache of NSA documents]].<ref name=Pe17/> Scott Shane of ''The New York Times'' stated that the involvement "shows that despite its shoestring staff, limited fund-raising from a boycott by major financial firms, and defections prompted by Mr. Assange's personal troubles and abrasive style, it remains a force to be reckoned with on the global stage."<ref>{{cite news |last=Shane |first=Scott |date=23 June 2013 |title=Offering Snowden Aid, WikiLeaks Gets Back in the Game |website=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/24/world/offering-snowden-aid-wikileaks-gets-back-in-the-game.html?ref=asia |access-date=17 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130624143236/https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/24/world/offering-snowden-aid-wikileaks-gets-back-in-the-game.html?ref=asia |archive-date=24 June 2013}}</ref>

In September 2013 Julian Assange announced the creation of the WikiLeaks [[counterintelligence]] unit. The project surveilled 19 surveillance contractors to understand their business dealings. According to Assange, they were "tracking the trackers" to "counter threats against investigative journalism and the public's right to know."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brandom |first=Russell |date=5 September 2013 |title=Julian Assange is tracking the movements of 19 spyware contractors |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/9/4/4695652/julian-assange-is-tracking-the-movements-of-19-spyware-contractors |access-date=25 April 2023 |website=[[The Verge]] |language=en-US |archive-date=25 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425213516/https://www.theverge.com/2013/9/4/4695652/julian-assange-is-tracking-the-movements-of-19-spyware-contractors |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dorling |first=Philip |date=4 September 2013 |title=WikiLeaks releases documents on global surveillance industry |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/wikileaks-releases-documents-on-global-surveillance-industry-20130905-hv1m6.html |access-date=25 April 2023 |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |archive-date=25 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230425213515/https://www.smh.com.au/technology/wikileaks-releases-documents-on-global-surveillance-industry-20130905-hv1m6.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The [[WikiLeaks Party]] was created in 2013 in part to support [[Julian Assange]]'s failed bid for a Senate seat in [[Australia]] in the [[2013 Australian federal election|2013 election]], where it won 0.62% of the national vote.<ref name="WP">{{cite news |last=Khazan |first=Olga |title=Julian Assange wants to start a Wikileaks party and run for office |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2012/12/12/assange-Wikileaks-party-australia |access-date=7 March 2013 |archive-date=30 January 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130222717/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2012/12/12/assange-wikileaks-party-australia/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |agency=Australian Associated Press |date=8 September 2013 |title=Julian Assange: WikiLeaks party will continue |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/08/election-2013-assange-wikileaks-party |access-date=11 October 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=1 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211201205341/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/08/election-2013-assange-wikileaks-party |url-status=live }}</ref> Assange said the party would advance WikiLeaks' objectives of promoting openness in government and politics and that it would combat intrusions on individual privacy.<ref name="WP" /><ref name="TA">{{cite news |last=Dorling |first=Philip |title=Assange looks to contest Senate election |publisher=The Age National Times |location=Melbourne |url=http://www.theage.com.au/opinion/political-news/assange-looks-to-contest-senate-election-20121212-2ba43.html |access-date=7 March 2013 |archive-date=5 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305173644/http://www.theage.com.au/opinion/political-news/assange-looks-to-contest-senate-election-20121212-2ba43.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="TC">{{cite web |last=Creagh |first=Sunanda |title='Wikileaks Party will attract the support of many women': Assange |url=http://theconversation.edu.au/Wikileaks-party-will-attract-the-support-of-many-women-assange-12246 |access-date=7 March 2013 |work=The Conversation |date=17 February 2013 |archive-date=8 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308011500/http://theconversation.edu.au/wikileaks-party-will-attract-the-support-of-many-women-assange-12246 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="SC">{{cite web |title=Wikileaks Party will attract female voters: Assange |url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/1738052/Wikileaks-Party-will-attract-female-voters-Assange |access-date=7 March 2013 |publisher=World News Australia |archive-date=6 March 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306162235/http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/1738052/WikiLeaks-Party-will-attract-female-voters-Assange |url-status=dead }}</ref> In December 2013, a delegation from the party, including its chairman [[John Shipton]], visited Syria and met with President [[Bashar al-Assad]]. Shipton said the goal of the meeting was demonstrating "solidarity with the Syrian people and their nation", improving the party's understanding of the country's civil war and told a Syrian TV station that WikiLeaks would be opening an office in Damascus in 2014. The meeting with Assad was criticised by the Australian Prime Minister, Foreign Minister and many WikiLeaks supporters.<ref>{{cite news |date=1 January 2014 |title=Wikileaks activists slammed for Bashar al-Assad meeting |work=The Australian |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/policy/Wikileaks-activists-slammed-for-bashar-alassad-meeting/story-fn59nm2j-1226792795063 |access-date=10 January 2018 |archive-date=2 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602115710/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/policy/wikileaks-activists-slammed-for-bashar-alassad-meeting/story-fn59nm2j-1226792795063 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="McKenny-2014">{{cite news |last1=McKenny |first1=Leesha |last2=Wroe |first2=David |date=1 January 2014 |title=Wikileaks Party defends its 'cup of tea' with Bashar al-Assad |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/Wikileaks-party-defends-its-cup-of-tea-with-bashar-alassad-20131231-304ne.html |access-date=1 January 2014 |archive-date=1 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140101020939/http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/wikileaks-party-defends-its-cup-of-tea-with-bashar-alassad-20131231-304ne.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Milman |first=Oliver |date=1 January 2014 |title=Meeting with Assad: WikiLeaks did not 'know or approve' of party's visit |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/01/meeting-assad-wikileaks-did-not-know |access-date=8 September 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529045507/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jan/01/meeting-assad-wikileaks-did-not-know |url-status=live }}</ref> Shipton stated that the meeting with al-Assad was "just a matter of good manners" and that the delegation had also met with members of the Syrian opposition.<ref name="McKenny-2014" /> However, these meetings with the opposition have not been verified. The WikiLeaks Party was deregistered by the [[Australian Electoral Commission]] on 23 July 2015 for lack of members under the ''[[Commonwealth Electoral Act 1918|Electoral Act]]''.<ref name="dereg">{{cite web |date=23 July 2015 |title=The Wikileaks Party |url=http://www.aec.gov.au/Parties_and_Representatives/Party_Registration/Deregistered_parties/Wikileaks.htm |access-date=24 July 2015 |publisher=Australian Electoral Commission |archive-date=24 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724115335/http://www.aec.gov.au/Parties_and_Representatives/Party_Registration/Deregistered_parties/wikileaks.htm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=LeMay |first=Renai |date=24 July 2015 |title=Wikileaks Party deregistered due to lack of members |url=https://delimiter.com.au/2015/07/24/wikileaks-party-deregistered-due-to-lack-of-members/ |access-date=8 February 2023 |website=Delimiter |language=en-US |archive-date=30 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230930135700/https://delimiter.com.au/2015/07/24/wikileaks-party-deregistered-due-to-lack-of-members/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks Party deregistered in Australia |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/wikileaks-party-deregistered-in-australia/ |access-date=8 February 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en |archive-date=8 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230208064531/https://www.zdnet.com/article/wikileaks-party-deregistered-in-australia/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2015 WikiLeaks began issuing "[[Bounty (reward)|bounties]]" of up to $100,000 for leaks.<ref name="wikileaks.org">{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – WikiLeaks issues call for $100,000 bounty on monster trade treaty |url=https://wikileaks.org/WikiLeaks-issues-call-for-100-000.html |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=wikileaks.org |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052034/https://wikileaks.org/WikiLeaks-issues-call-for-100-000.html |url-status=live }}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref> Assange had said in 2010 that WikiLeaks didn't but "would have no problem giving sources cash" and that there were systems in Belgium to let them.<ref name="leakonomy" /> WikiLeaks has issued crowd-sourced rewards for the [[Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership|TTIP]] chapters, the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership|TPP]]<ref name="wikileaks.org" /> and information on the [[Kunduz massacre]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks' Most Wanted |url=https://wikileaks.org/pledge/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313165549/https://wikileaks.org/pledge/ |archive-date=13 March 2022 |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=wikileaks.org}}</ref><ref name="wikileaks-twitter-2016">{{cite tweet|number=770358978203254784|user=wikileaks|title=Our position on rewards for information: https://t.co/1IJl0tAXNW|author=WikiLeaks|author-link=WikiLeaks|date=29 August 2016|access-date=19 March 2022|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313165942/https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/770358978203254784|archive-date=13 March 2022|url-status=live}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} WikiLeaks has issued other bounties for LabourLeaks,<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – WikiLeaks offers award for #LabourLeaks |url=https://wikileaks.org/WikiLeaks-offers-award-for-LabourLeaks.html |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=wikileaks.org |archive-date=12 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220312222835/https://wikileaks.org/WikiLeaks-offers-award-for-LabourLeaks.html |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election]]-related information,<ref>{{cite tweet|number=769649948870705152|user=wikileaks|title=We will soon issue a reward for additional US election related documents. Vote or reply with suggestions.|author=WikiLeaks|author-link=WikiLeaks|date=27 August 2016|access-date=19 March 2022|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313165840/https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/769649948870705152|archive-date=13 March 2022|url-status=live}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref><ref name="HuffPost-2016">{{Cite web |date=29 August 2016 |title=WikiLeaks Plans To Pay For Dirt On Clinton And Trump |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/wikileaks-plans-to-pay-for-dirt-on-clinton-and-trump_n_57c473dde4b0664f13c9bbac |access-date=25 October 2023 |website=HuffPost |language=en |archive-date=3 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220903140917/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/wikileaks-plans-to-pay-for-dirt-on-clinton-and-trump_n_57c473dde4b0664f13c9bbac |url-status=live }}</ref> and information to get a reporter at The Intercept fired over the [[Reality Winner|Reality Winner case]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Uchill |first=Joe |date=6 June 2017 |title=WikiLeaks offers $10,000 to get Intercept reporter fired |url=https://thehill.com/policy/cybersecurity/336518-wikileaks-offering-10000-to-get-intercept-reporter-fired/ |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |language=en |archive-date=13 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313165547/https://thehill.com/policy/cybersecurity/336518-wikileaks-offering-10000-to-get-intercept-reporter-fired |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} WikiLeaks has defended the practice with their vetting record, saying "police rewards produce results. So do journalistic rewards."<ref name="wikileaks-twitter-2016" /><ref name="HuffPost-2016" />

Its website stated in 2015 that it had released 10 million documents online.<ref name="WikiLeaks" />

=== 2016 U.S. presidential election ===
{{See also|2016 Democratic National Committee email leak|Podesta emails|Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections}}
Assange wrote on WikiLeaks in February 2016: "I have had years of experience in dealing with [[Hillary Clinton]] and have read thousands of her cables. Hillary lacks judgement and will push the United States into endless, stupid wars which spread terrorism. ...  she certainly should not become president of the United States."<ref>{{cite news |date=24 June 2016 |title=Why Julian Assange Doesn't Want Hillary Clinton to Be President |work=[[The Observer]] |url=http://observer.com/2016/06/why-julian-assange-doesnt-want-hillary-clinton-to-be-president/ |access-date=6 March 2018 |archive-date=24 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171224013724/http://observer.com/2016/06/why-julian-assange-doesnt-want-hillary-clinton-to-be-president/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In a 2017 interview by [[Amy Goodman]], Julian Assange said that choosing between Hillary Clinton and [[Donald Trump]] is like choosing between [[cholera]] or [[gonorrhea]]. "Personally, I would prefer neither."<ref>{{cite web |date=27 July 2016 |title=Assange: 2016 election is like choosing between 'cholera or gonorrhea' |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/07/julian-assange-us-election-2016-226281 |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=[[Politico]] |archive-date=26 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026162629/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/07/julian-assange-us-election-2016-226281 |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks editor [[Sarah Harrison (journalist)|Sarah Harrison]] stated that the site was not choosing which damaging publications to release, rather releasing information available to them.<ref>{{Cite news |title=How Julian Assange Turned WikiLeaks into Trump's Best Friend |work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-10-11/how-julian-assange-turned-wikileaks-into-trump-s-best-friend |access-date=27 October 2016 |archive-date=9 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161109132018/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-10-11/how-julian-assange-turned-wikileaks-into-trump-s-best-friend |url-status=live }}</ref> In conversations that were leaked in February 2018, Assange expressed a preference for a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] victory in the 2016 election, saying that "Dems+Media+liberals would then form a block to reign in their worst qualities. With Hillary in charge, GOP will be pushing for her worst qualities, dems+media+neoliberals will be mute. She's a bright, well connected, sadistic sociopath".<ref name="Lee-2018">{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Micah |last2=Currier |first2=Cora |date=14 February 2018 |title=In Leaked Chats, WikiLeaks Discusses Preference for GOP Over Clinton, Russia, Trolling, and Feminists They Don't Like |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/02/14/julian-assange-wikileaks-election-clinton-trump/ |access-date=15 February 2018 |website=The Intercept |language=en-US |archive-date=9 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210209193633/https://theintercept.com/2018/02/14/julian-assange-wikileaks-election-clinton-trump/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Having released information about a broad range of organisations and politicians, WikiLeaks started by 2016 to focus almost exclusively on [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] presidential candidate Hillary Clinton.<ref name="McLaughlin-2017">{{cite web |last=McLaughlin |first=Jenna |date=17 August 2017 |title=WikiLeaks Turned Down Leaks on Russian Government During U.S. Presidential Campaign |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/08/17/wikileaks-turned-down-leaks-on-russian-government-during-u-s-presidential-campaign/ |access-date=17 August 2017 |website=[[Foreign Policy]] |archive-date=21 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210221035812/https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/08/17/wikileaks-turned-down-leaks-on-russian-government-during-u-s-presidential-campaign/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 U.S. presidential election]], WikiLeaks only exposed material damaging to the [[Democratic National Committee]] and Hillary Clinton. According to ''The New York Times'', WikiLeaks timed one of its large leaks so that it would happen on the eve of the [[Democratic National Convention|Democratic Convention]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Savage |first=Charlie |date=26 July 2016 |title=Assange, Avowed Foe of Clinton, Timed Email Release for Democratic Convention |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/us/politics/assange-timed-wikileaks-release-of-democratic-emails-to-harm-hillary-clinton.html |access-date=23 October 2017 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=8 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308182211/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/us/politics/assange-timed-wikileaks-release-of-democratic-emails-to-harm-hillary-clinton.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Sunlight Foundation]] said that such actions meant that WikiLeaks was no longer striving to be transparent but rather sought to achieve political goals.<ref name="Vick-2017">{{cite news |last=Vick |first=Karl |title=WikiLeaks Is Getting Scarier Than the NSA |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |url=https://time.com/4450282/wikileaks-julian-assange-dnc-hack-criticism/ |access-date=23 October 2017 |archive-date=4 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171104034727/http://time.com/4450282/wikileaks-julian-assange-dnc-hack-criticism/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[Thomas Joscelyn]], a senior fellow at ''[[New York University School of Law|Just Security]]'', wrote that Assange had a "hatred of Clinton", whom he said was a "sadistic sociopath". Joscelyn wrote that "WikiLeaks' collusion with Russian government hackers during the 2016 presidential campaign" was "arguably even more consequential" than the  [[Iraq War documents leak]], the [[Afghan War documents leak]] and the [[United States diplomatic cables leak]]. According to Joscelyn, "Assange made it his goal in 2016 to counter the 'American liberal press,' which he accused of supporting Clinton. He aimed to turn that same press against her. Ultimately, with Russia's help, Assange succeeded."<ref name="Joscelyn_7/1/2024">{{cite web | last=Joscelyn | first=Thomas | title=How Julian Assange Shaped the 2016 Election | website=[[The Dispatch]] | date=1 July 2024 | url=https://thedispatch.com/article/how-julian-assange-shaped-the-2016-election/ | access-date=1 July 2024}}</ref>

==== Secret correspondence between WikiLeaks and Donald Trump Jr. ====

In November 2017 it was revealed that the WikiLeaks Twitter account secretly corresponded with [[Donald Trump Jr.]] during the 2016 presidential election.<ref name="Ioffe-2017">{{Cite news |last=Ioffe |first=Julia |title=The Secret Correspondence Between Donald Trump Jr. and WikiLeaks |language=en-US |work=[[The Atlantic]] |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/11/the-secret-correspondence-between-donald-trump-jr-and-wikileaks/545738/ |access-date=13 November 2017 |archive-date=13 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113222527/https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/11/the-secret-correspondence-between-donald-trump-jr-and-wikileaks/545738/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Pilkington-2017" /> The correspondence shows how WikiLeaks actively solicited the co-operation of Trump Jr., a campaign surrogate and advisor in the campaign of his father. WikiLeaks urged the Trump campaign to reject the results of the 2016 presidential election at a time when it looked as if the Trump campaign would lose.<ref name="Ioffe-2017" /> WikiLeaks asked Trump Jr. to share a WikiLeaks tweet with the made-up<ref name="Silverman-2018">{{Cite web |last=Silverman |first=Craig |date=27 August 2018 |title=Revealed: Notorious Pro-Trump Misinformation Site True Pundit Is Run By An Ex-Journalist With A Grudge Against The FBI |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/craigsilverman/revealed-notorious-pro-trump-misinformation-site-true |access-date=1 November 2023 |website=BuzzFeed News |language=en |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030002421/https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/craigsilverman/revealed-notorious-pro-trump-misinformation-site-true |url-status=live }}</ref> quote "Can't we just drone this guy?" which ''[[True Pundit]]'' said Hillary Clinton made about Assange.<ref name="Ioffe-2017" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Singal |first=Jesse |date=3 October 2016 |title=Explaining the Rumor That Hillary Clinton Wanted to Drone-Strike Julian Assange |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/10/no-clinton-didnt-say-she-wanted-to-drone-strike-assange.html |access-date=3 June 2023 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York Intelligencer]] |language=en-us |archive-date=13 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181113141827/http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/10/no-clinton-didnt-say-she-wanted-to-drone-strike-assange.html |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks also shared a link to a site that would help people to search through WikiLeaks documents.<ref name="Ioffe-2017" /> Trump Jr. shared both. After the election, WikiLeaks also requested that the president-elect push Australia to appoint Assange as [[Australian Ambassador to the United States|ambassador to the US]]. Trump Jr. provided this correspondence to congressional investigators looking into Russian interference in the 2016 election.<ref name="Ioffe-2017" /> Assange repeated his offer of being ambassador to the US after the messages became public, publicly tweeting to Donald Trump Jr. that "I could open a hotel style embassy in DC with luxury immunity suites for whistleblowers. The public will get a turbo-charged flow of intel about the latest CIA plots to undermine democracy. DM me."<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 November 2017 |title=Julian Assange has responded to Trump Jr releasing their private Twitter messages |url=https://www.the-independent.com/news/world/americas/us-politics/julian-assange-trump-jr-wikileaks-ambassador-offer-dm-messages-twitter-a8055021.html |access-date=26 October 2023 |website=The Independent |language=en |archive-date=26 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231026122755/https://www.the-independent.com/news/world/americas/us-politics/julian-assange-trump-jr-wikileaks-ambassador-offer-dm-messages-twitter-a8055021.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Klasfeld |first=Adam |date=16 November 2018 |title=Feds Say Suspected CIA WikiLeaker Spilled New Files From Prison |url=https://www.courthousenews.com/feds-say-suspected-cia-wikileaker-spilled-new-files-from-prison/ |website=Courthouse News Service |access-date=26 October 2023 |archive-date=26 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231026122753/https://www.courthousenews.com/feds-say-suspected-cia-wikileaker-spilled-new-files-from-prison/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The secretive exchanges led to criticism of WikiLeaks by some former supporters. WikiLeaks tweeted that the Clinton campaign was "constantly slandering" it as "a 'pro-Trump' 'pro-Russia' source". Journalist [[Barrett Brown]], a long-time defender of WikiLeaks, was exasperated that Assange was "complaining about 'slander' of being pro-Trump IN THE ACTUAL COURSE OF COLLABORATING WITH TRUMP". He wrote: "Was 'Wikileaks staff' lying on Nov 10, 2016, when they claimed, 'The allegations that we have colluded with Trump, or any other candidate for that matter, or with Russia, are just groundless and false', or did Assange lie to them?"<ref name="Mackey_11/15/2017">{{cite web |last=Mackey |first=Robert |date=15 November 2017 |title=Julian Assange's Hatred of Hillary Clinton Was No Secret. His Advice to Donald Trump Was. |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/11/15/wikileaks-julian-assange-donald-trump-jr-hillary-clinton/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171115193122/https://theintercept.com/2017/11/15/wikileaks-julian-assange-donald-trump-jr-hillary-clinton/ |archive-date=15 November 2017 |access-date=3 February 2023 |website=[[The Intercept]] |url-status=live }}</ref> Brown said Assange had acted "as a covert political operative", thus betraying WikiLeaks' focus on exposing "corporate and government wrongdoing".<ref name="Mackey_11/15/2017" />

==== Promotion of false conspiracy theories ====
In 2016 and 2017, WikiLeaks promoted several false [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]],<ref name="Ohlheiser-2016" /><ref name="Seitz-Wald-2016" /><ref name="bloomberg" /> most related to the [[2016 United States presidential election]].

===== Murder of Seth Rich =====
{{Further|Murder of Seth Rich}}

WikiLeaks promoted conspiracy theories about the murder of Seth Rich.<ref name="Rogin-2016">{{cite news |last=Rogin |first=Josh |date=12 August 2016 |title=Trump allies, WikiLeaks and Russia are pushing a nonsensical conspiracy theory about the DNC hacks |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2016/08/12/trump-allies-wikileaks-and-russia-are-pushing-a-nonsensical-conspiracy-theory-about-the-dnc-hacks/ |quote=Trump campaign surrogates are fueling a conspiracy theory that a murdered Democratic National Committee staffer was connected to the hacking of the DNC, a theory being pushed by WikiLeaks and the Russian state-controlled press |access-date=15 August 2016 |archive-date=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417212833/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/josh-rogin/wp/2016/08/12/trump-allies-wikileaks-and-russia-are-pushing-a-nonsensical-conspiracy-theory-about-the-dnc-hacks/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=How Seth Rich's death became an Internet conspiracy theory |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-seth-rich-conspiracy-20170523-htmlstory.html |access-date=26 October 2017 |issn=0458-3035 |archive-date=29 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170529184553/http://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-seth-rich-conspiracy-20170523-htmlstory.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Bui |first=Lynh |date=31 December 2016 |title=Homicides remain steady in the Washington region |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/homicides-remain-steady-in-the-washington-region/2016/12/31/f30b7db4-cc51-11e6-a747-d03044780a02_story.html |access-date=26 October 2017 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=5 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210205214529/https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/public-safety/homicides-remain-steady-in-the-washington-region/2016/12/31/f30b7db4-cc51-11e6-a747-d03044780a02_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Unfounded conspiracy theories, spread by some right-wing figures and media outlets, hold that Rich was the source of leaked emails and was killed for working with WikiLeaks.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bromwich |first=Jonah Engel |date=17 May 2017 |title=How the Murder of a D.N.C. Staffer Fueled Conspiracy Theories |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/17/us/seth-rich-dnc-wikileaks.html |access-date=17 May 2017 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=7 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201207155610/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/17/us/seth-rich-dnc-wikileaks.html |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks fuelled such theories when it offered a $20,000 reward for information on Rich's killer and when Assange implied that Rich was the source of the DNC leaks,<ref>{{cite news |date=23 May 2017 |title=Fox retracts Clinton murder conspiracy |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40021373 |access-date=26 October 2017 |archive-date=24 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170524080403/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40021373 |url-status=live }}</ref> although no evidence supports that.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Seitz-Wald |first=Alex |date=10 August 2016 |title=WikiLeaks Fuels Conspiracy Theories About DNC Staffer's Death |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/wikileaks-fuels-conspiracy-theories-about-dnc-staffer-s-death-n627401 |access-date=14 April 2019 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |language=en |archive-date=12 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210212185833/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2016-election/wikileaks-fuels-conspiracy-theories-about-dnc-staffer-s-death-n627401 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Stahl |first=Jeremy |date=9 August 2016 |title=WikiLeaks Is Fanning a Conspiracy Theory That Hillary Murdered a DNC Staffer |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2016/08/09/wikileaks_is_fanning_a_conspiracy_theory_that_hillary_murdered_a_dnc_staffer.html |issn=1091-2339 |quote=Julian Assange and his WikiLeaks organization appear to be actively encouraging a conspiracy theory that a Democratic National Committee staffer was murdered for nefarious political purposes, perhaps by Hillary Clinton. ... . There is of course absolutely zero evidence for this and Snopes has issued a comprehensive debunking of the premise itself |access-date=23 October 2016 |archive-date=20 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020044207/http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2016/08/09/wikileaks_is_fanning_a_conspiracy_theory_that_hillary_murdered_a_dnc_staffer.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Special Counsel Robert Mueller's [[Mueller report|report into Russian interference in the 2016 election]] said that Assange "implied falsely" that Rich was the source in order to obscure that Russia was the actual source.<ref>[https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf ''Mueller Report''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419072437/https://www.justice.gov/storage/report.pdf |date=19 April 2019 }}, vol I. p. 48: Beginning in the summer of 2016, Assange and WikiLeaks made a number of statements about Seth Rich, a former DNC staff member who was killed in July 2016. The statements about Rich implied falsely that he had been the source of the stolen DNC emails.</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Mervosh |first=Sarah |date=20 April 2019 |title=Seth Rich Was Not Source of Leaked D.N.C. Emails, Mueller Report Confirms |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/20/us/mueller-report-seth-rich-assange.html |access-date=24 April 2019 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=20 April 2019 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190420203507/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/20/us/mueller-report-seth-rich-assange.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Jamie Dupree |first=Cox Washington Bureau |title=Mueller: Wikileaks used dead DNC worker in bid to cover Russia ties |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/jamie-dupree/mueller-wikileaks-used-dead-dnc-worker-bid-cover-russia-ties/SWSSsHGY7BJNc8pSrzZ9XJ/ |access-date=24 April 2019 |website=ajc |language=en |archive-date=24 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424235013/https://www.ajc.com/blog/jamie-dupree/mueller-wikileaks-used-dead-dnc-worker-bid-cover-russia-ties/SWSSsHGY7BJNc8pSrzZ9XJ/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===== Democratic Party and Hillary Clinton =====
WikiLeaks popularised conspiracy theories about the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and Hillary Clinton, such as tweeting articles which suggested Clinton campaign chairman [[John Podesta]] engaged in [[Satanic panic|satanic rituals]],<ref name="Ohlheiser-2016" /><ref name="Beauchamp-2016">{{Cite news |last=Beauchamp |first=Zack |title=WikiLeaks just tried to justify its behavior this year in a bizarre Election Day statement |work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2016/11/8/13563750/wikileaks-2016-election-statement |access-date=8 November 2016 |archive-date=1 December 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201201111432/https://www.vox.com/world/2016/11/8/13563750/wikileaks-2016-election-statement |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Evon-2016">{{Cite news |last=Evon |first=Dan |title=FALSE: Clinton Campaign Chairman John Podesta Involved in Satanic 'Spirit Cooking' |language=en-US |work=[[Snopes]] |url=http://www.snopes.com/john-podesta-spirit-cooking/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |archive-date=10 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310214711/https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/john-podesta-spirit-cooking/ |url-status=live }}</ref> claiming that Hillary Clinton wanted to [[drone strike]] Assange,<ref name="Silverman-2018" /><ref name="LaCapria-2016">{{Cite news |last=LaCapria |first=Kim |title=To Silence Wikileaks, Hillary Clinton Proposed Drone Strike on Julian Assange? |language=en-US |work=[[Snopes]] |url=http://www.snopes.com/julian-assange-drone-strike/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |archive-date=10 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310214712/https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/julian-assange-drone-strike/ |url-status=live }}</ref> suggesting that Clinton wore earpieces to debates and interviews,<ref name="Firozi-2016">{{Cite news |last=Firozi |first=Paulina |date=8 September 2016 |title=WikiLeaks piles on to Clinton earpiece conspiracy |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/295116-wikileaks-piles-on-to-clinton-earpiece-conspiracy/ |access-date=8 November 2016 |archive-date=14 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114012512/http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/295116-wikileaks-piles-on-to-clinton-earpiece-conspiracy |url-status=live }}</ref> promoting thinly sourced theories about Clinton's health and according to [[Bloomberg Businessweek|Bloomberg]] creating "anti-Clinton theories out of whole cloth".<ref name="bloomberg" /><ref name="Liebelson-2016">{{cite web |last=Liebelson |first=Dana |date=12 September 2016 |title=WikiLeaks Feeds Conspiracy Theories That Hillary Clinton Has Parkinson's Or Head Injury Complications |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-hillary-clinton_us_57d6f4b2e4b00642712ebbd0 |access-date=29 December 2016 |website=[[HuffPost]] |archive-date=10 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210310214308/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-hillary-clinton_n_57d6f4b2e4b00642712ebbd0 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===== Promotion of false flag theories =====
On the day the [[Vault 7]] documents were first released, WikiLeaks described UMBRAGE as "a substantial library of attack techniques 'stolen' from malware produced in other states including the Russian Federation," and tweeted, "CIA steals other groups virus and malware facilitating [[false flag]] attacks."<ref name="Business Insider">{{cite web |last=Tani |first=Maxwell |date=9 March 2017 |title=Conservative media figures are embracing a wild WikiLeaks conspiracy theory that the CIA hacked the DNC, and then framed Russia |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-cia-hacked-2017-3 |access-date=12 March 2017 |work=[[Business Insider]] |archive-date=15 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170615144337/http://www.businessinsider.com/sean-hannity-wikileaks-conspiracy-theory-cia-hacked-2017-3 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[conspiracy theory]] soon emerged alleging that the CIA framed the [[Russian government]] for [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|interfering in the 2016 U.S. elections]]. Conservative commentators such as [[Sean Hannity]] and [[Ann Coulter]] speculated about this possibility on Twitter, and [[Rush Limbaugh]] discussed it on his radio show.<ref name="WaPo conspiracy">{{cite news |last=Blake |first=Aaron |title=Analysis – The dangerous and irresistible GOP conspiracy theory that explains away Trump's Russia problem |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/03/10/the-dangerous-and-irresistible-gop-conspiracy-theory-that-explains-away-trumps-russia-problem/ |access-date=12 March 2017 |archive-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506135358/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/03/10/the-dangerous-and-irresistible-gop-conspiracy-theory-that-explains-away-trumps-russia-problem/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Russian foreign minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] said that Vault 7 showed that "the CIA could get access to such 'fingerprints' and then use them."<ref name="Business Insider" />

In ''[[The Washington Post]]'' the cybersecurity researcher Ben Buchanan writes that he is sceptical of those theories and that he believes Russia to have initially obtained the DNC emails.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buchanan |first1=Ben |date=9 March 2017 |title=WikiLeaks doesn't raise doubts about who hacked the DNC. We still know it was Russia. |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/russia-likely-hacked-the-dnc-and-new-wikileaks-revelations-strengthen-the-case/2017/03/09/e5fe55e8-04d6-11e7-b1e9-a05d3c21f7cf_story.html |access-date=12 March 2017 |archive-date=6 June 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606031137/https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/russia-likely-hacked-the-dnc-and-new-wikileaks-revelations-strengthen-the-case/2017/03/09/e5fe55e8-04d6-11e7-b1e9-a05d3c21f7cf_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In April 2017 the WikiLeaks Twitter account suggested that the [[Khan Shaykhun chemical attack]], which international human rights organisations attributed to the Syrian government, was a [[false flag]] attack.<ref name="Taylor-2017">{{cite news |title=Analysis {{!}} Trump loves a conspiracy theory. Now his allies in the fringe media want him to fall for one in Syria |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/04/06/trump-loves-a-conspiracy-theory-now-his-allies-in-the-media-say-hes-falling-for-one-in-syria/ |access-date=5 May 2017 |archive-date=6 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170506065431/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/04/06/trump-loves-a-conspiracy-theory-now-his-allies-in-the-media-say-hes-falling-for-one-in-syria/ |url-status=live }}</ref> WikiLeaks stated that "while western establishment media beat the drum for more war in Syria the matter is far from clear", and shared a video by a Syrian activist who said that Islamist extremists were probably behind the attack, not the [[Government of Syria|Syrian government]].<ref name="Taylor-2017" />

=== Later years ===
In 2016 the WikiLeaks Twitter account was criticised for tweets that were seen as [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]].<ref name="TheForward-2016">{{Cite news |title=Why Does Wikileaks Have a Reputation for Anti-Semitism? |work=The Forward |url=http://forward.com/news/national/347546/why-does-wikileaks-have-a-reputation-for-anti-semitism/ |access-date=23 October 2016 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052004/https://forward.com/news/347546/why-does-wikileaks-have-a-reputation-for-anti-semitism/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Stahl-2016">{{Cite news |last=Stahl |first=Jeremy |date=25 July 2016 |title=Here's What WikiLeaks Might Have Meant by That Anti-Semitic Tweet It Deleted |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2016/07/25/what_wikileaks_might_have_meant_by_that_anti_semitic_tweet.html |access-date=23 October 2016 |issn=1091-2339 |archive-date=23 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023071403/http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2016/07/25/what_wikileaks_might_have_meant_by_that_anti_semitic_tweet.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Ellis-2016">{{Cite news |last=Ellis |first=Emma Grey |title=WikiLeaks Has Officially Lost the Moral High Ground |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/07/wikileaks-officially-lost-moral-high-ground/ |access-date=23 October 2016 |archive-date=13 November 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113041919/https://www.wired.com/2016/07/wikileaks-officially-lost-moral-high-ground/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 17 October 2016 WikiLeaks announced that a "state party" had severed the Internet connection of Julian Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy. WikiLeaks blamed US Secretary of State [[John Kerry]] for pressuring the Ecuadorian government in severing Assange's Internet, an accusation which the [[United States State Department]] denied.<ref name="Daily Dot Internet">{{cite web |last=Couts |first=Andrew |date=18 October 2016 |title=WikiLeaks publishes more Podesta emails after Ecuador cuts Assange's Internet |url=http://www.dailydot.com/layer8/wikileaks-podesta-emails-part-11-julian-assange-internet-cut/ |access-date=23 October 2016 |website=[[The Daily Dot]] |archive-date=23 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023054505/http://www.dailydot.com/layer8/wikileaks-podesta-emails-part-11-julian-assange-internet-cut/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Ecuadorian government stated that it had "temporarily" severed Assange's Internet connection because of WikiLeaks' release of documents "impacting on the U.S. election campaign," although it also stated that this was not meant to prevent WikiLeaks from operating.<ref>{{cite web |last=Bennett |first=Cory |title=Ecuador admits restricting Internet access for WikiLeaks over election meddling |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/ecuador-admits-restricting-internet-access-for-wikileaks-over-election-meddling-229963 |access-date=23 October 2016 |website=[[Politico]] |date=18 October 2016 |archive-date=22 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022060530/http://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/ecuador-admits-restricting-internet-access-for-wikileaks-over-election-meddling-229963 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence]] concluded that in 2016, "WikiLeaks actively sought, and played, a key role in the [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russian influence campaign]] and very likely knew it was assisting a Russian intelligence influence effort."<ref>{{cite web |last=Karhula |first=Päivikki |date=5 October 2012 |title=What is the effect of WikiLeaks for Freedom of Information? |url=http://www.ifla.org/publications/what-is-the-effect-of-wikileaks-for-freedom-of-information |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120630172755/http://www.ifla.org/publications/what-is-the-effect-of-wikileaks-for-freedom-of-information |archive-date=30 June 2012 |access-date=11 October 2012 |publisher=International Federation of Library Associations and Institutions}}</ref>

In April 2017 [[United States Attorney General|Attorney General]] [[Jeff Sessions]] said that the US Government had prioritised its attempts to arrest Assange.<ref name=Pe17>{{cite web |last=Perez |first=Evan |url=https://www.cnn.com/2017/04/20/politics/julian-assange-wikileaks-us-charges/ |title=US prepares charges to seek Julian Assange's arrest – CNNPolitics |publisher=CNN |date=20 April 2017 |access-date=28 January 2019 |archive-date=27 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127050139/https://www.cnn.com/2017/04/20/politics/julian-assange-wikileaks-us-charges/ |url-status=live }}</ref> On 16 August 2017 [[Republican Party (United States)|US Republican]] congressman [[Dana Rohrabacher]] visited Assange and told him that Trump would pardon him on condition that he would agree to say that Russia was not involved in the [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak]]s.<ref name="Bowcott_Borger_19/2/2020" /><ref name="Mai-Duc_17/8/2017" /> At his extradition hearings in 2020, Assange's defence team alleged in court that this offer was made "on instructions from the president". Trump and Rohrabacher subsequently said they had never spoken about the offer and Rohrabacher said he had made the offer on his own initiative.<ref name="Bowcott_Borger_19/2/2020">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/feb/19/donald-trump-offered-julian-assange-pardon-russia-hack-wikileaks |title=Donald Trump 'offered Julian Assange a pardon if he denied Russia link to hack' |work=The Guardian |date=19 February 2020 |access-date=19 February 2020 |author=Bowcott, Owen and Julian Borger}}</ref><ref name="Mai-Duc_17/8/2017">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-201708-htmlstory.html#rohrabacher-on-meeting-with-wikileaks-assange-we-talked-about-what-might-be-necessary-to-get-him-out |title=Rohrabacher on meeting with WikiLeaks' Assange: We talked about 'what might be necessary to get him out' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=17 August 2017 |access-date=20 February 2020 |author=Mai-Duc, Christine |archive-date=17 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217022046/https://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-201708-htmlstory.html#rohrabacher-on-meeting-with-wikileaks-assange-we-talked-about-what-might-be-necessary-to-get-him-out |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/rohrabacher-confirms-he-offered-trump-pardon-to-assange-for-proof-russia-didnt-hack-dnc-email-131438007.html |title=Rohrabacher confirms he offered Trump pardon to Assange for proof Russia didn't hack DNC email |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=20 February 2020 |access-date=20 February 2020 |author=Isikoff, Michael |archive-date=20 February 2020 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200220162904/https://news.yahoo.com/rohrabacher-confirms-he-offered-trump-pardon-to-assange-for-proof-russia-didnt-hack-dnc-email-131438007.html?guccounter=1 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2017, traffic to the WikiLeaks website was diverted by [[DNS hijacking]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=What Is DNS Hijacking? |url=https://www.wired.com/story/what-is-dns-hijacking/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |magazine=Wired |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131346/https://www.wired.com/story/what-is-dns-hijacking/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Hern |first=Alex |date=31 August 2017 |title=WikiLeaks 'hacked' as OurMine group answers 'hack us' challenge |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/31/wikileaks-hacked-ourmine-group-julian-assange-dns-attack |access-date=29 January 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=7 November 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107021329/https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/aug/31/wikileaks-hacked-ourmine-group-julian-assange-dns-attack |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Toor |first=Amar |date=31 August 2017 |title=WikiLeaks website apparently hacked by OurMine |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/31/16232164/wikileaks-hacked-ourmine-website |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=The Verge |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240129131347/https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/31/16232164/wikileaks-hacked-ourmine-website |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2018, 11,000 messages from a private chat with WikiLeaks and key supporters from May 2015 through November 2017 was leaked. The messages showed Assange criticising Hillary Clinton and expressing a desire for a Republican president because he believed Clinton would have "a greater freedom to start wars than the GOP and has a will to do so".<ref name="Lee-2018" /> Later that year, "tens of thousands" of files from WikiLeaks laptops was leaked to the [[Associated Press]].<ref name="The New York Times" />

In January 2019, WikiLeaks sent journalists a "confidential legal communication not for publication" with a list of 140 things not to say about Julian Assange that WikiLeaks said were "false and defamatory".<ref>{{Cite news |date=6 January 2019 |title=WikiLeaks tells reporters 140 things not to say about Julian Assange |language=en |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-ecuador-assange-idUSKCN1P00NN |access-date=26 November 2022 |archive-date=31 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331074157/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-ecuador-assange-idUSKCN1P00NN |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Anapol |first=Avery |date=7 January 2019 |title=WikiLeaks tells media organizations what not to report about Julian Assange: report |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/424116-wikileaks-sends-email-to-media-organizations-with-list-of-things-not-to-report/ |access-date=26 November 2022 |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |language=en-US |archive-date=28 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230328094048/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/424116-wikileaks-sends-email-to-media-organizations-with-list-of-things-not-to-report/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Soon after the list was leaked online, WikiLeaks posted a heavily edited version of it.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gallagher |first=Sean |date=7 January 2019 |title=Please don't repeat these things WikiLeaks says you can't say about Assange [Updated] |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2019/01/140-things-wikileaks-says-reporters-cant-say-about-assange/ |access-date=26 November 2022 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us |archive-date=27 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230527063946/https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2019/01/140-things-wikileaks-says-reporters-cant-say-about-assange/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The group was criticised and mocked for the list and their handling of it.<ref>{{Cite web |first=Mike |last=Masnick |date=8 January 2019 |title=Irony Alert: Wikileaks Sends Reporters A List Of 140 Things Not To Say About Julian Assange; Tells Them Not To Publish |url=https://www.techdirt.com/2019/01/08/irony-alert-wikileaks-sends-reporters-list-140-things-not-to-say-about-julian-assange-tells-them-not-to-publish/ |access-date=26 November 2022 |website=Techdirt |language=en-US |archive-date=29 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230329075218/https://www.techdirt.com/2019/01/08/irony-alert-wikileaks-sends-reporters-list-140-things-not-to-say-about-julian-assange-tells-them-not-to-publish/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=7 January 2019 |title=Leaked WikiLeaks Email: Non-Murderer Julian Assange Doesn't Stink or Live Under the Stairs |url=https://gizmodo.com/leaked-wikileaks-email-non-murderer-julian-assange-doe-1831547094 |access-date=26 November 2022 |website=Gizmodo |language=en |archive-date=28 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221228001112/https://gizmodo.com/leaked-wikileaks-email-non-murderer-julian-assange-doe-1831547094 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=12 April 2019 |title=Julian Assange is many things |url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/cut-paste/julian-assange-is-a-journalist-meticulously-clean-kind-to-his-cat-and-not-putins-btch/news-story/7dd3ac97f3daad8ad41bd7d668220d68 |access-date=26 November 2022 |website=www.theaustralian.com.au |language=en |archive-date=26 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221126172606/https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/cut-paste/julian-assange-is-a-journalist-meticulously-clean-kind-to-his-cat-and-not-putins-btch/news-story/7dd3ac97f3daad8ad41bd7d668220d68 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Chapman |first=Matthew |date=7 January 2019 |title=Twitter mocks WikiLeaks for giving reporters list of 140 things not to say about Julian Assange |url=https://www.salon.com/2019/01/07/internet-mocks-wikileaks-for-giving-reporters-list-of-140-defamatory-things-not-to-say-about-julian-assange_partner/ |access-date=26 November 2022 |website=[[Salon.com|Salon]] |language=en |archive-date=13 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713051732/https://www.salon.com/2019/01/07/internet-mocks-wikileaks-for-giving-reporters-list-of-140-defamatory-things-not-to-say-about-julian-assange_partner/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In November 2022, much of the content released by WikiLeaks disappeared from the website, bringing the number of documents from around 10 million to around 3,000. Other reported issues with the site included the websites search ability not working and a broken submission page.<ref name="Gizmodo-2022b2"/><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Burgess |first=Matt |title=Apple Tracks You More Than You Think |url=https://www.wired.com/story/apple-iphone-privacy-analytics-security-roundup/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |access-date=24 December 2022 |archive-date=4 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231104084414/https://www.wired.com/story/apple-iphone-privacy-analytics-security-roundup/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

== Administration ==

WikiLeaks describes itself as "an uncensorable system for untraceable mass document leaking"<ref>{{cite news |last=Moss |first=Stephen |date=14 July 2010 |title=Julian Assange: the whistleblower |work=[[The Guardian]] |place=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/jul/14/julian-assange-whistleblower-wikileaks |url-status=live |access-date=7 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110626230605/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2010/jul/14/julian-assange-whistleblower-wikileaks |archive-date=26 June 2011}}</ref> with its goal being "to bring important news and information to the public".<ref name="epic">{{cite web |title=EPIC v. DOJ, FBI: Wikileaks |url=http://epic.org/foia/epic_v_doj_fbi_wikileaks.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140214023818/http://epic.org/foia/epic_v_doj_fbi_wikileaks.html |archive-date=14 February 2014 |publisher=[[Electronic Privacy Information Center]]}}</ref> It is "a project of the Sunshine Press",<ref name="TheGuardian-2023" /><ref name="BBC-2023" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – About |url=https://wikileaks.org/About.html |access-date=29 January 2023 |website=wikileaks.org |archive-date=17 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230217020604/https://wikileaks.org/About.html |url-status=live }}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} a [[non-profit organisation]] based in Iceland.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |date=27 March 2010 |title=The war on WikiLeaks and why it matters |url=https://www.salon.com/2010/03/27/wikileaks/ |access-date=29 January 2023 |website=[[Salon.com|Salon]] |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129040916/https://www.salon.com/2010/03/27/wikileaks/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Brenner |first=Bill |date=9 December 2010 |title=The WikiLeaks drama: A timeline |url=https://www.csoonline.com/article/2126269/the-wikileaks-drama-a-timeline.html |access-date=29 January 2023 |website=CSO Online |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129040912/https://www.csoonline.com/article/2126269/the-wikileaks-drama-a-timeline.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2010, Julian Assange and [[Kristinn Hrafnsson]] registered Sunshine Press Productions [[Ehf.|ehf]]<ref name="Skatturinn-2023" /> as a business without a headquarters in Iceland.<ref>{{Cite news |date=12 November 2010 |title=WikiLeaks registers company in Iceland |language=en-AU |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-11-13/wikileaks-registers-company-in-iceland/2335098 |access-date=29 January 2023 |archive-date=29 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129040916/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2010-11-13/wikileaks-registers-company-in-iceland/2335098 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Knobbe |first1=Martin |last2=Sontheimer |first2=Michael |date=3 May 2019 |title=WikiLeaks: Everything Was Done To Make Assange Miserable |language=en |work=Der Spiegel |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/wikileaks-everything-was-done-to-make-assange-miserable-a-1265603.html |access-date=29 January 2023 |issn=2195-1349 |archive-date=29 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129040916/https://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/wikileaks-everything-was-done-to-make-assange-miserable-a-1265603.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Assange serves as the Director of Sunshine Press Productions ehf and is on the board of directors with Hrafnsson and Ingi Ragnar Ingason.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Assange |first=Julian |date=23 February 2012 |title=AFFIDAVIT OF Julian Paul Assange |url=https://wikileaks.org/IMG/pdf/Witness_Statement_Leveson_-_Julian_Assange_-_23_February_2012.pdf |access-date=29 January 2023 |website=www.wikileaks.org |archive-date=29 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230329010451/https://wikileaks.org/IMG/pdf/Witness_Statement_Leveson_-_Julian_Assange_-_23_February_2012.pdf |url-status=live }}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref><ref name="Icenews-2010">{{cite web |date=13 November 2010 |title=Wikileaks starts company in Icelandic apartment |url=http://www.icenews.is/index.php/2010/11/13/wikileaks-starts-company-in-icelandic-apartment/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101122222226/http://www.icenews.is/index.php/2010/11/13/wikileaks-starts-company-in-icelandic-apartment/ |archive-date=22 November 2010 |access-date=22 November 2011 |website=Icenews.is}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks spokesman quietly steps out of the spotlight |url=https://apnews.com/article/97f0a6617a984f19813dd8adf451fa00 |access-date=29 January 2023 |website=[[Associated Press|AP News]] |date=28 February 2017 |language=en |archive-date=29 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230129040916/https://apnews.com/article/97f0a6617a984f19813dd8adf451fa00 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="TheGuardian-2023">{{cite news |title=Pass notes No 2,758: Wikileaks |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/06/pass-notes-wikileaks |access-date=7 January 2023 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052007/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/apr/06/pass-notes-wikileaks |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Deilur um skiptingu bóta til Wikileaks – Sveinn Andri fær tugi milljóna |work=DV |url=https://www.dv.is/eyjan/2019/07/11/deilur-um-skiptingu-bota-til-wikileaks-sveinn-andri-faer-tugi-milljona/ |access-date=7 January 2023 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052011/https://www.dv.is/eyjan/2019/07/11/deilur-um-skiptingu-bota-til-wikileaks-sveinn-andri-faer-tugi-milljona/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="BBC-2023">{{cite news |title=What is Wikileaks? |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-10757263 |access-date=7 January 2023 |archive-date=6 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230106052119/https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-10757263 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Skatturinn-2023">{{cite news |title=Sunshine Press Productions ehf (6110100280) |work=Skatturinn |url=https://www.skatturinn.is/fyrirtaekjaskra/leit/kennitala/6110100280 |access-date=7 January 2023 |archive-date=5 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230105080026/https://www.skatturinn.is/fyrirtaekjaskra/leit/kennitala/6110100280 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Gavin MacFadyen]] was a deputy board member.<ref name="Icenews-2010" /> In 2010, the WikiLeaks team then consisted of five people working full-time and about 800 people who worked occasionally, none of whom were compensated.<ref name="leakonomy">{{cite news |author=Mey, Stefan |date=4 January 2010 |title=Leak-o-nomy: The Economy of Wikileaks (Interview with Julian Assange) |work=Medien-Ökonomie-Blog |url=http://stefanmey.wordpress.com/2010/01/04/leak-o-nomy-the-economy-of-wikileaks/ |url-status=dead |access-date=19 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101213110334/http://stefanmey.wordpress.com/2010/01/04/leak-o-nomy-the-economy-of-wikileaks/ |archive-date=13 December 2010}}</ref><ref name="The Sydney Morning Herald-2010" /> Former WikiLeaks journalist [[James Ball (journalist)|James Ball]] said in 2011 that "WikiLeaks is not a conventional organisation. It has no board, no governance, and no effective rules."<ref name="Ball-2011" />

=== Editorial policy ===
The scholar and internet activist [[Ethan Zuckerman]] suggested that WikiLeaks' editorial policy changes can be viewed as different stages. In the first stage, Zuckerman says WikiLeaks did very little redacting and almost all leaks were accepted, and the main focus was on leakers protecting their identities.<ref name="MIT Technology Review">{{Cite web |title=Everything You Need to Know About Wikileaks |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/2010/12/09/120156/everything-you-need-to-know-about-wikileaks/ |access-date=8 July 2023 |website=MIT Technology Review |language=en |archive-date=11 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711013640/https://www.technologyreview.com/2010/12/09/120156/everything-you-need-to-know-about-wikileaks/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Radio Berkman 171">{{Cite web |title=» Radio Berkman 171: Wikileaks and the Information Wars MediaBerkman |url=https://blogs.harvard.edu/mediaberkman/2010/12/08/radio-berkman-171/ |access-date=8 July 2023 |language=en |archive-date=11 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711013640/https://blogs.harvard.edu/mediaberkman/2010/12/08/radio-berkman-171/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In response to early criticism that having no editorial policy would drive out good material with spam and promote "automated or indiscriminate publication of confidential records",<ref>{{cite news |author=Aftergood, Steven |date=3 January 2007 |title=Wikileaks and untraceable document disclosure |work=Secrecy News |publisher=Federation of American Scientists |url=https://fas.org/blogs/secrecy/2007/01/wikileaks_and_untraceable_docu/ |url-status=live |access-date=21 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130311214041/https://fas.org/blog/secrecy/2007/01/wikileaks_and_untraceable_docu.html |archive-date=11 March 2013}}</ref> WikiLeaks established a policy that only accepted only documents "of political, diplomatic, historical or ethical interest" (and excluded "material that is already publicly available").<ref>{{cite web |title=WikiLeaks' submissions page |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks:Submissions |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419013425/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks%3ASubmissions |archive-date=19 April 2008 |access-date=17 June 2010 |publisher=WikiLeaks}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} Under the new policy, submissions are reviewed by anonymous WikiLeaks reviewers, and documents that do not meet the editorial criteria are rejected. By 2008, the revised FAQ stated: "Anybody can post comments to it. [...] Users can publicly discuss documents and analyse their credibility and veracity."<ref>{{cite web |year=2008 |title=What is Wikileaks? How does Wikileaks operate? |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks:About#What_is_Wikileaks.3F_How_does_Wikileaks_operate.3F |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504122032/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks%3AAbout |archive-date=4 May 2008 |website=WikiLeaks}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} After the 2010 reorganisation, posting new comments on leaks was no longer possible.<ref name="wikigone">{{cite news |last=Gilson |first=Dave |date=19 May 2010 |title=WikiLeaks Gets A Facelift |work=Mother Jones |place=San Francisco |url=http://motherjones.com/mojo/2010/05/wikileaks-assange-returns |url-status=live |access-date=17 June 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429130452/http://www.motherjones.com/mojo/2010/05/wikileaks-assange-returns |archive-date=29 April 2014}}</ref><ref name="Radio Berkman 171" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Harrison |first=Stephen |date=9 May 2019 |title=WikiLeaks Is Not a Wiki |language=en-US |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |url=https://slate.com/technology/2019/05/wikileaks-not-wiki-wikipedia.html |access-date=9 July 2023 |issn=1091-2339 |archive-date=11 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711013640/https://slate.com/technology/2019/05/wikileaks-not-wiki-wikipedia.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

According to Zuckerman, the second stage was "an [[advocacy journalism]] phase". Zuckerman gave the 2010 release of [[July 12, 2007, Baghdad airstrike|Collateral Murder]] as an example, which ''[[MIT Technology Review]]'' described as a "highly curated, produced and packaged political statement ... meant to illustrate a political point of view, not merely to inform". Zuckerman said the third stage involved WikiLeaks working with outside media outlets to curate cables for release.<ref name="MIT Technology Review" /><ref name="Radio Berkman 171" /> In December 2010, Zuckerman speculated that the next stage would be for WikiLeaks to release documents all at once or without redacting them.<ref name="Radio Berkman 171" /> In 2016, Assange said that "often it's the case that we have to do a lot of exploration and [[marketing]] of the material we publish ourselves to get a big political impact for it".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Savage |first=Charlie |date=26 July 2016 |title=Assange, Avowed Foe of Clinton, Timed Email Release for Democratic Convention |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/us/politics/assange-timed-wikileaks-release-of-democratic-emails-to-harm-hillary-clinton.html |access-date=1 November 2023 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=8 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308182211/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/us/politics/assange-timed-wikileaks-release-of-democratic-emails-to-harm-hillary-clinton.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

An [[News embargo|embargo agreement]] WikiLeaks made for the Stratfor leak aimed to ensure that media organisations in smaller countries with less resources that are collaborating with WikiLeaks got a fair shot at covering the stories that involve their country. ''[[The Atlantic]]'' suggested that the complexity of the embargo had been a source of confusion among media partners.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hudson |first1=John |title=WikiLeaks' Elaborate Embargo on the Stratfor Emails |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/02/wikileaks-elaborate-embargo-stratfor-emails/331179/ |work=[[The Atlantic]] |publisher=Atlantic Monthly Group |date=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126195439/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/02/wikileaks-elaborate-embargo-stratfor-emails/331179/|archive-date=26 January 2021|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> In 2017, WikiLeaks told ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' that it sometimes scheduled releases around high-profile events.<ref name="McLaughlin-2017" />

In response to a question in 2010 about whether WikiLeaks would release information that he knew might get someone killed, Assange said that he had instituted a "harm-minimization policy". This meant that people named in some documents might be contacted before publication, but that there were also instances where members of WikiLeaks might have "blood on our hands."<ref name="Khatchdourian" /> One member of WikiLeaks told ''[[The New Yorker]]'' they were initially uncomfortable with Assange's editorial policy but changed her mind because she thought no one had been unjustly harmed.<ref name="Khatchdourian" />

==== Response ====
In an August 2010 open letter, the non-governmental organisation [[Reporters Without Borders]] praised WikiLeaks' past usefulness in exposing "serious violations of human rights and civil liberties" but criticised the organisation over a perceived absence of editorial control.<ref name="RSF-Julliard-2010b">{{Cite web |title=Reporters Sans Frontières – Open letter to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange: ''A bad precedent for the Internet's future'' |url=http://en.rsf.org/united-states-open-letter-to-wikileaks-founder-12-08-2010,38130.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328200448/http://en.rsf.org/united-states-open-letter-to-wikileaks-founder-12-08-2010%2C38130.html |archive-date=28 March 2014 |access-date=1 December 2010 |publisher=En.rsf.org}}</ref>

In a 2013 resolution, the [[International Federation of Journalists]], a trade union of journalists, called WikiLeaks a "new breed of media organisation".<ref>{{cite web |date=16 July 2013 |title=Global journalists' union supports Wikileaks |url=http://www.alliance.org.au/global-journalists-union-supports-wikileaks |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231025031/http://www.alliance.org.au/global-journalists-union-supports-wikileaks |archive-date=31 December 2013 |access-date=2 March 2014 |publisher=Alliance.org.au}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=4 October 2021 |title=What have been the biggest revelations to come from WikiLeaks? |url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/wikileaks-julian-assange-most-controversial-leaks-anniversary-2006-132213960.html |access-date=3 July 2024 |website=Yahoo News |language=en-AU |archive-date=29 November 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241129225929/https://au.news.yahoo.com/wikileaks-julian-assange-most-controversial-leaks-anniversary-2006-132213960.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Others do not consider WikiLeaks to be journalistic in nature. Media ethicist [[Kelly McBride]] of the [[Poynter Institute for Media Studies]] wrote in 2011: "WikiLeaks might grow into a journalist endeavor. But it's not there yet."<ref name="KMcBride">Kelly McBride, "What Is WikiLeaks? That's the Wrong Question" in ''Page One: Inside the New York Times and the Future of Journalism'' (documentary film, ed. [[David Folkenflik]]: PublicAffairs, 2011).</ref> [[Bill Keller]] of ''The New York Times'' considers WikiLeaks to be a "complicated source" rather than a journalistic partner.<ref name="KMcBride" /> Prominent [[First Amendment]] lawyer [[Floyd Abrams]] writes that WikiLeaks is not a journalistic organisation, but instead "an organization of political activists; ... a source for journalists; and ... a conduit of leaked information to the press and the public".<ref name="Abrams">[[Floyd Abrams]], ''Friend of the Court: On the Front Lines with the First Amendment'' (Yale University Press, 2013), p. 390.</ref>

=== Financing ===
WikiLeaks is a [[not-for-profit organisation]]{{refn|name=intNP}} and is funded by private donations, exclusivity contracts<ref name="leakonomy" /> and concessions from their media partners.<ref name="Assange-2011">{{Cite web |last=Assange |first=Julian |date=30 November 2011 |title=WikiLeaks Secrets and Lies Julian Assange Interview Transcript |url=https://file.wikileaks.org/file/cms/Folder%203/WIKILEAKS%20SECRETS%20AND%20LIES%20JULIAN%20ASSANGE%20INTERVIEWTRANSCRIPT.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210110174630/https://file.wikileaks.org/file/cms/Folder%203/WIKILEAKS%20SECRETS%20AND%20LIES%20JULIAN%20ASSANGE%20INTERVIEWTRANSCRIPT.pdf |archive-date=10 January 2021 |access-date=11 November 2022 |website=WikiLeaks}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref> Assange has said that in some cases legal aid has been donated by media organisations such as the [[Associated Press]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', and the [[National Newspaper Publishers Association]].<ref name="leakonomy" /> Assange said in early 2010 that WikiLeaks' only revenue consists of donations, but it has considered other options including auctioning early access to documents.<ref name="leakonomy" /> In September 2010, Assange said that WikiLeaks received millions of dollars in media partnerships, stating it "win[s] concessions in relation to the number of journalists that will be put on it and how big they'll run with it."<ref name="Assange-2011" />

In 2010, Assange said the organisation was registered as a library in Australia, a foundation in France, and a newspaper in Sweden, and that it also used two US-based non-profit [[501c3]] organisations for funding purposes.<ref>{{cite news |date=23 August 2015 |title=How WikiLeaks Keeps Its Funding Secret |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704554104575436231926853198 |access-date=3 February 2015 |archive-date=4 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204005113/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704554104575436231926853198 |url-status=live }}</ref> According to Daniel Domscheit-Berg, Assange registered Wikileaks ICT in Australia and would not tell anyone how much money was in the Australian fund or what it was being spent on.<ref name="Fow20Traf" />

==== 2010–2013 ====
The [[Wau Holland Foundation]], one of the WikiLeaks' main funding channels, stated that it received more than €900,000 in public donations between October 2009 and December 2010, of which €370,000 has been passed on to WikiLeaks. Hendrik Fulda, vice-president of the Wau Holland Foundation, said that every new WikiLeaks publication brought "a wave of support", and that donations were strongest in the weeks after WikiLeaks started publishing leaked diplomatic cables.<ref name="spiegel131210" /><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Horton |first=Scott |date=6 August 2010 |title=Financing WikiLeaks |magazine=Harper's Magazine |place=New York |url=http://www.harpers.org/archive/2010/08/hbc-90007485 |url-status=live |access-date=15 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019211817/http://harpers.org/archive/2010/08/hbc-90007485 |archive-date=19 October 2012}}</ref> According to Assange, WikiLeaks' media partnerships for the cables earned them almost $2 million three months after it started publishing.<ref name="Assange-2011" /> WikiLeaks was paid £150,000 by [[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]] and [[Channel 4]] for two five-minute video clips about the [[Iraq War documents leak|Iraq War Logs]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 February 2011 |title=Inside WikiLeaks: Former Insider Spills The Beans |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/inside-wikileaks-former-i_n_823502 |access-date=2 May 2023 |website=[[HuffPost]] |language=en |archive-date=2 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230502092615/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/inside-wikileaks-former-i_n_823502 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011a">{{Cite book |last=Domscheit-Berg |first=Daniel |title=Inside Wikileaks : my time with Julian Assange at the world's most dangerous website |date=2011 |publisher=Crown Publishers |others=Tina Klopp, Jefferson S. Chase |isbn=978-0-307-95191-5 |location=New York |oclc=701412231 }}</ref> In December 2010, Assange said that WikiLeaks received €100,000 a day at its peak<ref>{{Cite news |last=Harding |first=Luke |date=23 December 2010 |title=Julian Assange: my fate will rest in Cameron's hands if US charges me |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/23/julian-assange-fate-david-cameron |access-date=6 February 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=6 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206105525/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/23/julian-assange-fate-david-cameron |url-status=live }}</ref> and the Wau Holland Foundation stated that Julian Assange and three other permanent employees had begun to receive salaries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wikileaks donations still flowing, but not to Assange legal fund |work=The Local |place=Berlin |url=http://m.thelocal.de/sci-tech/20101223-31975.html |url-status=dead |access-date=23 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002143644/http://m.thelocal.de/sci-tech/20101223-31975.html |archive-date=2 October 2013}}</ref>

During 2010, WikiLeaks received over $1.9 million in donations.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=WikiLeaks Donations Topped $1.9 Million in 2010 |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/04/wau-holland-report/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |access-date=23 September 2022 |archive-date=26 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220626110857/https://www.wired.com/2011/04/wau-holland-report/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2011 donations dropped sharply and WikiLeaks received only around $180,000 in donations, while their expenses increased from $519,000 to $850,000.<ref name="Zetter-1059">{{Cite magazine |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=WikiLeaks Donations Down to a Trickle |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/05/wikileaks-donations-down/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |access-date=23 September 2022 |archive-date=23 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220923191830/https://www.wired.com/2013/05/wikileaks-donations-down/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Al Jazeera offered WikiLeaks $1.3 million for access to data.<ref name="O'Hagan-2014"/> During September 2011 WikiLeaks began auctioning items on [[eBay]] to raise funds.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hayes |first=Isabel |date=30 September 2011 |title=Wikileaks is a leaking boat: Assange |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/wikileaks-is-a-leaking-boat-assange-20111001-1l1yd.html |access-date=13 May 2021 |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |language=en |archive-date=13 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210513230146/https://www.smh.com.au/national/wikileaks-is-a-leaking-boat-assange-20111001-1l1yd.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Wikileaks started accepting bitcoin in 2011 as a currency which could not be blocked by financial institutions or a government.<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – PayPal freezes WikiLeaks donations |url=https://wikileaks.org/PayPal-freezes-WikiLeaks-donations.html |website=wikileaks.org |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=14 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221014212223/https://wikileaks.org/PayPal-freezes-WikiLeaks-donations.html |url-status=live }}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Matonis |first=Jon |title=WikiLeaks Bypasses Financial Blockade With Bitcoin |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonmatonis/2012/08/20/wikileaks-bypasses-financial-blockade-with-bitcoin/ |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052039/https://www.forbes.com/sites/jonmatonis/2012/08/20/wikileaks-bypasses-financial-blockade-with-bitcoin/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Huang |first=Roger |title=How Bitcoin And WikiLeaks Saved Each Other |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rogerhuang/2019/04/26/how-bitcoin-and-wikileaks-saved-each-other/ |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103195202/https://www.forbes.com/sites/rogerhuang/2019/04/26/how-bitcoin-and-wikileaks-saved-each-other/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2012, WikiLeaks raised $68,000 through the Wau Holland Foundation and had expenses more than $507,000.<ref name="Zetter-1059" /> Between January and May, Wau Holland Foundation was only able to cover $47,000 in essential infrastructure for WikiLeaks, but not an additional $400,000 that was submitted "to cover publishing campaigns and logistics in 2012".<ref name="Zetter-1059" />

[[David Allen Green]] wrote in ''[[New Statesman|The New Statesman]]'' in 2011 that there was "no other sensible way of interpreting" leaked [[non-disclosure agreement]]s other than WikliLeaks seeing itself "as a [[commercial organisation]] in the business of owning and selling leaked information". [[Becky Hogge]], who had signed the agreement, wrote that "the NDA certainly is poorly drafted, and it may be terrible PR. But remember that WikiLeaks is an organisation conceived and run by computer hackers" and suggested that WikiLeaks was attempting to "engage with the commercial media on its own terms".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Green |first=David Allen |date=11 May 2011 |title=The £12m question: how WikiLeaks gags its own staff |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/2011/05/wikileaks-information-legal |access-date=21 January 2024 |website=New Statesman |language=en-US |archive-date=23 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240123155308/https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/2011/05/wikileaks-information-legal |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hogge |first=Becky |date=16 May 2011 |title=Why I signed the WikiLeaks NDA |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2011/05/wikileaks-organisation-order |access-date=21 January 2024 |website=New Statesman |language=en-US |archive-date=25 September 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230925110247/https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2011/05/wikileaks-organisation-order |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Financial blockade ====
{{see also|Reception of WikiLeaks#Response from the financial industry|Operation Payback#Operation Avenge Assange}}

On 22 January 2010, the Internet payment intermediary [[PayPal]] suspended WikiLeaks' account and froze its assets. WikiLeaks said that this had happened before, and was done for "no obvious reason".<ref name="WillRegJan10">{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Christopher |date=25 January 2010 |title=Wikileaks pledge drive hobbled by PayPal suspension |language=en |work=[[The Register]] |publisher=Situation Publishing |url=https://www.theregister.com/2010/01/25/wikileaks_paypal/ |access-date=24 November 2019 |archive-date=9 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201109041553/https://www.theregister.com/2010/01/25/wikileaks_paypal/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|number=8101847372|user=wikileaks|title=Paypal has again locked our donation account for no obvious reason. We need an alternative to this arbitrary freezing of assets.|author=WikiLeaks|author-link=WikiLeaks|date=23 January 2010|access-date=19 March 2022|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220220030322/https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/8101847372|archive-date=20 February 2022|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2010, the internet payment company [[Moneybookers]] closed WikiLeaks' account and sent Assange letters saying the account was closed following an audit "to comply with money laundering or other investigations conducted by government authorities." According to Moneybookers, initially the "account was suspended due to being accessed from a blacklisted IP address. However, following recent publicity and the subsequently addition of the WikiLeaks entity to blacklists in Australia and watchlists in the USA, we have terminated the business relationship."<ref name="Leigh-2010">{{Cite news |last1=Leigh |first1=David |last2=Evans |first2=Rob |date=14 October 2010 |title=WikiLeaks says funding has been blocked after government blacklisting |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/oct/14/wikileaks-says-funding-is-blocked |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=5 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190905023834/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/oct/14/wikileaks-says-funding-is-blocked |url-status=live }}</ref> The blacklisting came a few days after the Pentagon expressed anger at WikiLeaks for publishing the [[United States documents leak of the War in Afghanistan|Afghan War logs]].<ref name="Leigh-2010" />

In December 2010, PayPal suspended WikiLeaks' account. PayPal said it had taken action after the [[US State Department]] sent a letter to Wikileaks stating that Wikileaks' activities were illegal in the US.<ref name="bbc0812102" /> Hendrik Fulda, vice-president of the Wau Holland Foundation, said that the Foundation had been receiving twice as many donations through PayPal as through normal banks before PayPal's decision to suspend WikiLeaks' account.<ref name="spiegel131210">{{cite news |date=13 December 2010 |title=Donations Were Never as Strong as Now |work=Spiegel International |place=Hamburg |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,734318,00.html |url-status=live |access-date=15 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715205752/http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0%2C1518%2C734318%2C00.html |archive-date=15 July 2011}}</ref> In this time, [[Mastercard]], [[Visa Inc.#Visa Europe|Visa Europe]], [[Bank of America]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Western Union]] and Swiss bank [[PostFinance]] stopped dealing with WikiLeaks. Datacell, the IT company that enabled WikiLeaks to accept credit and debit card donations, threatened Mastercard and Visa with legal action to enforce the resumption of payments to WikiLeaks. Datacell said Visa's action was the result of political pressure.<ref name="bbc0812102" /><ref name="wired0712122" />

In October 2011 Assange said that the financial blockade had cost WikiLeaks ninety-five per cent of its revenue.<ref name="reuters241011">{{cite news |last1=Holden |first1=Michael |date=24 October 2011 |title=WikiLeaks says "blockade" threatens its existence |language=en |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-wikileaks/wikileaks-says-blockade-threatens-its-existence-idUSTRE79N46K20111024 |access-date=22 June 2021 |archive-date=24 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624203111/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-wikileaks/wikileaks-says-blockade-threatens-its-existence-idUSTRE79N46K20111024 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2012, an Icelandic district court ruled that [[Valitor]], the Icelandic partner of [[Visa Inc.|Visa]] and [[MasterCard]], was violating the law when it stopped accepting donations to WikiLeaks and that donations to WikiLeaks must resume within 14 days or Valitor would be fined US$6,000 a day.<ref name="wired0712122" /> In November 2012, the European Union's [[European Commission]] said Mastercard and Visa were unlikely to have violated EU anti-trust rules.<ref>{{Cite news |agency=Press Association |date=27 November 2012 |title=Julian Assange expresses surprise over EU WikiLeaks decision |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/27/julian-assange-eu-wikileaks-decision |access-date=7 April 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052520/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/nov/27/julian-assange-eu-wikileaks-decision |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2013, Assange said the blockade also effected the [[WikiLeaks Party]].<ref>{{Cite news |date=8 September 2013 |title=Assange vows to stand again for fledgling WikiLeaks Party |language=en-AU |work=ABC News |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-09-08/assange/4944532 |access-date=20 October 2023 |archive-date=12 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231112155314/https://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-09-08/assange/4944532 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In response to the financial blockade of Wikileaks, [[Glenn Greenwald]] and others created the [[Freedom of the Press Foundation]] "to block the US government from ever again being able to attack and suffocate an independent journalistic enterprise the way it did with WikiLeaks".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwald |first1=Glenn |date=17 December 2012 |title=New press freedom group is launched to block US government attacks {{!}} Glenn Greenwald |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/dec/17/wikileaks-new-press-freedom-group |access-date=29 October 2022 |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en |archive-date=26 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220126055526/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2012/dec/17/wikileaks-new-press-freedom-group |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Anonymous (hacker group)|Anonymous]] also launched a [[Operation Payback#Operation Avenge Assange|series of cyberattacks]] against companies that cut ties with WikiLeaks.<ref name="Weaver-2010" /><ref name="Addley-2010" />

==== 2014–2018 ====
In 2014, [[Sunshine Press Productions]] [[Ehf.|ehf]] began receiving funds from Wau Holland Foundation for WikiLeaks.<ref name="Wau Holland Foundation">{{Cite web |title=Jahresbericht 2014 |url=https://www.wauland.de/media/2014_Jahresbericht.pdf |website=Wau Holland Foundation |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=2 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230502155849/https://www.wauland.de/media/2014_Jahresbericht.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> From 2014 to 2017 WikiLeaks was reimbursed for project coordination, technical preparation, removing metadata, reviewing information, communicating with media partners costs and a new submission platform and document search.<ref name="Wau Holland Foundation" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Jahresbericht 2015 der Wau-Holland-Stiftung |url=https://www.wauland.de/media/2015_Jahresbericht.pdf |website=Wau Holland Foundation |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=30 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230530162910/https://www.wauland.de/media/2015_Jahresbericht.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Jahresbericht 2016 der Holland Stiftung |url=https://www.wauland.de/media/2016-12-31_jahresbericht.pdf |website=Wau Holland Foundation |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=1 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230601013654/https://www.wauland.de/media/2016-12-31_jahresbericht.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Jahresbericht 2017 der Wau Holland Stiftung |url=https://www.wauland.de/media/2017-12-31-jahresbericht.pdf |website=Wau Holland Foundation |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=31 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230531071656/https://www.wauland.de/media/2017-12-31-jahresbericht.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[2016 Democratic National Committee email leak|DNC emails]] and [[Podesta emails]] were not funded by the Wau Holland Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Statement on WikiLeaks in Project Area 'Freedom of Information' – Wau Holland Stiftung |url=https://wauland.de/en/news/2017/12/statement-on-wikileaks-in-project-area-freedom-of-information/ |access-date=7 April 2023 |website=wauland.de |archive-date=7 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230407190003/https://wauland.de/en/news/2017/12/statement-on-wikileaks-in-project-area-freedom-of-information/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In October 2017, Julian Assange said WikiLeaks had made a 50,000% return on [[Bitcoin]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kharpal |first=Arjun |date=16 October 2017 |title=WikiLeaks founder Assange claims he made 50,000% return on bitcoin thanks to the US government |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/16/wikileaks-julian-assange-bitcoin-50000-percent-return-thanks-to-us-government.html |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=[[CNBC]] |language=en |archive-date=13 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313165548/https://www.cnbc.com/2017/10/16/wikileaks-julian-assange-bitcoin-50000-percent-return-thanks-to-us-government.html |url-status=live }}</ref> By that December, it had raised at least $25 million in Bitcoin.<ref name="Nakashima-2018">{{Cite news |title=A German hacker offers a rare look inside the secretive world of Julian Assange and WikiLeaks |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-german-hacker-offers-a-rare-look-inside-the-secretive-world-of-julian-assange-and-wikileaks/2018/01/17/e6211180-f311-11e7-b390-a36dc3fa2842_story.html |access-date=21 March 2022 |issn=0190-8286 |archive-date=23 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423073658/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-german-hacker-offers-a-rare-look-inside-the-secretive-world-of-julian-assange-and-wikileaks/2018/01/17/e6211180-f311-11e7-b390-a36dc3fa2842_story.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2018, the Wau Holland Foundation reimbursed Sunshine Press Productions for WikiLeaks' publications, as well as public relations and $50,000 for legal expenses in the [[Democratic National Committee v. Russian Federation]] lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jahresbericht 2018 der Wau Holland Stiftung |url=https://www.wauland.de/media/2018-12-31-jahresbericht.pdf |website=Wau Holland Foundation |access-date=7 April 2023 |archive-date=31 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230531014326/https://www.wauland.de/media/2018-12-31-jahresbericht.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Hosting ===

In 2010, the website was available on multiple servers, different [[domain name]]s and had an official [[dark web]] version as a result of a number of [[denial-of-service attack]]s and its removal from different [[Domain Name System]] (DNS) providers.<ref name="satter">{{cite news |last1=Satter |first1=Raphael G. |first2=Peter |last2=Svensson |date=3 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks fights to stay online amid attacks |work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9JSHKUG0.htm |access-date=14 March 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204043730/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9JSHKUG0.htm |archive-date=4 December 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Randall |first1=David |last2=Cooper |first2=Charlie |date=5 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks hit by new online onslaught |work=[[The Independent]] |place=London |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/wikileaks-hit-by-new-online-onslaught-2151570.html |url-status=dead |access-date=4 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419020654/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/wikileaks-hit-by-new-online-onslaught-2151570.html |archive-date=19 April 2014}}</ref>

Until August 2010, WikiLeaks was hosted by [[PRQ]], a Swedish company providing "highly secure, no-questions-asked hosting services". PRQ was reported by ''[[The Register]]'' to have "almost no information about its clientele and maintains few if any of its own [[server log|logs]]".<ref name="goodwin">{{cite news |author=Goodwin, Dan |date=21 February 2008 |title=Wikileaks<!-- sic! --> judge gets Pirate Bay treatment |work=The Register |place=London |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/02/21/wikileaks_bulletproof_hosting/ |access-date=7 December 2010 |archive-date=17 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017024609/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/02/21/wikileaks_bulletproof_hosting/ |url-status=live }}</ref> That month, WikiLeaks reached an agreement with the [[Pirate Party (Sweden)|Swedish Pirate Party]] to host several of their servers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=AFP |date=17 August 2010 |title=WikiLeaks gets new host – Swedish pirates |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i6FrU92zArUG-oCoogmmdIrU9c4g |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821093357/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5i6FrU92zArUG-oCoogmmdIrU9c4g |archive-date=21 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Fung |first=Brian |title=It's official: WikiLeaks and Sweden's Pirate Party ink a hosting deal |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2010/08/17/its-official-wikileaks-and-swedens-pirate-party-ink-a-hosting-deal/ |access-date=16 April 2023 |website=Foreign Policy |date=17 August 2010 |language=en-US |archive-date=16 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230416175440/https://foreignpolicy.com/2010/08/17/its-official-wikileaks-and-swedens-pirate-party-ink-a-hosting-deal/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Pirate Party Strikes Hosting Deal With Wikileaks * TorrentFreak |url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-party-strikes-hosting-deal-with-wikileaks-100817/ |access-date=16 April 2023 |language=en |archive-date=16 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230416175441/https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-party-strikes-hosting-deal-with-wikileaks-100817/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Later, WikiLeaks was hosted mainly by the Swedish Internet service provider [[Bahnhof]] in the [[Pionen]] facility, a former nuclear bunker in Sweden.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 August 2010 |title=Pentagon-papirer sikret i atom-bunker |language=no |work=[[VG Nett]] |place=Oslo |url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10018210 |url-status=live |access-date=6 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922042634/http://www.vg.no/nyheter/utenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10018210 |archive-date=22 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |date=30 August 2010 |title=Wikileaks<!-- sic! --> Servers Move To Underground Nuclear Bunker |work=[[Forbes]] (blog) |url=https://blogs.forbes.com/andygreenberg/2010/08/30/wikileaks-servers-move-to-underground-nuclear-bunker/?boxes=businesschanneltopstories |access-date=6 December 2010 |archive-date=22 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222021018/http://blogs.forbes.com/andygreenberg/2010/08/30/wikileaks-servers-move-to-underground-nuclear-bunker/?boxes=businesschanneltopstories |url-status=live }}</ref> Other servers were spread around the world with the main server located in Sweden.<ref name="DN1">{{cite news |author=Fredén, Jonas |date=14 August 2010 |title=Jagad och hatad&nbsp;– men han vägrar vika sig |language=sv |trans-title=Chased and hated&nbsp;– but he refuses to give way |work=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |place=Stockholm |url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/jagad-och-hatad-men-han-vagrar-vika-sig/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100818113905/http://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/jagad-och-hatad-men-han-vagrar-vika-sig-1.1153725 |archive-date=18 August 2010}}</ref>

After the site became the target of a [[denial-of-service attack]], WikiLeaks moved its website to [[Amazon.com|Amazon]]'s servers.<ref name="amazon2"/> Amazon later removed the website.<ref name="amazon2"/> Assange said that WikiLeaks chose Amazon and other hosts knowing it would probably be kicked off the service "to separate rhetoric from reality".<ref name="amazon2"/><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks got kicked off Amazon on purpose, says Assange |url=https://www.cnet.com/tech/mobile/wikileaks-got-kicked-off-amazon-on-purpose-says-assange/ |access-date=23 October 2023 |website=CNET |language=en |archive-date=1 November 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231101041152/https://www.cnet.com/tech/mobile/wikileaks-got-kicked-off-amazon-on-purpose-says-assange/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=3 December 2010 |title=Julian Assange answers your questions |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2010/dec/03/julian-assange-wikileaks |access-date=23 October 2023 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=9 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161209090137/https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2010/dec/03/julian-assange-wikileaks |url-status=live }}</ref>  In a public statement, Amazon said WikiLeaks was not following its terms of service. The company stated: <blockquote>There were several parts they were violating. For example, our terms of service state that 'you represent and warrant that you own or otherwise control all of the rights to the content ... that use of the content you supply does not violate this policy and will not cause injury to any person or entity.' It's clear that WikiLeaks doesn't own or otherwise control all the rights to this classified content.<ref name="Hennigan2"/></blockquote> WikiLeaks then moved to servers at French provider [[OVH]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Poncet, Guerric |date=3 December 2010 |title=Expulsé d'Amazon, WikiLeaks trouve refuge en France |language=fr |work=[[Le Point]] |place=Paris |url=http://www.lepoint.fr/high-tech-internet/expulse-d-amazon-wikileaks-s-installe-en-france-02-12-2010-1270137_47.php |access-date=2 December 2010 |archive-date=18 October 2017 |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20171018074956/http://www.lepoint.fr/high-tech-internet/expulse-d-amazon-wikileaks-trouve-refuge-en-france-02-12-2010-1270137_47.php |url-status=live }}</ref> After criticism from the French government, a judge in Paris ruled that there was no need for OVH to cease hosting WikiLeaks without more information.<ref>{{Cite web |date=6 December 2010 |title=French web host need not shut down WikiLeaks site: judge |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iojKm00N9vMvjVGwO2ZNko9rVpBw?docId=CNG.3c86e1065eee2cfd740284f4a84f3555.121 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130103041304/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iojKm00N9vMvjVGwO2ZNko9rVpBw?docId=CNG.3c86e1065eee2cfd740284f4a84f3555.121 |archive-date=3 January 2013 |access-date=7 September 2019 |website=[[Agence France-Presse|Agence France-Presse (AFP)]]}}</ref>

WikiLeaks was dropped by [[EveryDNS]] after distributed denial-of-service ([[DDoS]]) attacks against WikiLeaks hurt the quality of service for its other customers. Supporters of WikiLeaks waged verbal and DDoS attacks on EveryDNS. Because of a typographical error in blogs mistaking EveryDNS for competitor ''[[EasyDNS]]'', the sizeable Internet backlash hit EasyDNS. Despite that, EasyDNS began providing WikiLeaks with DNS service on "two 'battle hardened' servers" to protect the quality of service for its other customers.<ref name="Ladurantaye"/>

=== Insurance files ===
WikiLeaks has used heavily encrypted files<ref name="Booth-2010">{{Cite news |last=Booth |first=Robert |date=7 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks to keep releasing cables despite Assange arrest |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/07/wikileaks-cables-julian-assange-arrest |access-date=9 February 2023 |issn=0261-3077 |archive-date=29 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240529052511/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/07/wikileaks-cables-julian-assange-arrest |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=15 December 2010 |title='insurance.aes256', Julian Assange's contingency plan |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20101215-insuranceaes256-julian-assange-contingency-plan-life-insurance-wikileaks |access-date=9 February 2023 |website=France 24 |language=en |archive-date=9 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230209183811/https://www.france24.com/en/20101215-insuranceaes256-julian-assange-contingency-plan-life-insurance-wikileaks |url-status=live }}</ref> to protect their publications against censorship,<ref name="Stockley-2013">{{Cite web |date=20 August 2013 |title=What's Wikileaks hiding in its 400GB of 'insurance' files? |url=https://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2013/08/20/whats-wikileaks-hiding-in-its-400gb-of-insurance-files/ |access-date=9 February 2023 |website=Naked Security |language=en-US |archive-date=9 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230209183813/https://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2013/08/20/whats-wikileaks-hiding-in-its-400gb-of-insurance-files/ |url-status=live }}</ref> to pre-release publications,<ref name="News.au-2017">{{Cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=WikiLeaks password is an anti-CIA JFK quote |url=https://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/wikileaks-password-is-an-anticia-jfk-quote/news-story/d6c1cc5385c4f1330bb87f1be2ecefa3 |website=News.au.com |access-date=9 February 2023 |archive-date=12 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221012142726/https://www.news.com.au/finance/work/leaders/wikileaks-password-is-an-anticia-jfk-quote/news-story/d6c1cc5385c4f1330bb87f1be2ecefa3 |url-status=live }}</ref> and as protection against arrest.<ref name="Keller-2011">{{Cite news |last=Keller |first=Bill |date=26 January 2011 |title=Dealing With Assange and the WikiLeaks Secrets |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/30/magazine/30Wikileaks-t.html |access-date=9 February 2023 |issn=0362-4331 |archive-date=8 September 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/30/magazine/30Wikileaks-t.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="Rosenberg-2011">{{Cite web |date=30 January 2011 |title=Spotlight: NYT Chief on Wikileaks Saga {{!}} The Atlantic Wire |url=http://www.theatlanticwire.com/opinions/view/opinion/Spotlight-NYT-Chief-on-Wikileaks-Saga-6730 |access-date=9 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130074412/http://www.theatlanticwire.com/opinions/view/opinion/Spotlight-NYT-Chief-on-Wikileaks-Saga-6730 |archive-date=30 January 2011 }}</ref> The files have been described as "insurance",<ref name="Booth-2010" /><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=WikiLeaks Posts Mysterious 'Insurance' File |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/07/wikileaks-insurance-file/ |access-date=9 February 2023 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks' 'insurance' file aimed at ensuring work goes on |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/wbna40512398 |access-date=9 February 2023 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=5 December 2010 |language=en}}</ref> a "[[dead man's switch]]",<ref name="Stockley-2013" /> "a kind of doomsday option",<ref name="Keller-2011" /><ref name="Rosenberg-2011" /> and a "poison pill".<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 February 2014 |title=Assange ready to unleash tide of new secrets {{!}} The Sunday Times |website=[[The Sunday Times]] |url=https://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/National/article470338.ece |access-date=9 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227120524/https://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/uk_news/National/article470338.ece |archive-date=27 February 2014 }}</ref> The insurance files sometimes come with [[Commitment scheme|pre-commitment hashes]].<ref name="Swearingen-2023">{{Cite web |last=Swearingen |first=Jake |title=Something Weird (or Weirder Than Normal) Is Happening at WikiLeaks |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/11/wikileak-hashes-dont-match-so-whats-going-on.html |access-date=9 February 2023 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York Intelligencer]] |date=16 November 2016 |language=en-us}}</ref>

WikiLeaks staff have said: <blockquote>insurance files are encrypted copies of unpublished documents submitted to us. We do this periodically, and especially at moments of high pressure on us, to ensure the documents can not be lost and history preserved. You will not be able to see the contents of any of our insurance files, until and unless the we are in a position where we must release the key. But you can download them and help spread them to ensure their safe keeping.<ref>{{Cite web |last=WikiLeaks staff |date=10 November 2016 |title=WikiLeaks staff AMA |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IAmA/comments/5c8u9l/comment/d9ukayp/?context=3 |website=Reddit}}</ref></blockquote>

On 29 July 2010 WikiLeaks added an [[Advanced Encryption Standard|AES]] encrypted "Insurance file" to the Afghan War Diary page.<ref name="wired_insurance" /> There has been speculation that it was intended to serve as insurance in case the WikiLeaks website or its spokesman Julian Assange are incapacitated, upon which the [[passphrase]] could be published.<ref name="wired_insurance">{{cite news |last=Zetter |first=Kim |date=30 July 2010 |title=WikiLeaks Posts Mysterious 'Insurance' File |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |place=New York |url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/07/wikileaks-insurance-file/ |url-status=live |access-date=11 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004083509/http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/07/wikileaks-insurance-file/ |archive-date=4 October 2012}}</ref><ref name="telegraph_dns_insuranceaes">{{cite news |last=Ward |first=Victoria |date=3 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks website disconnected as US company withdraws support |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |place=London |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/wikileaks/8178457/WikiLeaks-website-disconnected-as-US-company-withdraws-support.html |url-status=live |access-date=3 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204064107/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/wikileaks/8178457/WikiLeaks-website-disconnected-as-US-company-withdraws-support.html |archive-date=4 December 2010}}</ref> After the release of the [[United States diplomatic cables leak|US diplomatic cables]], [[CBS]] predicted that "If anything happens to Assange or the website, a key will go out to unlock the files. There would then be no way to stop the information from spreading like wildfire because so many people already have copies."<ref name="cbsnews_diplomaticbomb">{{cite news |last=Palmer |first=Elizabeth |date=2 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks Backup Plan Could Drop Diplomatic Bomb |work=[[CBS]] News |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/wikileaks-backup-plan-could-drop-diplomatic-bomb/ |url-status=live |access-date=3 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203205140/http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/12/02/eveningnews/main7111845.shtml |archive-date=3 December 2010}}</ref> Assange's lawyer, [[Mark Stephens (solicitor)|Mark Stephens]], called the files "a thermo-nuclear device in the information age" and said they included information on Guantanamo Bay, aerial video of a U.S. airstrike in Afghanistan that allegedly killed civilians, BP reports and Bank of America documents.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lind |first=Michael |date=22 December 2010 |title=Yes, Julian Assange actually is a criminal |url=https://www.salon.com/2010/12/22/lind_wikileaks/ |website=[[Salon.com|Salon]]}}</ref>

In August 2013, WikiLeaks posted three insurance files as torrents, totalling 400 gigabytes.<ref name="Stockley-2013" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Szoldra |first=Paul |title=Wikileaks Just Released A Massive 'Insurance' File That No One Can Open |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/wikileaks-insurance-file-2013-8 |access-date=9 February 2023 |website=[[Business Insider]] |language=en-US}}</ref> WikiLeaks said it "encrypted versions of upcoming publication data ("insurance") from time to time to nullify attempts at [[prior restraint]]."<ref name="Stockley-2013" />

In June 2016, WikiLeaks posted an 88-gigabyte insurance file.<ref>{{Cite web |title=After Julian Assange's arrest, fate of 88GB 'insurance' files uncertain |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/world/2019/04/12/After-Julian-Assange-arrest-fate-of-88GB-insurance-files-uncertain.html |access-date=3 July 2024 |website=The Week |language=en}}</ref> On 16 October 2016, WikiLeaks tweeted an insurance file about Ecuador.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Casey |first1=Nicholas |last2=Becker |first2=Jo |date=12 April 2019 |title=As Ecuador Harbored Assange, It Was Subjected to Threats and Leaks |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/12/world/europe/ecuador-assange-wikileaks.html |access-date=10 February 2023 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In November, it posted insurance files for the US, the UK and Ecuador,<ref>{{Cite web |last=WikiLeaks |date=8 November 2016 |title=Download encrypted future WL publications for safekeeping |url=https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/796085225394536448 |access-date=10 February 2023 |website=[[Twitter]] |language=en}}</ref> and an unlabelled 90-gigabyte insurance file was posted.<ref name="Swearingen-2023" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Swearingen |first=Jake |date=16 November 2016 |title=Something Weird (or Weirder Than Normal) Is Happening at WikiLeaks |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/11/wikileak-hashes-dont-match-so-whats-going-on.html |access-date=3 July 2024 |website=Intelligencer |language=en}}</ref>

On 7 March 2017, WikiLeaks posted an encrypted file containing the [[Vault 7#Part 1 – "Year Zero"|Vault 7 Year Zero]] release.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 March 2017 |title=WikiLeaks promises to release 'huge' trove of documents in hours |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/tech/wikileaks-year-zero-vault-7-julian-assange-encrypted-release-twitter-download-a7615671.html |access-date=10 February 2023 |website=[[The Independent]] |language=en}}</ref> The password, "SplinterItIntoAThousandPiecesAndScatterItIntoTheWinds", was a reference to a quote by US President [[John F. Kennedy]].<ref name="News.au-2017" /><ref>{{cite book |editor-last1=Thompson |editor-first1=Antonio Scott |editor-last2=Frentzos |editor-first2=Christos G.|last=Renouard|first=Joe|title=The Routledge Handbook of American Military and Diplomatic History; 1865 to the Present |date=2013 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-415-88847-9|chapter=Eisenhower, Kennedy, and the CIA|pages=279–287 |url=https://www.routledge.com/The-Routledge-Handbook-of-American-Military-and-Diplomatic-History-186/Antonio-Thompson-Frentzos/p/book/9780415888479?_gl=1*kozm1u*_ga*MzYwMTY3OTA5LjE2OTY3NjQwNjY.*_ga_0HYE8YG0M6*MTY5NzExMDEwOC4yLjEuMTY5NzExMDU0NS4wLjAuMA|quote=Kennedy—unused to failure, and furious that planners had overestimated the chances of success—lost faith in the military and intelligence communities. He forced Allen Dulles and two deputy directors to resign, and he told an aide that he wanted to 'splinter the CIA in a thousand pieces and scatter it to the winds.'}}</ref>

=== Staff ===
In July 2010, it was reported the website had 800 occasional helpers.<ref name="The Sydney Morning Herald-2010">{{Cite web |date=15 July 2010 |title=Julian Assange: the whistleblower |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/julian-assange-the-whistleblower-20100715-10bkp.html |access-date=1 November 2023 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en}}</ref> According to [[Daniel Domscheit-Berg]], WikiLeaks exaggerated the number of volunteers and Assange used many [[pseudonym]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schoenfeld |first=Gabriel |title=Book Review: Inside WikiLeaks |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703584804576144182023423452 |access-date=2 May 2023 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=14 February 2011 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011a" /> Domscheit-Berg suggested that Assange may have been "Jay Lim", who identified online as an occasional WikiLeaks spokesperson and as its legal advisor.<ref name="Columbia Journalism Review">{{Cite web |title=Did Assange Play Lawyer? |url=https://www.cjr.org/behind_the_news/did_assange_play_lawyer.php |access-date=29 May 2023 |website=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011a" />

Daniel Domscheit-Berg, [[Sarah Harrison (journalist)|Sarah Harrison]], Kristinn Hrafnsson and Joseph Farrell have been involved in the project.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mostrous |first=Alexi |date=4 August 2011 |title=He came for a week and stayed a year |work=The Times |place=London |url=https://www.thetimes.com/article/he-came-for-a-week-and-stayed-a-year-8xxwcb323lj |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209164635/http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/life/article3114254.ece |archive-date=9 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="wikileaksrevolt" /> [[Gavin MacFadyen]] was acknowledged by Assange as a "beloved director of WikiLeaks" shortly after his death in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roberts |first1=Sam |date=28 October 2016 |title=Gavin MacFadyen, 76, Mentor and Defender of WikiLeaks Founder, Dies |website=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/28/business/media/gavin-macfadyen-dies-wikileaks.html |access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref> [[Jacob Appelbaum]] is the only known American member of WikiLeaks, acting as a senior editor and spokesman.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 August 2010 |title=Wikileaks editor interrogated by US border police |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/wikileaks-editor-interrogated-by-us-border-police-2041235.html |access-date=19 March 2023 |website=[[The Independent]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Rich |first=Nathaniel |date=1 December 2010 |title=The American Wikileaks Hacker |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/the-american-wikileaks-hacker-238019/ |access-date=19 March 2023 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=2 December 2010 |title=Meet the Most Dangerous Man in Cyberspace: The American Behind Wikileaks |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/meet-the-most-dangerous-man-in-cyberspace-the-american-behind-wikileaks-242845/ |access-date=19 March 2023 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Gottfrid Svartholm]] had worked with WikiLeaks as a technical consultant and managed critical infrastructure.<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – WikiLeaks consultant Gottfrid Svartholm Warg extradited from Sweden after alleged access to NSA contractor CSC |url=https://wikileaks.org/WikiLeaks-consultant-Gottfrid.html |access-date=19 March 2023 |website=wikileaks.org}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=12 December 2013 |title=Pirate Bay cofounder reportedly held in solitary confinement |url=https://www.dailydot.com/unclick/gottfrid-svartholm-warg-pirate-bay-solitary-confinement/ |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=[[The Daily Dot]] |language=en-US}}</ref> He was also listed as part of the "decryption and transmission team" on ''[[July 12, 2007, Baghdad airstrike|Collateral Murder]]'' and credited for "networking" and helped with several other endeavours.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Pirate Bay Founder Helped Wikileaks On Several Fronts * TorrentFreak |url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-founder-helped-wikileaks-on-several-fronts-130205/ |access-date=22 July 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=20 May 2013 |title=Wikileaks stöder Svartholm Warg |language=sv |work=Dagens Nyheter |url=https://www.dn.se/ekonomi/wikileaks-stoder-svartholm-warg/ |access-date=19 March 2023 |issn=1101-2447}}</ref> [[Rop Gonggrijp]], [[Birgitta Jónsdóttir]], [[Smári McCarthy]] and Herbert Snorrason are WikiLeaks volunteers and members who the US government has tried to surveil with court orders.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Knight |first=Sam |date=21 June 2013 |title=Court Documents Reveal Extent of Federal Investigation Into WikiLeaks |language=en-US |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/court-documents-reveal-extent-federal-investigation-wikileaks/ |access-date=19 March 2023 |issn=0027-8378}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=8 January 2011 |title=U.S. orders Twitter to hand over WikiLeaks records |language=en |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wikileaks-twitter-idUSTRE70716420110108 |access-date=19 March 2023}}</ref> WikiLeaks was represented in Russia by [[Israel Shamir]] and in Sweden by his son [[Johannes Wahlström]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Brown |first=Andrew |date=17 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks and Israel Shamir |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/andrewbrown/2010/dec/17/wikileaks-israel-shamir-russia-scandinavia |access-date=19 March 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks May Employ an Anti-Semitic Holocaust Denier – Slideshow – Daily Intel |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2010/12/wikileaks_may_employ_an_antise.html |access-date=19 March 2023 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York Intelligencer]]|date=14 December 2010 |language=en-us}}</ref>

The WikiLeaks dropbox architecture was rebuilt by a WikiLeaks programmer known to most insiders as "The Architect".<ref name="Perlroth-2012">{{Cite web |last=Perlroth |first=Nicole |date=27 October 2012 |title=One On One: Andy Greenberg, Author, "This Machine Kills Secrets" |url=https://archive.nytimes.com/bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/10/27/one-on-one-andy-greenberg-author-this-machine-kills-secrets/ |access-date=5 February 2023 |website=[[The New York Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Khan-2021">{{Cite web |last=Khan |first=Jemima |date=10 June 2021 |title=Jemima Khan on Julian Assange: how the Wikileaks founder alienated his allies |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/2013/02/jemima-khan-julian-assange-how-wikileaks-founder-alienated-his-allies |access-date=6 February 2023 |website=New Statesman |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Greenberg-2023" /> He also instructed another WikiLeaks technician, and some of his colleagues thought he was a computer genius.<ref name="Fowler-2011" /><ref>{{Cite news |date=3 October 2011 |title=WikiLeaks 'Architect' threatens site's future |language=en-AU |work=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]] |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-10-04/wikileaks-architect/3207748 |access-date=6 February 2023}}</ref><ref name="Reuters">{{Cite news |date=28 January 2011 |title=EXCLUSIVE – WikiLeaks: The Next Generation |language=en |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idINIndia-54487220110128 |access-date=7 February 2023}}</ref> According to [[Andy Greenberg]], insiders told him "when The Architect joined WikiLeaks it was a mess. It was two creaking servers without all the flashy security that Assange had promised in interviews with the media. The Architect rebuilt it from scratch."<ref name="Perlroth-2012" /> According to Wired, "WikiLeaks had been running on a single server with sensitive backend components like the submission and e-mail archives connected to the public-facing [[Wiki]] page. The Architect separated the platforms and set up a number of servers in various countries."<ref name="Zetter-2011" />

In August 2011 WikiLeaks volunteer [[Sigurdur Thordarson]] became the first FBI informant to work from inside WikiLeaks, and gave the FBI several hard drives he had copied from Assange and core WikiLeaks members.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Poulsen |first=Kevin |date=27 June 2013 |title=WikiLeaks Volunteer Was a Paid Informant for the FBI |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/06/wikileaks-mole/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|access-date=11 January 2021}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |title=The WikiLeaks Mole |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/news/the-wikileaks-mole-20140106 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=14 January 2016}}</ref> In November 2011 WikiLeaks dismissed Thordarson due to his [[embezzlement]] of $50,000, to which charge (along with several other offences) he later pleaded guilty in an Icelandic court.<ref>{{cite web |author=Daðason, Kolbeinn Tumi |date=22 December 2014 |title=Siggi "The Hacker" receives a two year prison sentence |url=https://www.visir.is/g/2014141229831/siggi--the-hacker--receives-a-two-year-prison-sentence |access-date=4 November 2021 |work=[[Vísir.is]]}}</ref>

[[Alexa O'Brien]] briefly worked for WikiLeaks in 2014, later saying the organisation was not a good fit.<ref name="Feature podcast">{{cite web |date=23 January 2020 |title=Feature podcast: Alexa O'Brien on Wikileaks, intelligence and influence |url=https://risky.biz/HF4/ |access-date=14 February 2021 |publisher=Risky Business}}</ref> On 26 September 2018, it was announced that Julian Assange had appointed [[Kristinn Hrafnsson]] as [[editor-in-chief]] of WikiLeaks with Assange continuing as its publisher.<ref name="Bridge" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=London |first1=Domanii Cameron in |date=27 September 2018 |title=Julian Assange has stepped down as the editor of WikiLeaks |newspaper=News.com.au |url=https://www.news.com.au/world/europe/julian-assange-has-stepped-down-as-the-editor-of-wikileaks/news-story/5f616b419f7fd8154779fefe69c4c1b6 |access-date=6 December 2018}}</ref>

=== Submissions ===
WikiLeaks restructured its process for contributions after its first document leaks did not gain much attention. Assange stated this was part of an attempt to take the voluntary effort typically seen in [[Wiki]] projects and "redirect it to ... material that has real potential for change".<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Hartley |first1=John |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yGgurMv2Y_EC&q=why+no+longer+contribute+to+wikileaks&pg=PT393 |title=A Companion to New Media Dynamics |last2=Burgess |first2=Jean |last3=Bruns |first3=Axel |date=9 January 2013 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781118321638 |language=en}}</ref> Before this, the Wikileaks FAQ, under "How will Wikileaks operate?", read as of February 2007:<ref name="whatis">{{cite web |year=2007 |title=FAQ: How will Wikileaks operate? |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/faq-en |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216183617/http://www.wikileaks.org/faq-en |archive-date=16 February 2007 |access-date=3 October 2022 |website=WikiLeaks}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}

{{blockquote|text=To the user, Wikileaks will look very much like Wikipedia. Anybody can post to it, anybody can edit it. No technical knowledge is required. Leakers can post documents anonymously and untraceably. Users can publicly discuss documents and analyze their credibility and veracity.}}

WikiLeaks stopped using a "[[wiki]]" communal publication method by May 2010.<ref name="wikigone" /> After the arrest of [[Chelsea Manning]] in May 2010, WikiLeaks distanced itself from the idea it actively encouraged people to send classified information, and changed the description of its submission page to say "WikiLeaks accepts a range of material, but we do not solicit it". WikiLeaks removed "classified" from a description of material it accepts and changed the assertion that "submitting confidential material to WikiLeaks is safe, easy and protected by law" to it "is protected by law in better democracies". WikiLeaks also began taking steps to position itself as a news organisation, and portrayed their work as filtering and analysing documents, not just posting them raw.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Savage |first=Charlie |date=16 December 2010 |title=U.S. Tries to Build Case for Conspiracy by WikiLeaks |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/16/world/16wiki.html |access-date=30 September 2023 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

In 2010 Assange said WikiLeaks received some submissions through the postal mail.<ref>{{Cite web |title=What is WikiLeaks? |url=https://news.blogs.cnn.com/2010/07/25/what-is-wikileaks/ |access-date=1 October 2022 |language=en |archive-date=1 October 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221001175809/https://news.blogs.cnn.com/2010/07/25/what-is-wikileaks/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> That year, Julian Assange said that the servers were located in Sweden and the other countries "specifically because those nations offer legal protection to the disclosures made on the site". He said the [[Constitution of Sweden|Swedish constitution]] gives the information–providers total legal protection and that it is forbidden for any administrative authority to make inquiries about the sources of any type of newspaper.<ref name="DN1" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Helin, Jan |date=14 August 2010 |title=Därför blir Julian Assange kolumnist i Aftonbladet |language=sv |work=[[Aftonbladet]] (blog) |place=Stockholm |url=http://blogg.aftonbladet.se/janhelin/2010/08/darfor-blir-julian-assange-kolumnist-i-aftonbladet |url-status=live |access-date=15 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820032744/http://blogg.aftonbladet.se/janhelin/2010/08/darfor-blir-julian-assange-kolumnist-i-aftonbladet |archive-date=20 August 2012}}</ref> This could make it difficult for any authority to target WikiLeaks by placing a [[Burden of proof (law)|burden of proof]] upon any complainant.<ref name="goodwin" /> According to the [[Columbia Journalism Review]], "a variety of Swedish media law experts made it clear that Assange and WikiLeaks had repeatedly misrepresented not only the strength of the law, but its application to WikiLeaks."<ref name="Columbia Journalism Review" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=A Swedish Shield, Unraised |url=https://www.cjr.org/campaign_desk/a_swedish_shield_unraised.php |access-date=29 May 2023 |website=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref>

According to [[Andy Greenberg]] and ''Wired'', The Architect was the engineer who rebuilt the WikiLeaks submission system, separated the sensitive platforms from the public-facing Wiki and set up servers in various countries.<ref name="Khan-2021" /><ref name="Zetter-2011" /><ref name="Greenberg-2023" /> During the [[#2010 internal dissent|2010 reorganisation]], The Architect left with Domscheit-Berg, taking the code<ref name="Bustillos-2023" /> behind the submission system with him.<ref name="Fowler-2011" /><ref name="Zetter-2011" /><ref name="Greenberg-2023" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |date=27 September 2012 |title=How Two Bulgarian Journalists Created a WikiLeaks Copycat That Actually Worked |url=https://slate.com/technology/2012/09/this-machine-kills-secrets-excerpt-how-two-bulgarian-journalists-created-a-copycat-site-that-actually-worked.html |access-date=22 July 2022 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |language=en}}</ref> Assange said that the submission system was temporarily down because its backlog was too big.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Crawford |first=Jeanne Whalen And David |title=WikiLeaks Faces New Competition |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704805204575594612532529470 |access-date=7 February 2023 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=4 November 2010 |language=en-US}}</ref> WikiLeaks later said it was down because of Domscheit-Berg's "acts of sabotage" when he left the organisation, which had forced WikiLeaks to "overhaul the entire submission system", and the staff lacked time to do so.<ref name="Zetter-2011" />

WikiLeaks submissions stayed offline until May 2015.<ref name="Greenberg-2015" /><ref name="wikileaks-2015" /> While it was offline, WikiLeaks announced it was building a state-of-the-art secure submission system. The launch of the new system was delayed by security concerns about [[Public key certificate|SSL certificates]] in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Constantin |first=Lucian |date=29 November 2011 |title=WikiLeaks: Security worries impede new submission system |url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/2499524/wikileaks--security-worries-impede-new-submission-system.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722040127/https://www.computerworld.com/article/2499524/wikileaks--security-worries-impede-new-submission-system.html |archive-date=22 July 2022 |access-date=22 July 2022 |website=Computerworld |language=en }}</ref><ref name="Greenberg-2">{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Unveils 160 Firms' Surveillance Gear Sales Docs, Still No Submissions System |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/12/01/wikileaks-unveils-160-firms-surveillance-gear-sales-docs-still-no-submission-system/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230515202946/http://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/12/01/wikileaks-unveils-160-firms-surveillance-gear-sales-docs-still-no-submission-system/ |archive-date=15 May 2023 |access-date=27 January 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en }}</ref> During this time, WikiLeaks continued to publish documents. These publications originated from material which had been directly shared with WikiLeaks by hackers, or were the result of Wikileaks organising and republishing already-public leaks.<ref name="Greenberg-2015" /> In an October 2011 press conference, Assange said that because the submission system did not work, sources "had to establish contacts with the organisation and transmit us the material through other mechanisms".<ref name="Greenberg-2" /> In 2011 ''Forbes'' suggested that [[Andy Müller-Maguhn]] and Bugged Planet might be WikiLeaks' source for the Spy Files and in 2018 a former WikiLeaks associate said that Müller-Maguhn and a colleague administered the submission server in 2016, though Müller-Maguhn denies this.<ref name="Greenberg-2" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=A German hacker offers a rare look inside the secretive world of Julian Assange and WikiLeaks |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/a-german-hacker-offers-a-rare-look-inside-the-secretive-world-of-julian-assange-and-wikileaks/2018/01/17/e6211180-f311-11e7-b390-a36dc3fa2842_story.html |access-date=22 July 2022 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> That October, WikiLeaks suggested "lawyer to lawyer" as an alternate submission method, naming [[Margaret Ratner Kunstler]].<ref name="Pilkington-2017">{{Cite news |last=Pilkington |first=Ed |date=14 November 2017 |title=Donald Trump Jr communicated with WikiLeaks during final stages of election |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2017/nov/13/donald-trump-jr-communicated-with-wikileaks-during-final-stages-of-election |access-date=11 February 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name="Bloomberg30012019">{{cite news |last=Kocieniewski |first=David |date=30 January 2019 |title=The Civil Rights Warrior Who May Have Linked Roger Stone to WikiLeaks |work=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-30/the-civil-rights-warrior-who-may-have-linked-stone-to-wikileaks |access-date=8 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190921020520/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-30/the-civil-rights-warrior-who-may-have-linked-stone-to-wikileaks |archive-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>

Assange told writer [[Charles Glass]] in 2023 that WikiLeaks was no longer able to publish due to his imprisonment and the effect that US government surveillance and WikiLeaks' funding restrictions were having on potential whistleblowers. Assange said that other media outlets were not filling the void.<ref name="Glass-2024">{{cite web |last1=Glass |first1=Charles |title=A Visit to Belmarsh Prison, Where Julian Assange Awaits His Final Appeal Against Extradition to the US |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/activism/julian-assange-wikileaks-belmarsh-prison/ |website=The Nation |access-date=4 January 2024 |date=2 January 2024}}</ref>

== Legal issues ==

There have been many legal issues in different countries and several investigations surrounding WikiLeaks since it was founded.

In August 2010, the internet payment company Moneybookers closed WikiLeaks' account due to publicity over its release of the Afghan war logs and because WikiLeaks had been added to the official US watchlist and an Australian government blacklist.<ref name="Leigh-2010" />

=== Legal issues in Australia ===
In December 2010, the Australian Prime Minister [[Julia Gillard]] said that "I absolutely condemn the placement of this information on the WikiLeaks website – it's a grossly irresponsible thing to do and an illegal thing to do".<ref>{{cite news |title=Gillard condemns WikiLeaks |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/gillard-condemns-wikileaks-20101202-18haq.html |access-date=26 March 2020 |agency=AAP |publisher=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=2 December 2010}}</ref> After criticism and a revolt within her party, she said she was referring to "the original theft of the material by a junior U.S. serviceman rather than any action by Mr. Assange".<ref>{{cite interview |title=Gillard refines verdict on Assange |first=Julia |last=Gillard |date=7 December 2010 |url=http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2010/s3086783.htm |interviewer=Lyndal Curtis |work=[[The World Today (Australian radio program)|The World Today]] |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC Radio]] (Australia) |access-date=12 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209143804/http://www.abc.net.au/worldtoday/content/2010/s3086783.htm |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Patricia |last=Karvelas |title=Party revolt growing over Prime Minister Julia Gillard's WikiLeaks stance |work=[[The Australian]] |place=Sydney |date=14 December 2010 |url=http://www.news.com.au/features/wikileaks/party-revolt-at-pms-wiki-stance/story-fn79cf6x-1225970594165 |access-date=14 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731185654/http://www.news.com.au/features/wikileaks/party-revolt-at-pms-wiki-stance/story-fn79cf6x-1225970594165 |archive-date=31 July 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Australian Federal Police]] later said that the release of the cables by WikiLeaks breached no Australian laws.<ref>{{cite news |title=Gillard a sycophant, says Assange mum |url=https://www.news.com.au/breaking-news/gillard-a-sycophant-says-assange-mum/news-story/4fe6e3e629cc0fca8bcce0c0ada12ca8 |access-date=26 March 2020 |agency=AAP |publisher=News Limited |date=1 February 2011}}</ref>

On 2 September 2011 [[Attorney-General of Australia|Australia's attorney general]], [[Robert McClelland (Australian politician)|Robert McClelland]] released a statement that the [[United States diplomatic cables leak|US diplomatic cables]] published by Wikileaks identified at least one ASIO officer, and that it was a crime in Australia to publish information which could identify an intelligence officer. McClelland said that "On occasions before this week, WikiLeaks redacted identifying features where the safety of individuals or national security could be put at risk. It appears this hasn't occurred with documents that have been distributed across the internet this week." According to ''[[The Guardian]]'' and ''Al Jazeera'', this meant "Julian Assange could face prosecution in Australia."<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 September 2011 |title=Julian Assange could face arrest in Australia over unredacted cables |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/02/julian-assange-arrest-australia-wikileaks |access-date=21 November 2022 |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks criticised over uncensored cables |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2011/9/3/wikileaks-criticised-over-uncensored-cables |access-date=5 January 2023 |website=www.aljazeera.com |language=en}}</ref>

In 2014, WikiLeaks published information about political bribery allegations, violating a gag order in Australia.<ref name="Associated Press" /> According to Peter Bartlett, a media lawyer in Australia, "if Assange ever comes back to Australia, you would expect that he would immediately be charged with breaking a suppression order."<ref name="Associated Press" />

=== Legal issues in Europe ===

==== Germany ====
In December 2008 WikiLeaks said that [[Federal Intelligence Service|BND]] President [[Ernst Uhrlau]] threatened WikiLeaks with criminal prosecution if it did not remove "files or reports related to the BND".<ref>{{Cite web |title=German spy chief threatens Wikileaks – WikiLeaks |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/German_spy_chief_threatens_Wikileaks |access-date=27 January 2024 |website=wikileaks.org}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} Later that month WikiLeaks published what it said were emails with the BND.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Correspondence between BND and Wikileaks, as of Dec 22 2008 – WikiLeaks |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/wiki/Correspondence_between_BND_and_Wikileaks,_as_of_Dec_22_2008 |access-date=27 January 2024 |website=www.wikileaks.org}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}

In March 2009, German police raided the offices of Wikileaks Germany and the homes of Theodor Reppe, who owned the registration for WikiLeaks' German domain while searching for evidence of "distribution of pornographic material".<ref name="Fae-2009">{{Cite web |last=Fae |first=Jane |title=German police boot down doors of Wikileaks offices |url=https://www.theregister.com/2009/03/26/german_police_raid_wikileaks/ |access-date=27 January 2024 |website=www.theregister.com |language=en}}</ref> The Register reported that<blockquote>As well as wasting the time of 11 detectives involved in this raid, Wikileaks claim that police requested the passwords to the "wikileaks.de" domain, asked that the entire domain be disabled, failed to inform Mr Reppe of his rights, and then issued false statements claiming that Mr. Reppe had agreed to "not having a witness" present. According to Wikileaks, the Police would give no further information to Mr. Reppe and no contact was made with Wikileaks before or after the search. Wikileaks are therefore in the dark as to exactly why the raid occurred.<ref name="Fae-2009" /></blockquote>

==== United Kingdom ====

On 8 February 2018, the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|UK Supreme Court]] unanimously allowed a leaked document that had been published by WikiLeaks to be admitted as evidence. The cable had been excluded from use in an earlier part of the case before the Administrative Court based on the fact that it was a diplomatic communication, which enjoy "inviolable" [[Vienna Convention on Diplomatic Relations 1961|Vienna Convention]] protections that prevent them from being used in court outside of exceptional circumstances. The Supreme Court ruled that since the document had already been widely disseminated, it had lost any protections it might have had.<ref name="brickcourt.co.uk">{{cite web |date=12 February 2018 |title=Supreme Court considers important test of the Vienna Convention in relation to Wikileaks documents |url=http://www.brickcourt.co.uk/news/detail/supreme-court-considers-important-test-of-vienna-convention-in-relation-to-wikileaks-documents |access-date=11 September 2018 |publisher=Brick Court Chambers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=18 April 2013 |title=Chagossians suffer blow in fight to go home as court rejects WikiLeaks cable |url=http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/apr/18/chagos-islanders-court-rejects-wikileaks-cable |access-date=22 April 2021 |website=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=8 February 2018 |title=R (on the application of Bancoult No 3) (Appellant) v Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs (Respondent) |url=http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKSC/2018/3.html |access-date=11 September 2018 |publisher=United Kingdom Supreme Court}}</ref><ref name="Ejil210218">{{cite web |last1=McCorquodale |first1=Robert |date=21 February 2018 |title=Wikileaks Documents are Admissible in a Domestic Court |url=https://www.ejiltalk.org/wikileaks-documents-are-admissible-in-a-domestic-court/ |access-date=28 November 2020 |website=EJIL: Talk! |language=en}}</ref>

=== Legal issues in United States ===
{{See also|Bank Julius Baer v. WikiLeaks|Democratic National Committee v. Russian Federation}}
In early February 2008, the [[Julius Baer Group]] sued WikiLeaks in California to have documents removed from their website. Judge [[Jeffrey White]] forced [[Dynadot]] to disassociate the site's [[domain name]] records with its servers, preventing use of the domain name to reach the site. Initially, the bank only wanted the documents to be removed (WikiLeaks had failed to name a contact person). After civil rights challenges, the judge lifted the injunction<ref name="opinion">{{cite court|litigants=Bank Julius Baer v. WikiLeaks|court=N.D. Cal.|reporter=F. Supp. 2d|vol=535|opinion=980|pinpoint=|date=2008|url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/20081515535fsupp2d98011416|quote=|access-date=8 February 2019}}</ref> and the bank dropped the case on 5 March 2008.<ref name="Claburn">{{cite web |last=Claburn |first=Thomas |date=6 March 2008 |title=Swiss Bank Abandons Lawsuit Against Wikileaks: The wiki had posted financial documents it said proved tax evasion by Bank Julius Baer's clients |url=http://www.informationweek.com/management/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=206902154 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310223152/http://www.informationweek.com/management/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=206902154 |archive-date=10 March 2008 |access-date=6 March 2008 |publisher=[[InformationWeek]]}}</ref>

On 20 April 2018, the Democratic National Committee filed a multimillion-dollar lawsuit in [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|federal district court in Manhattan]] against Russia, the Trump campaign, WikiLeaks and Julian Assange, alleging a conspiracy to disrupt the [[2016 United States presidential election]] in Trump's favour.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hamburger |first1=Tom |last2=Helderman |first2=Rosalind S. |last3=Nakashima |first3=Ellen |date=20 April 2018 |title=Democratic Party sues Russia, Trump campaign and WikiLeaks alleging 2016 campaign conspiracy |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/democratic-party-files-lawsuit-alleging-russia-the-trump-campaign-and-wikileaks-conspired-to-disrupt-the-2016-campaign/2018/04/20/befe8364-4418-11e8-8569-26fda6b404c7_story.html |access-date=20 April 2018}}</ref> The suit was dismissed [[with prejudice]] on 30 July 2019. In his judgement, Judge [[John Koeltl]] said that WikiLeaks "did not participate in any wrongdoing in obtaining the materials in the first place" and therefore was within the law in publishing the information.<ref>{{cite news |last1=David O'Brien |first1=Rebecca |date=30 July 2019 |title=Judge Dismisses Democrats' Suit Against Russia, Trump Campaign |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[News Corp]] |location=New York |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/judge-dismisses-democrats-suit-against-russia-trump-campaign-11564539167 |access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref> The federal judge also wrote <blockquote>The DNC's interest in keeping 'donor lists' and 'fundraising strategies' secret is dwarfed by the newsworthiness of the documents as a whole...If WikiLeaks could be held liable for publishing documents concerning the DNC's political financial and voter-engagement strategies simply because the DNC labels them 'secret' and trade secrets, then so could any newspaper or other media outlet.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Judge dismisses DNC suit against Trump campaign, Russia over email hack |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/30/dnc-lawsuit-trump-campaign-russia-email-hack-1441166 |website=[[Politico]]|date=30 July 2019 }}</ref></blockquote>

==== United States criminal investigations ====
{{See also|Julian Assange#US criminal investigations}}The [[United States Department of Justice|US Justice Department]] began a criminal investigation of WikiLeaks and Julian Assange soon after the [[United States diplomatic cables leak|leak of diplomatic cables in 2010]] began.<ref name="Savage20101201">{{cite news |last=Savage |first=Charlie |title=U.S. Weighs Prosecution of WikiLeaks Founder, but Legal Scholars Warn of Steep Hurdles |date=1 December 2010 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/02/world/02legal.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=5 December 2010}}</ref> ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that the department was considering charges under the [[Espionage Act of 1917]], an action which former prosecutors characterised as "difficult" because of [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] protections for the press.<ref name=Savage20101201 /><ref name="nakashima">{{cite news |last=Nakashima |first=Ellen |author2=Markon, Jerry |title=WikiLeaks founder could be charged under Espionage Act |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/11/29/AR2010112905973.html |access-date=5 December 2010 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=30 November 2010}}</ref> Several Supreme Court cases, while not conclusive, (e.g. ''[[Bartnicki v. Vopper]]'') have established that the American [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] protects the re-publication of illegally gained information provided the publishers did not themselves violate any laws in acquiring it. The question of criminal punishment or a civil injunction after publication, like in the WikiLeaks case, is less established.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2010/07/26/pentagon-papers-ii-on-wikileaks-and-the-first-amendment/ |access-date =6 December 2010 |date=26 July 2010 |title=Pentagon Papers II? On WikiLeaks and the First Amendment |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] (blog) |author=Jones, Ashby |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511022459/https://blogs.wsj.com/law/2010/07/26/pentagon-papers-ii-on-wikileaks-and-the-first-amendment/ |archive-date=11 May 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2010, the [[National Security Agency|NSA]] added Assange to its Manhunting Timeline.<ref name="Greenwald-2014a">{{Cite web |last1=Greenwald |first1=Glenn |first2=Ryan |last2=Gallagher |date=18 February 2014 |title=Snowden Documents Reveal Covert Surveillance and Pressure Tactics Aimed at WikiLeaks and Its Supporters |url=https://theintercept.com/2014/02/18/snowden-docs-reveal-covert-surveillance-and-pressure-tactics-aimed-at-wikileaks-and-its-supporters/ |access-date=5 February 2023 |website=The Intercept |language=en}}</ref> In August 2010, the Pentagon had concluded that the [[United States documents leak of the War in Afghanistan|Afghan War documents leak]] broke the law. A letter from the Department of Defence general counsel said that "it is the view of the Department of Defence that WikiLeaks obtained this material in circumstances that constitute a violation of US law, and that as long as WikiLeaks holds this material, the violation of the law is ongoing."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dombey |first=Daniel |date=21 August 2010 |title=Pentagon concludes WikiLeaks broke law |url=https://www.ft.com/content/8ae43d12-acd1-11df-8582-00144feabdc0 |access-date=18 March 2023 |website=Financial Times}}</ref> In November 2010, [[Harold Hongju Koh|Harold Koh]], the [[Legal Adviser of the Department of State]], wrote that the [[United States diplomatic cables leak]] "were provided in violation of US law and without regard for the grave consequences of this action" and "as long as WikiLeaks holds such material, the violation of the law is ongoing".<ref name="smh_DeptState_rejects">{{cite news |date=28 November 2010 |title=US Rejects Talks with WikiLeaks |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |url=http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/us-rejects-talks-with-wikileaks-20101128-18c57.html |url-status=live |access-date=28 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129222408/http://news.smh.com.au/breaking-news-world/us-rejects-talks-with-wikileaks-20101128-18c57.html |archive-date=29 November 2010}}</ref><ref name="Koh_refuses_pdf">{{cite news |last=Koh |first=Harold Hongju |author-link=Harold Hongju Koh |date=27 November 2010 |title=Dear Ms. Robinson and Mr. Assange |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://media.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/documents/Dept_of_State_Assange_letter.pdf |url-status=dead |access-date=28 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224054809/http://media.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/documents/Dept_of_State_Assange_letter.pdf |archive-date=24 December 2010}}</ref>

On 14 December 2010 the [[United States Department of Justice]] issued a [[WikiLeaks-related Twitter subpoenas|subpoena directing Twitter]] to provide information for accounts registered to or associated with WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite web |date=17 January 2009 |title=Twitter Subpoena |url=http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2011/01/07/twitter/subpoena.pdf |access-date=10 January 2011 |website=[[Salon.com|Salon]] |archive-date=12 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112061516/http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2011/01/07/twitter/subpoena.pdf |url-status=dead }}</ref> Twitter decided to notify its users.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rushe, Dominic |date=8 January 2011 |title=Icelandic MP fights US demand for her Twitter account details |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/08/us-twitter-hand-icelandic-wikileaks-messages |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725200602/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2011/jan/08/us-twitter-hand-icelandic-wikileaks-messages |archive-date=25 July 2011 |access-date=10 January 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]] |place=London}}</ref>

In 2011 a [[Sigurdur Thordarson|WikiLeaks volunteer]] became an FBI informant<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kushner |first=David |date=6 January 2014 |title=The WikiLeaks Mole |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/culture-news/the-wikileaks-mole-102787/ |access-date=8 February 2023 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Poulsen |first=Kevin |title=WikiLeaks Volunteer Was a Paid Informant for the FBI |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/06/wikileaks-mole/ |access-date=8 February 2023 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Farivar |first=Cyrus |date=28 June 2013 |title=Teenage WikiLeaks volunteer: Why I served as an FBI informant |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/06/teenage-wikileaks-volunteer-why-i-served-as-an-fbi-informant/ |access-date=8 February 2023 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us}}</ref> and Google was served with search warrants for the contents of email accounts belonging to WikiLeaks volunteers Herbert Snorrason and Smari McCarthy.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bohn |first=Dieter |date=22 June 2013 |title=Secret warrant used to access WikiLeaks volunteer's Gmail account |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/6/22/4453722/secret-warrant-used-to-access-wikileaks-volunteers-gmail-account |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=[[The Verge]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Poulsen |first=Kevin |title=In WikiLeaks Probe, Feds Used a Secret Search Warrant to Get Volunteer's Gmail |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/06/wikileaks-gmail/ |access-date=2 May 2023 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Knight |first=Sam |date=21 June 2013 |title=Court Documents Reveal Extent of Federal Investigation Into WikiLeaks |magazine=The Nation |language=en-US |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/court-documents-reveal-extent-federal-investigation-wikileaks/ |access-date=14 March 2022 |issn=0027-8378}}</ref> The NSA discussed categorising WikiLeaks as a "malicious foreign actor" for surveillance purposes.<ref name="Greenwald-2014a" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Reitman |first=rainey |date=19 February 2014 |title=Surveillance and Pressure Against WikiLeaks and Its Readers |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2014/02/surveillance-and-pressure-wikileaks-readers |access-date=5 February 2023 |website=Electronic Frontier Foundation |language=en}}</ref>

In March 2012, Google was served with search warrants for the contents of email accounts and other information belonging to WikiLeaks staff members [[Sarah Harrison (journalist)|Sarah Harrison]], [[Joseph Farrell (journalist)|Joseph Farrell]], and [[Kristinn Hrafnsson]] as part of a criminal investigation with alleged offences including [[Espionage Act of 1917|espionage]], conspiracy to commit espionage, the theft or conversion of property belonging to the United States government, violation of the [[Computer Fraud and Abuse Act]], and [[Conspiracy (criminal)|criminal conspiracy]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Google silent on WikiLeaks email warrant for nearly three years |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/google-silent-on-wikileaks-email-warrant-for-nearly-three-years/ |access-date=2 May 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Pilkington |first1=Ed |last2=Rushe |first2=Dominic |date=25 January 2015 |title=WikiLeaks demands answers after Google hands staff emails to US government |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/jan/25/wikileaks-google-staff-emails-us-government |access-date=27 January 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> According to Daniel Domscheit-Berg in 2010, the WikiLeaks email accounts for Kristinn Hrafnsson and a young WikiLeaks staffer had automatically forwarded to their Google account, opening the organisation to surveillance risks.<ref name="Zetter" /><ref name="Domscheit-Berg-2011a" />

By 2013,  [[Jérémie Zimmermann]], [[Smári McCarthy]], [[Jacob Appelbaum]], David House and [[Jennifer Robinson (lawyer)|Jennifer Robinson]] had been detained and interrogated or approached when attempts were made to recruit them as informants.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hedges |first=Chris |date=8 May 2013 |title=An Interview With Julian Assange |language=en-US |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/interview-julian-assange/ |access-date=13 February 2023 |issn=0027-8378}}</ref>

In 2014, FBI and CIA officials lobbied the White House to designate Wikileaks as an "information broker" to allow for more investigative tools against it and according to former officials "potentially paving the way" for its prosecution. [[Laura Poitras]] later described attempts to classify herself and Assange as "information brokers" rather than journalists as "a threat to journalists worldwide".<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Barnes |first1=Julian E. |last2=Goldman |first2=Adam |last3=Savage |first3=Charlie |date=17 November 2018 |title=How the Trump Administration Stepped Up Pursuit of WikiLeaks's Assange |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/16/us/politics/trump-administration-assange-wikileaks.html |access-date=27 January 2024 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="Kidnapping" />

In April 2017, prosecutors began drafting a memo that considered charging members of WikiLeaks with conspiracy, theft of government property or violating the Espionage Act.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Justice Dept. debating charges against WikiLeaks members in revelations of diplomatic, CIA materials |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/justice-dept-debating-charges-against-wikileaks-members-in-revelations-of-diplomatic-cia-materials/2017/04/20/32b15336-2548-11e7-a1b3-faff0034e2de_story.html |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> That month, CIA director [[Mike Pompeo]] called WikiLeaks "a non-state hostile intelligence service often abetted by state actors like Russia". In December 2019, Congress designated Wikileaks and [[Julian Assange]] as a "non-state hostile intelligence service often abetted by state actors" that "should be treated as such a service by the United States" in the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020]]. In the opinion of some former officials, the designation allowed the [[CIA]] to launch and plan operations that did not require presidential approval or congressional notice.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grim |first1=Ryan |last2=Sirota |first2=Sara |title=Julian Assange Kidnapping Plot Casts New Light on 2018 Senate Intelligence Maneuver |url=https://theintercept.com/2021/09/28/assange-kidnapping-wikileaks-cia-senate/ |website=The Intercept |access-date=25 December 2021 |date=28 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gibbons |first1=Chip |title=The US Considered Kidnapping and Even Assassinating Julian Assange |url=https://www.jacobinmag.com/2021/09/united-states-kidnap-assassinate-julian-assange-wikileaks-cia-yahoo-news |website=jacobinmag.com |access-date=25 December 2021 |date=30 September 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The Plot to Kill Julian Assange: Report Reveals CIA's Plan to Kidnap, Assassinate WikiLeaks Founder |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2021/9/28/cia_julian_assange_assassination_plot |website=Democracy Now! |access-date=25 December 2021 |language=en |date=28 September 2021}}</ref><ref name="Kidnapping" />

In 2017 in the wake of the Vault 7 leaks, the CIA discussed plans to kidnap or assassinate Julian Assange, according to [[Yahoo! News]] in  September 2021. It also planned to spy on associates of WikiLeaks, sow discord among its members, and steal their electronic devices.<ref name="Kidnapping">{{cite web |last1=Dorfman |first1=Zach |last2=Naylor |first2=Sean D. |last3=Isikoff |first3=Michael |date=26 September 2021 |title=Kidnapping, assassination and a London shoot-out: Inside the CIA's secret war plans against WikiLeaks |url=https://news.yahoo.com/kidnapping-assassination-and-a-london-shoot-out-inside-the-ci-as-secret-war-plans-against-wiki-leaks-090057786.html |access-date=26 September 2021 |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]]}}</ref> Former CIA Director [[Mike Pompeo]] stated that the US officials who had spoken to Yahoo should be prosecuted for exposing CIA activities.<ref>{{cite web |title=The US Considered Kidnapping and Even Assassinating Julian Assange |url=https://jacobinmag.com/2021/09/united-states-kidnap-assassinate-julian-assange-wikileaks-cia-yahoo-news? |access-date=1 October 2021 |publisher=Jacobin}}</ref>

In November 2018, an accidental filing with Assange's name was seen to indicate there were undisclosed charges against him.<ref name="apnews.com">{{Cite web |date=26 April 2021 |title=Charges undermine Assange denials about hacked email origins |url=https://apnews.com/article/north-america-ap-top-news-john-podesta-indictments-julian-assange-69b28dd8fc034cb0a2528048638d7893 |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=[[Associated Press|AP News]] |language=en}}</ref> On 11 April 2019, Assange was charged in a computer hacking conspiracy.<ref>{{Cite web |date=11 April 2019 |title=WikiLeaks Founder Charged in Computer Hacking Conspiracy |url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-edva/pr/wikileaks-founder-charged-computer-hacking-conspiracy |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=justice.gov |language=en}}</ref> On 23 May, a superseding indictment was filed with charges of Conspiracy to Receive National Defense Information, Obtaining National Defense Information, Disclosure of National Defense Information, and Conspiracy to Commit Computer Intrusion.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 May 2019 |title=WikiLeaks Founder Julian Assange Charged in 18-Count Superseding Indictment |url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/wikileaks-founder-julian-assange-charged-18-count-superseding-indictment |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=justice.gov |language=en}}</ref> On 24 June 2020, another superseding indictment was filed which added to the allegations but not the charges.<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 June 2020 |title=WikiLeaks Founder Charged in Superseding Indictment |url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/wikileaks-founder-charged-superseding-indictment |access-date=14 March 2022 |website=justice.gov |language=en}}</ref>

The day after charging Assange, prosecutors contacted Domscheit-Berg. Prosecutors also spoke with David House for about 90 minutes, who had previously testified to the grand jury in exchange for immunity. House testified about helping run political operations for WikiLeaks and that Assange wanted him "to help achieve favorable press for Chelsea Manning." According to House, the grand jury "wanted full insight into WikiLeaks, what its goals were and why I was associated with it. . . . It was all related to disclosures around the war logs." House said he had contact with Assange until 2013 and with WikiLeaks until 2015.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Benner |first1=Katie |last2=Shane |first2=Scott |date=16 April 2019 |title=Justice Dept. Investigated WikiLeaks After Secretly Indicting Assange |language=en-US |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/16/us/politics/wikileaks-investigation-justice-department.html |access-date=8 February 2023 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Chelsea Manning subpoenaed to testify before grand jury in Assange investigation |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/chelsea-manning-subpoenaed-to-testify-before-grand-jury-in-assange-investigation/2019/03/01/fe3bd582-3c32-11e9-a06c-3ec8ed509d15_story.html |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Chelsea Manning and Jeremy Hammond refused to testify for the grand jury.<ref>{{Cite web |first1=Katelyn |last1=Polantz |first2=Veronica |last2=Stracqualursi |first3=Mark |last3=Morales |date=12 March 2020 |title=Federal judge orders Chelsea Manning's release from jail {{!}} CNN Politics |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/12/politics/chelsea-manning-suicide-attempt-virginia-jail/index.html |access-date=8 February 2023 |website=[[CNN]]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=12 March 2020 |title=Judge Orders Chelsea Manning and Jeremy Hammond Released From Jail |url=https://gizmodo.com/judge-orders-chelsea-manning-and-jeremy-hammond-release-1842301516 |access-date=8 February 2023 |website=Gizmodo |language=en}}</ref>

In early 2019, the [[Mueller report]] wrote the Special Counsel's office considered charging WikiLeaks or Assange "as conspirators in the computer-intrusion conspiracy and that there were "factual uncertainties" about the role that Assange may have played in the hacks or their distribution that were "the subject of ongoing investigations" by the US Attorney's Office.<ref>{{Cite web |first1=Jason |last1=Leopold |first2=Ken |last2=Bensinger |title=Mueller Investigated Julian Assange, WikiLeaks, And Roger Stone For DNC Hacks And Election Law Violations |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/jasonleopold/new-mueller-investigated-julian-assange-wikileaks-and-roger |access-date=10 February 2023 |website=[[BuzzFeed News]] |date=3 November 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Falconer |first=Rebecca |date=3 November 2020 |title=Read: DOJ updated Mueller report with new details on Roger Stone and Julian Assange |url=https://www.axios.com/2020/11/03/new-mueller-report-details-roger-stone-julian-assange |access-date=10 February 2023 |website=[[Axios (website)|Axios]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Polantz |first=Katelyn |date=3 November 2020 |title=Mueller investigated – but didn't charge – Stone, WikiLeaks and Assange for Russian hack of Democrats in 2016, less-redacted report shows {{!}} CNN Politics |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/11/02/politics/new-mueller-report-released/index.html |access-date=10 February 2023 |website=[[CNN]] |language=en}}</ref>

In June 2023, ''[[The Age]]'' reported that the FBI is seeking to gather new evidence in the case, based on a request from the FBI to interview [[Andrew O'Hagan]], who refused the request.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Knott |first=Matthew |date=31 May 2023 |title=FBI restarts Julian Assange probe despite hopes of release |url=https://www.theage.com.au/politics/federal/fbi-restarts-julian-assange-probe-despite-hopes-of-release-20230531-p5dcoe.html |access-date=2 June 2023 |website=The Age |language=en}}</ref>

In June 2024, Assange pled guilty to one count of violating the Espionage Act.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2024/06/25/julian-assange-wikileaks-guilty-espionage-act/74203330007/ |title=WikiLeaks' Julian Assange pleads guilty to violating Espionage Act in plea deal for freedom |first=Bart |last=Jansen |work=USA Today |date=25 June 2024 |access-date=26 June 2024}}</ref> Under the plea deal, he was sentenced to time served and released. He agreed to instruct Wikileaks to destroy or return unpublished documents.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2024/06/25/julian-assange-plea-deal-updates/ |title=Julian Assange to attend plea deal hearing in Saipan |date=25 June 2024 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=25 June 2024}}</ref>

==== Use of leaked documents in court ====
In April 2011 the US Department of Justice warned military lawyers acting for Guantanamo Bay detainees against clicking of links on sites such as ''[[The New York Times]]'' that might lead to classified files published by WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sorkin |first1=Amy Davidson |date=28 April 2011 |title=WikiLeaks: The Secrets that Aren't |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/amy-davidson/wikileaks-the-secrets-that-arent |access-date=8 May 2021}}</ref> In June the same year the US Department of Justice ruled that attorneys acting for Guantanamo Bay detainees could cite documents published by WikiLeaks. The use of the documents was subject to restrictions.<ref>{{cite web |date=13 June 2011 |title=DOJ Details Access, Use of WikiLeaks Documents in Gitmo Cases |url=https://legaltimes.typepad.com/blt/2011/06/doj-details-access-use-of-wikileaks-documents-in-gitmo-cases.html |access-date=8 May 2021 |website=The BLT: The Blog of Legal Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=6 June 2011 |title=Judge Gives DOJ Reprieve In WikiLeaks Document Dispute |url=https://legaltimes.typepad.com/blt/2011/06/doj-crafting-guidance-over-wikileaks-documents.html |access-date=8 May 2021 |website=The BLT: The Blog of Legal Times}}</ref>

== Publications ==
{{Main|Information published by WikiLeaks}}The initial tranche of WikiLeaks' documents came from a WikiLeaks' activist who owned a server that was a node in the [[Tor network]]. After they noticed that Chinese hackers used the network to gather information from foreign governments, the activist began recording the information. This let Assange show potential contributors that WikiLeaks was viable and say it had "received over one million documents from thirteen countries".<ref name="Khatchdourian" />

=== 2006–2008 ===
* WikiLeaks posted its first document in December 2006, a decision to assassinate Somali government officials signed by rebel leader Sheikh [[Hassan Dahir Aweys]].<ref name="Khatchdourian" /> Assange and WikiLeaks were uncertain of its authenticity, and the document's authenticity was never determined.<ref name="Khatchdourian" />
* In August 2007, the UK newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]'' published a story about corruption by the family of the former Kenyan leader [[Daniel arap Moi]] based on information provided via WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite news |title=The looting of Kenya |url=https://www.theguardian.com/kenya/story/0,,2159757,00.html |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 August 2007 |access-date=28 February 2008 |place=London |first=Xan |last=Rice |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131213722/http://www.guardian.co.uk/kenya/story/0%2C%2C2159757%2C00.html |archive-date=31 January 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> Corruption was a major issue in the election that followed, which was marred by violence. According to Assange, "1,300 people were eventually killed, and 350,000 were displaced. That was a result of our leak. On the other hand, the Kenyan people had a right to that information and 40,000 children a year die of malaria in Kenya. And many more die of money being pulled out of Kenya, and as a result of the Kenyan shilling being debased".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cadwalladr |first=Carole |date=31 July 2010 |title=Julian Assange, monk of the online age who thrives on intellectual battle |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/aug/01/julian-assange-wikileaks-afghanistan |issn=0029-7712}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=23 August 2016 |title=Is Wikileaks putting people at risk? |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37165230 |access-date=22 October 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Copeland |first=Rafiq |date=13 December 2010 |title=Life and death under WikiLeaks: what we learnt in Kenya |url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2010/12/13/life-and-death-under-wikileaks-what-we-learnt-in-kenya/ |access-date=22 October 2023 |website=[[Crikey]]}}</ref>
* In November 2007, a March 2003 copy of ''[[Camp Delta Standard Operating Procedures|Standard Operating Procedures for Camp Delta]]'' detailing the protocol of the [[United States Army|US Army]] at the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] was released.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/politics/onlinerights/news/2007/11/gitmo |title=Sensitive Guantánamo Bay Manual Leaked Through Wiki Site |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |place=New York |date=14 November 2007 |author=Singel, Ryan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140210123003/http://www.wired.com/politics/onlinerights/news/2007/11/gitmo |archive-date=10 February 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/wiki/Camp_Delta_Standard_Operating_Procedure |title=Camp Delta Standard Operating Procedure |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160430004411/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Camp_Delta_Standard_Operating_Procedure |archive-date=30 April 2016 |access-date=15 May 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> The document revealed that some prisoners were off-limits to the [[International Committee of the Red Cross]], something that the US military had in the past denied repeatedly.<ref name="Reuters 15 November 2007">{{cite news |title=Guantanamo operating manual posted on Internet |date=15 November 2007 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSN1424207020071114?pageNumber=1 |work=[[Reuters]]|access-date =15 November 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222055914/https://www.reuters.com/article/newsOne/idUSN1424207020071114?pageNumber=1 |archive-date=22 December 2008 |url-status=live}}</ref> The Guantánamo Bay Manual included procedures for transferring prisoners and methods of evading protocols of the [[Geneva convention]].<ref name="guardian230208">{{cite news |last1=Leigh |first1=David |last2=Franklin |first2=Jonathan |title=Whistle while you work |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2008/feb/23/internet.usa |access-date=8 April 2021 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 February 2008 |language=en}}</ref>
* In February 2008, WikiLeaks released documents that it said showed involvement in [[money laundering]] and [[tax evasion]] at the [[Cayman Islands]] branch of the Swiss Bank [[Julius Baer Group|Julius Baer]] given to WikiLeaks by [[Rudolf Elmer]], which resulted in the bank [[Bank Julius Baer vs. WikiLeaks|suing WikiLeaks]] and obtaining an injunction which temporarily suspended the operation of wikileaks.org.<ref name="injunction">{{cite press release |title=Wikileaks.org under injunction |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks.org_under_injunction |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306005837/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks.org_under_injunction |archive-date=6 March 2008 |publisher=WikiLeaks |date=18 February 2008 |access-date=28 February 2008}}</ref> The California judge had [[Dynadot]], the service provider of WikiLeaks block the site's domain (wikileaks.org) on 18 February 2008. The website was instantly mirrored, and later that month the judge overturned his previous decision citing [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] concerns and questions about legal [[jurisdiction]].<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite news |url=http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/1039527/judge-rethinks-wikileaks |title=Judge reverses Wikileaks injunction |work=The Inquirer |place=London |date=2 March 2008 |author=Orion, Egan |access-date=23 September 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209125421/http://www.theinquirer.net/inquirer/news/1039527/judge-rethinks-wikileaks |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Gollner, Philipp |work=[[Reuters]]|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSN2927431720080229 |title=Judge reverses ruling in Julius Baer leak case |date=29 February 2008 |access-date=1 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210183558/https://www.reuters.com/article/internetNews/idUSN2927431720080229 |archive-date=10 December 2010 |url-status=live}}</ref>
* In March 2008, WikiLeaks published what it referred to as "the collected secret 'bibles' of [[Scientology]]", and three days later received letters threatening to sue them for breach of copyright.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/04/08/church_of_scientology_contacts_wikileaks/ |title=Scientology threatens Wikileaks with injunction |work=The Register |place=London |date=8 April 2008 |access-date=7 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215204305/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/04/08/church_of_scientology_contacts_wikileaks/ |archive-date=15 February 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>
* In September 2008, during the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 United States presidential election campaigns]], the contents of a Yahoo account belonging to Republican vice-presidential nominee [[Sarah Palin]] were [[Sarah Palin email hack|posted on WikiLeaks]] after being hacked by [[4chan]] user David Kernell.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://blog.wired.com/27bstroke6/2008/09/group-posts-e-m.html |magazine=Threat Level ([[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] blog) |author=Zetter, Kim |date=17 September 2008 |title=Group Posts E-Mail Hacked From Palin Account&nbsp;– Update |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090403071526/http://blog.wired.com/27bstroke6/2008/09/group-posts-e-m.html |archive-date=3 April 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/wiki/Sarah_Palin_Yahoo_account_2008 |title=Sarah Palin Yahoo account 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329143446/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Sarah_Palin_Yahoo_account_2008 |archive-date=29 March 2016 |access-date=15 May 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sarah Palin E-mail Hacker Sentenced to 1 Year in Custody |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/11/palin-hacker-sentenced/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref>
* In November 2008, the membership list of the far-right [[British National Party]] was posted to WikiLeaks, after appearing briefly on a weblog.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/7956824.stm |title='BNP membership' officer sacked |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=23 March 2009 |date=21 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326060319/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/7956824.stm |archive-date=26 March 2009 |url-status=live}}</ref> A year later, in October 2009, another list of BNP members was leaked, said by the BNP's leader, Nick Griffin, to be a 'malicious forgery'.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/oct/20/bnp-membership-list-wikileaks |title=BNP membership list leaked |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=20 October 2009 |place=London |first=Robert |last=Booth |date=20 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130130044736/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2009/oct/20/bnp-membership-list-wikileaks |archive-date=30 January 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2009 ===

* During 2008 and 2009, WikiLeaks published lists of forbidden or illegal web addresses for [[Internet censorship in Australia|Australia]], Denmark, Norway and Thailand. These were created to prevent access to [[child pornography]], but half the links are to unrelated sites, including online poker sites, YouTube links, regular gay and straight porn sites, Wikipedia entries, euthanasia sites, websites of fringe religions such as satanic sites, fetish sites, Christian sites, the website of a tour operator and even a Queensland dentist. Some Wikileaks pages were also added to the Australian blacklist after it published the Danish blacklist.<ref name="Fae-2009" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Oates, John |date=18 March 2009 |title=Aussie firewall blocks Wikileaks |work=The Register |place=London |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/03/18/aussie_firewall_wikileaks/ |url-status=live |access-date=17 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016213350/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2009/03/18/aussie_firewall_wikileaks/ |archive-date=16 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Moses, Asher |date=19 March 2009 |title=Leaked Australian blacklist reveals banned sites |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2009/03/19/1237054961100.html |url-status=live |access-date=19 March 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008013359/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2009/03/19/1237054961100.html |archive-date=8 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Internet Censorship in Thailand |url=http://secure.wikileaks.org/wiki/Internet_Censorship_in_Thailand |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080116070133/http://secure.wikileaks.org/wiki/Internet_Censorship_in_Thailand |archive-date=16 January 2008 |access-date=17 June 2010 |publisher=wikileaks.org}}</ref> According to Australian officials, some of the links published by WikiLeaks "have never been the subject of a complaint or ACMA investigation, and have never been included on the ACMA blacklist".<ref name="Fae-2009" />
* In January 2009, WikiLeaks released 86 telephone intercept recordings of Peruvian politicians and businessmen involved in the [[2008 Peru oil scandal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.terra.com.pe/noticias/noticias/act1609692/aparecen-86-nuevos-petroaudios-romulo-leon.html |title=Aparecen 86 nuevos petroaudios de Rómulo León |work=Terra Peru |language=es |place=Lima |date=28 January 2009 |access-date=8 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017060119/http://www.terra.com.pe/noticias/noticias/act1609692/aparecen-86-nuevos-petroaudios-romulo-leon.html |archive-date=17 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>
* In February, WikiLeaks cracked the encryption to and published NATO's Master Narrative for Afghanistan and three other classified or restricted NATO documents on the Pentagon Central Command (CENTCOM) site.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Wikileaks cracks NATO's Master Narrative for Afghanistan – WikiLeaks |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Wikileaks_cracks_NATO%27s_Master_Narrative_for_Afghanistan |access-date=1 May 2022 |website=wikileaks.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kushner |first=David |title=Click and Dagger: Inside WikiLeaks' Leak Factory |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/06/click-and-dagger-wikileaks-julian-assange-iraq-video-updated/ |access-date=1 May 2022 |website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |language=en-US}}</ref>
* During February, WikiLeaks released 6,780 [[Congressional Research Service]] reports<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/11/AR2009021101388.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122022922/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/02/11/AR2009021101388.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 January 2011 |title=Thousands of Congressional Reports Now Available Online |author=Krebs, Brian |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=11 February 2009 |access-date=7 December 2010}}</ref> followed in March by a set of documents belonging to [[Barclays Bank]] that had been ordered removed from the website of ''The Guardian''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/jul/06/wikileaks-wikipedia-indiana-jones |title=Read all about it |work=[[The Guardian]] |place=London |author=Luft, Oliver |date=6 July 2009 |access-date=7 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827011115/http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2009/jul/06/wikileaks-wikipedia-indiana-jones |archive-date=27 August 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>
* In July, WikiLeaks released a report disclosing a "serious nuclear accident" at the Iranian [[Nuclear facilities in Iran#Natanz|Natanz nuclear facility]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mirror.wikileaks.info/wiki/Serious_nuclear_accident_may_lay_behind_Iranian_nuke_chief%27s_mystery_resignation/ |title=Serious nuclear accident may lay behind Iranian nuke chief's mystery resignation |publisher=wikileaks |date=16 July 2009 |access-date=16 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203160534/http://mirror.wikileaks.info/wiki/Serious_nuclear_accident_may_lay_behind_Iranian_nuke_chief%27s_mystery_resignation/ |archive-date=3 December 2010 }}</ref> According to media reports, the accident may have been the direct result of a [[cyberattack|cyber-attack]] at [[Iran]]'s nuclear program, carried out with the [[Stuxnet]] computer worm, a [[cyberweapon|cyber-weapon]] allegedly built by the United States and [[Israel]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/09/27/6_mysteries_about_stuxnet |title=6 mysteries about Stuxnet |author=Hounshell, Blake |website=Passport (blog) |publisher=Foreign Policy |location=Washington DC |date=27 September 2010 |access-date=28 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209181744/http://blog.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2010/09/27/6_mysteries_about_stuxnet |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Woodward, Paul |url=http://warincontext.org/2010/09/26/iran-confirms-stuxnet-found-at-bushehr-nuclear-power-plant/ |title=Iran confirms Stuxnet found at Bushehr nuclear power plant |publisher=Warincontext.org |date=22 February 1999 |access-date=28 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209162332/http://warincontext.org/2010/09/26/iran-confirms-stuxnet-found-at-bushehr-nuclear-power-plant/ |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>
* In September, internal documents from [[Kaupthing Bank]] were leaked from shortly before the collapse of Iceland's banking sector, which had caused the [[2008–2012 Icelandic financial crisis]]. The document showed that suspiciously large sums of money were loaned to various owners of the bank, and large debts written off.<ref>{{cite web |title=Miklar hreyfingar rétt fyrir hrun |trans-title= Large movements just before crash |url=http://www.ruv.is/frett/miklar-hreyfingar-rett-fyrir-hrun |date=31 July 2009 |website=[[RÚV|Ríkisútvarpið (RÚV)]] |location=Reykjavik |language=is |access-date=22 September 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809051437/http://www.ruv.is/frett/miklar-hreyfingar-rett-fyrir-hrun |archive-date=9 August 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>
* In October, [[Joint Services Protocol 440]], a British document advising the security services on how to avoid documents being leaked, was published by WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tom |last=Chivers |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/defence/6261756/MoD-how-to-stop-leaks-document-is-leaked.html |title=MoD 'how to stop leaks' document is leaked |work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |location=London |date=5 October 2009 |access-date=6 October 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107215301/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/defence/6261756/MoD-how-to-stop-leaks-document-is-leaked.html |archive-date=7 January 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>
* In November, released 570,000 intercepts of pager messages sent on the day of the [[11 September attacks]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504383_162-5770280-504383.html?tag=mncol%3btxt/ |title=Egads! Confidential 9/11 Pager Messages Disclosed;November 2009 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502094524/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-504383_162-5770280-504383.html |archive-date=2 May 2011 |date=25 November 2009 |access-date=15 May 2016 |first=Declan |last=McCullagh |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2009/nov/25/september-11-wikileaks-pager-messages |title=9/11 re-enacted: Wikileaks publishes September 11 pager messages |work=[[The Guardian]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130908081324/http://www.theguardian.com/world/blog/2009/nov/25/september-11-wikileaks-pager-messages |archive-date=8 September 2013 |access-date=15 May 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Egads!_Confidential_9/11_Pager_Messages_Disclosed |title=Egads! Confidential 9/11 Pager Messages Disclosed |publisher=WikiLeaks |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091128081304/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Egads%21_Confidential_9/11_Pager_Messages_Disclosed |archive-date=28 November 2009 |access-date=15 May 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> These included messages sent from the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]], the [[FBI]], the [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] and the [[NYPD]], in response to the disaster.<ref name="yahoo041021">{{cite web |last1=Middis |first1=Jessie |title=The most shocking revelations to come from WikiLeaks |url=https://au.news.yahoo.com/on-this-day-the-most-shocking-revelations-to-come-from-wiki-leaks-210023597.html |website=au.news.yahoo.com |access-date=4 October 2021 |language=en-AU |date=4 October 2021}}</ref>

==== Trafigura report and super-injunction ====
In September 2009 Wikileaks published the ''Minton Report'', a scientific report about the [[2006 Ivory Coast toxic waste dump]]. The oil-trading firm [[Trafigura]] had illegally exported toxic waste and then had it dumped in [[Abidjan]], resulting in deaths and severe health problems in the local population. 30,000 claimants sued Trafigura in London, in one of the largest class-action suits brought before a British court.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 September 2009 |title='Dirty tricks' over toxic waste |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC News]]|location=London |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/newsnight/8260955.stm |quote=One of the largest class action lawsuits ever brought before the British courts is about to be settled. The case follows the illegal dumping of toxic waste in the Ivory Coast three years ago, which has been the subject of a continuing Newsnight investigation.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=21 May 2009 |title=Dumping ground |language=en |work=[[Al Jazeera English|Al-Jazeera]] |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/program/people-power/2009/5/21/dumping-ground |quote=In the largest class action in British history, human rights lawyer, Martyn Day, is representing 30,000 Ivorians against the world's third-largest oil trader, Trafigura.}}</ref> The company had its law firm [[Carter-Ruck|Carter{{nbh}}Ruck]] obtain a [[super-injunction]] to prevent discussion by the media of either the contents of the report or the existence of the injunction itself.<ref name="Fow20Traf">{{cite book |last1=Fowler |first1=Andrew |url=https://www.mup.com.au/books/the-most-dangerous-man-in-the-world-paperback-softback--1 |title=The Most Dangerous Man In The World: Julian Assange and WikiLeaks' Fight for Freedom |date=2020 |publisher=[[Melbourne University Press]] |isbn=9780522876857 |edition=2nd |location=Melbourne |pages=221–228}}</ref> Assange published two editorials on Wikileaks about the situation, writing:<ref name="Fow20Traf" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Assange |first1=Julian |date=14 October 2009 |title=Guardian Still Under Secret Toxic Waste Gag |work=WikiLeaks |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Guardian_still_under_secret_toxic_waste_gag |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501031410/https://www.wikileaks.org/wiki/Guardian_still_under_secret_toxic_waste_gag |archive-date=1 May 2012}}</ref>
{{blockquote|On September 14, WikiLeaks released the full Minton report in an attempt to undermine the injunction. The UK press was then left in the Kafkaesque position where neither the Minton report, nor the injunction against it could be mentioned, despite the report appearing on the front page of WikiLeaks.}}
Wikileaks maintained the report on its site and encouraged British journalists on the social network [[Twitter]] to break the censorship brought about by the injunction. After a question had been tabled about the report in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] under [[parliamentary privilege]], Trafigura's law firm Carter{{nbh}}Ruck said the injunction was ''[[sub judice]]'', which MPs worried could prevent discussion of the affair in parliament itself.<ref name="Fow20Traf" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Leigh |first1=David |date=15 October 2009 |title=Carter-Ruck in new move to stop debate in parliament |work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2009/oct/15/carter-ruck-trafigura-parliament-injunction}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Ponsford |first1=Dominic |date=19 October 2009 |title=Trafigura: 'Never again should a newspaper be barred from reporting Parliament' |work=[[Press Gazette]] |publisher=Progressive Media International |location=London |url=https://pressgazette.co.uk/archive-content/trafigura-never-again-should-a-newspaper-be-barred-from-reporting-parliament/}}</ref> The publicity generated about the easy availability of the report on the Wikileaks website, and subsequently its publication by the Norwegian broadcaster [[NRK]], led Carter-Ruck to agree to a modification of the injunction. The affair prompted a wider discussion in the British press about the continued use of super-injunctions.<ref name="Fow20Traf" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cohen |first1=Noam |date=19 October 2009 |title=Twitter and a Newspaper Untie a Gag Order |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/19/technology/internet/19link.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowers |first1=Mary |date=17 October 2009 |title=Trafigura Report on Dumped Waste in Ivory Coast Revealed |language=en |work=[[The Times]] |location=London |url=https://www.thetimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/article/trafigura-report-on-dumped-waste-in-ivory-coast-revealed-tsj8tcthszc}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=16 October 2009 |title=How the Trafigura story came to be told |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/oct/16/trafigura-carter-ruck-the-guardian}}</ref>

=== 2010 ===
{{Main|Iraq War documents leak|Afghan War documents leak}}
[[File:2007-07-12 sun measurement.png|thumb|Gun camera footage of the [[July 12, 2007, Baghdad airstrike|airstrike of 12 July 2007]] in Baghdad, showing the slaying of [[Namir Noor-Eldeen]] and a dozen other civilians by a US helicopter]]
In February WikiLeaks published a leaked diplomatic cable from the United States Embassy in Reykjavik relating to the [[Icesave dispute]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Classified_cable_from_US_Embassy_Reykjavik_on_Icesave,_13_Jan_2010 |title=Classified cable from US Embassy Reykjavik on Icesave, 13 Jan 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708204401/https://wikileaks.org/wiki/Classified_cable_from_US_Embassy_Reykjavik_on_Icesave%2C_13_Jan_2010 |archive-date=8 July 2011 |url-status=live }}. WikiLeaks. Retrieved 22 November 2011.</ref> The cable, known as [[Reykjavik 13]], was the first of the classified documents WikiLeaks published among those allegedly provided to them by [[Chelsea Manning]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Myers |first=Steven |date=6 July 2010 |title=Charges for Soldier Accused of Leak |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/07/world/middleeast/07wikileaks.html |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=guardian.co.uk |date=1 March 2013 |title=Bradley Manning's personal statement to court martial: full text |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/01/bradley-manning-wikileaks-statement-full-text |access-date=20 March 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

In March WikiLeaks released a secret 32-page [[US Department of Defense]] Counterintelligence Analysis Report, written in March 2008, that discusses the leaking of material by WikiLeaks and how it could be deterred.<ref name="USarmyintel">{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-20000469-38.html |title=U.S. Army worried about Wikileaks in secret report |last=Mccullagh |first=Declan |website=[[CNET]] News |date=15 March 2010 |access-date =15 March 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012034413/http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-20000469-38.html |archive-date=12 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/03/18/us/18wiki.html |title=Pentagon Sees a Threat From Online Muckrakers |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Stephanie |last=Strom |date=17 March 2010}}</ref> It also released a [[CIA]] report about the public relations strategies that would best be employed to shore up support for the Afghan war in Europe.<ref>{{cite web |title=CIA report into shoring up Afghan war support in Western Europe, 11 Mar 2010 |url=https://wikileaks.org/wiki/CIA_report_into_shoring_up_Afghan_war_support_in_Western_Europe,_11_Mar_2010 |website=WikiLeaks |date=26 March 2010}}{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}}</ref><ref name=ScNat10/><ref name=WaDeu10/> ''[[The Nation]]'' referred to it as a "call to arms for a propaganda war",<ref name=ScNat10>{{cite news |last1=Scahill |first1=Jeremy |title=WikiLeaks and War Crimes |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/archive/wikileaks-and-war-crimes/ |work=[[The Nation]] |date=12 August 2010}}</ref> and Albert Stahel of the Strategic Studies Institute in Zurich told ''[[Deutsche Welle]]'' that it is "a marketing concept. And the object of it is to manipulate the public".<ref name=WaDeu10>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Tamsin |title=War Marketing |url=https://www.dw.com/en/the-war-machine-and-freedom-of-thought/a-5475626 |work=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=26 July 2010 |language=en}}</ref>

In April a classified video of the [[12 July 2007 Baghdad airstrike]] was released, showing two [[Reuters]] employees being fired at after the pilots mistakenly thought the men were carrying weapons, which were in fact cameras.<ref>{{cite news |title=Video Shows U.S. Killing of Reuters Employees |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/06/world/middleeast/06baghdad.html |date=6 April 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |author1=Bumiller, Elisabeth |author2=Stelter, Brian |access-date=7 April 2010}}</ref> After the men were killed, the video shows US forces firing on a family van that stopped to pick up the bodies.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.netflix.com/WiPlayer?movieid=80003063 |title=WikiLeaks: War, Lies, and Videotape (2011 movie) |place=France |date=12 September 2011 |agency=Production Co: Premières Lignes Télévision |archive-url=https://archive.today/20141213202151/http://www.netflix.com/WiPlayer?movieid=80003063 |archive-date=13 December 2014}}</ref> Press reports of the number killed in the attacks vary from 12 to "over 18".<ref name="nytimes20100726">{{cite news|title=In Disclosing Secret Documents, WikiLeaks Seeks 'Transparency' |first=Eric |last=Schmitt |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/26/world/26wiki.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 July 2010 |access-date=27 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101210182456/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/26/world/26wiki.html?_r=1 |archive-date=10 December 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name="totalfatalities">{{cite news|author-link=Bill Keller|last=Keller|first=Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/30/magazine/30Wikileaks-t.html|title=Dealing With Assange and the WikiLeaks Secrets|work=[[The New York Times]]|format=adapted from introduction to the book ''Open Secrets''|date=26 January 2011|access-date=18 June 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120908/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/30/magazine/30Wikileaks-t.html|archive-date=8 September 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Among the dead were two journalists and two children were also wounded.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iraq war files: Apache Hellfire victims |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/iraq-war-files-the-apache-hellfire-victims |publisher=Channel 4 |date=22 October 2010 |access-date=27 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110212031306/http://www.channel4.com/news/iraq-war-files-the-apache-hellfire-victims |archive-date=12 February 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=US soldier on aftermath of WikiLeaks Apache attack |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/9136984.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=28 October 2010 |access-date=27 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209103443/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/9136984.stm |archive-date=9 February 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In June Manning was arrested after alleged chat logs were given to United States authorities by former hacker [[Adrian Lamo]], in whom she had confided. Manning reportedly told Lamo she had leaked the [[Collateral Murder video|"Collateral Murder" video]], a video of the [[Granai airstrike]] and about 260,000 diplomatic cables to WikiLeaks.<ref name="wired">{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/06/leak/ |author-link1=Kevin Poulsen |first1=Kevin |last1=Poulsen |author-link2=Kim Zetter |first2=Kim |last2=Zetter |title=U.S. Intelligence Analyst Arrested in Wikileaks Video Probe |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |place=New York |date=6 June 2010 |access-date=15 June 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027125007/http://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2010/06/leak/ |archive-date=27 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> Manning later said that before WikiLeaks, she tried approaching ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'' and [[Politico]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pilkington |first=Ed |date=28 February 2013 |title=Manning says he first tried to leak to Washington Post and New York Times |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/feb/28/manning-washington-post-new-york-times |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

In July WikiLeaks released [[Afghan War documents leak|92,000 documents]] related to the [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|war in Afghanistan]] between 2004 and the end of 2009 to the publications ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[Der Spiegel]]''. The documents detail individual incidents including "[[friendly fire]]" and civilian casualties.<ref name="guardian1">{{cite news |title=Afghanistan war logs: the unvarnished picture |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 July 2010 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/jul/25/afghanistan-war-logs-guardian-editorial?intcmp=239 |access-date=26 July 2010 |place=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728043710/http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2010/jul/25/afghanistan-war-logs-guardian-editorial?intcmp=239 |archive-date=28 July 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> WikiLeaks asked the [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] and human-rights groups to help remove names from the documents to reduce the potential harm caused by their release but did not receive assistance.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pentagon Slams WikiLeaks' Plan to Post More War Logs |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704407804575425900461793766?mod=WSJ_article_LatestHeadlines#articleTabs%3Darticle |access-date=13 August 2010 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=12 August 2010 |author=Barnes, Julian E. |author2=Whalen, Jeanne |place=New York |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015111311/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704407804575425900461793766.html?mod=WSJ_article_LatestHeadlines |archive-date=15 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref> WikiLeaks only reviewed about 2,000 documents in detail and used a tagging and keyword system. Assange said that a court might decide somethings were crimes, but added that "army personnel are basically engineers, who build roads and fire guns. They are frank and direct, and the top people mostly won't lie to you unless they're repeating a lie that someone else told them".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Crampton |first=Caroline |date=27 July 2010 |title=A rare glimpse of Julian Assange |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/science-tech/2010/07/afghanistan-documents-assange |access-date=21 January 2024 |website=New Statesman |language=en-US}}</ref>

After the [[Love Parade stampede]] in [[Duisburg]], Germany, on 24 July 2010, a local resident published internal documents of the city administration regarding the planning of Love Parade. The city government reacted by securing a [[court order]] on 16 August forcing the removal of the documents from the website on which it was hosted.<ref>{{cite news |first=Konrad |last=Lischka |url=http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/0,1518,712408,00.html |title=Einstweilige Verfügung&nbsp;– Duisburg verbietet Blogger-Veröffentlichung zur Love Parade |language=de |work=Der Spiegel |date=18 August 2010 |place=Hamburg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224220127/http://www.spiegel.de/netzwelt/netzpolitik/0%2C1518%2C712408%2C00.html |archive-date=24 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 20 August 2010, WikiLeaks released 43 internal documents regarding the Love Parade 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/wikileaks-releases-documents-on-love-parade-tragedy/story-e6frfrnr-1225908260011 |title=WikiLeaks releases documents on Love Parade tragedy |work=news.com.au Technology |date=21 August 2010 |agency=NewsCore |place=Sydney |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012015126/http://www.news.com.au/technology/wikileaks-releases-documents-on-love-parade-tragedy/story-e6frfrnr-1225908260011 |archive-date=12 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>

After the leak of information concerning the Afghan War, in October 2010, around [[Iraq War documents leak|400,000 documents]] relating to the [[Iraq War]] were released. The [[United States Department of Defense|US Department of Defense]] referred to the Iraq War Logs as "the largest leak of classified documents in its history". Media coverage of the leaked documents emphasised claims that the US government had ignored reports of [[torture]] by the Iraqi authorities during the period after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 war]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Huge Wikileaks release shows US 'ignored Iraq torture' |work=[[BBC News]] |date=23 October 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-11611319 |access-date=23 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720082422/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-11611319 |archive-date=20 July 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== United States diplomatic cables leak ===
{{Main|United States diplomatic cables leak|Contents of the United States diplomatic cables leak|l2=contents|Reactions to the United States diplomatic cables leak|l3=reactions}}

On 28 November 2010 WikiLeaks and ''[[El País]]'', ''[[Le Monde]]'', ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', ''[[The Guardian]]'', and ''The New York Times'' started simultaneously to publish the first 220 of 251,287 leaked documents labelled confidential&nbsp;– but not top-secret&nbsp;– and dated from 28 December 1966 to 28 February 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Shane |first=Scott |title=Leaked Cables Offer Raw Look at U.S. Diplomacy |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/29/world/29cables.html|access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=28 November 2010 |author2=Lehren, Andrew W.}}</ref><ref name="manila">{{cite news |last=Suarez |first=Kris Danielle |url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/11/29/10/1796-memos-us-embassy-manila-wikileaks-cablegate |title=1,796 Memos from US Embassy in Manila in WikiLeaks 'Cablegate' |work=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=30 November 2010 |access-date=19 December 2010 |place=Manila |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927221008/http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/11/29/10/1796-memos-us-embassy-manila-wikileaks-cablegate |archive-date=27 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>
[[File:Wikileaks protest Madrid 11th December 2.jpg|thumb|WikiLeaks supporters protest in front of the [[Embassy of the United Kingdom, Madrid|British Embassy]] in Madrid, 11 December 2010.]]

The [[Contents of the United States diplomatic cables leak|contents of the diplomatic cables]] include numerous unguarded comments and revelations regarding: US diplomats gathering personal information about [[Ban Ki-moon]], Secretary-General of the United Nations, and other top UN officials; critiques and praises about the host countries of various United States embassies; political manoeuvring regarding [[climate change]]; discussion and resolutions towards ending ongoing tension in the Middle East; efforts and resistance towards [[nuclear disarmament]]; actions in the [[War on Terror]]; assessments of other threats around the world; dealings between various countries; United States [[Military intelligence|intelligence]] and [[counterintelligence]] efforts; and other diplomatic actions. [[Reactions to the United States diplomatic cables leak]] varied. The [[2010–2011 Tunisian protests|overthrow of the presidency in Tunisia]] of 2011 has been attributed partly to reaction against the corruption revealed by leaked cables.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/jan/13/tunisia-youth-revolution |title=Tunisia's youth finally has revolution on its mind |work='Comment is Free' blog (The Guardian) |author=Sam |date=13 January 2011 |access-date=20 January 2011 |place=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126223120/http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2011/jan/13/tunisia-youth-revolution |archive-date=26 January 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://wikileaks.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/01/13/wikileaks_and_the_tunisia_protests?sms_ss=twitter&at_xt=4d2ffe4d9c2649d7,1 |title=The First WikiLeaks Revolution? |author=Dickinson, Elizabeth |date=13 January 2011 |work=Foreign Policy |place=Washington DC |access-date=20 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209174447/http://wikileaks.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2011/01/13/wikileaks_and_the_tunisia_protests?sms_ss=twitter&at_xt=4d2ffe4d9c2649d7%2C1 |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

According to the former [[Ambassadors of the United States|US Ambassador]] to [[Cameroon]] from 2004 to 2007, [[R. Niels Marquardt|Niels Marquardt]], Marafa Hamidou Yaya was arrested on "entirely unproven corruption charges", subjected to a "[[kangaroo court]]", and given a 25-year prison sentence. Marquardt said Marafa's only crime was having told him that he "might be interested" in the presidency one day. According to Marquardt, when Wikileaks released the cable in which this was mentioned, it became front-page news in Cameroon and led directly to Marafa's arrest.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks Damage Lives On: The Case of Marafa Hamidou Yaya |url=https://afsa.org/wikileaks-damage-lives-case-marafa-hamidou-yaya |access-date=26 February 2023 |website=afsa.org}}</ref> The U.S. ambassador at the time, [[Robert P. Jackson|Robert Jackson]], said Marafa's trial did not specify the evidence against him.<ref name=":0" />

==== Unredacted cable release ====

===== Background =====
In August 2010, Assange gave ''[[The Guardian|Guardian]]'' journalist [[David Leigh (journalist)|David Leigh]] an [[Key (cryptography)|encryption key]] and a URL where he could locate the file containing the U.S. diplomatic cables. In February 2011 David Leigh and [[Luke Harding (journalist)|Luke Harding]] of ''The Guardian'' published the book ''[[WikiLeaks: Inside Julian Assange's War on Secrecy]]'' containing the encryption key. Leigh said he believed the key was a temporary one that would expire within days. Wikileaks supporters disseminated the encrypted files to [[mirror site]]s in December 2010 after Wikileaks experienced cyber-attacks. When Wikileaks learned what had happened it notified the [[US State Department]]. On 25 August 2011 the German magazine ''[[Der Freitag]]'' published an article giving details which would enable people to piece the information together.<ref name="Ball-2011b2">{{cite news |last=Ball |first=James |date=1 September 2011 |title=WikiLeaks prepares to release unredacted US cables Media guardian.co.uk |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/01/wikileaks-prepares-unredacted-us-cables |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212090525/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2011/sep/01/wikileaks-prepares-unredacted-us-cables |archive-date=12 February 2013}}. Guardian. Retrieved 5 September 2011.</ref>

===== Release =====
WikiLeaks posted some unredacted cables before their media partners edited them, but later redacted them.<ref name=":26">{{Cite web |last=Ungerleider |first=Neal |date=14 January 2011 |title=The Newest WikiLeaks Problem: Unredacted Cables |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1717414/newest-wikileaks-problem-unredacted-cables |website=[[Fast Company]]}}</ref>

In January 2011, several unredacted cables not on the WikiLeaks website were posted online by an associate of WikiLeaks, [[Israel Shamir]]. The cables included the names of people implied to be connected to bribery, and highly suggestive clues about the identity of an American informant. Shamir explained: "Handing confidential and secret information to everybody is the thing of Wikileaks. That's what it is about. Your question is like asking police why they catch thieves. That is what they are for."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ungerleider |first=Neal |date=12 January 2011 |title=Unredacted WikiLeaks Cables Leaked to Internet |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1716675/unredacted-wikileaks-cables-leaked-internet |access-date=5 August 2022 |website=Fast Company |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":26" /> [[Yulia Latynina]], writing in ''[[The Moscow Times]],'' alleged that Shamir concocted a cable which allegedly quoted European Union diplomats' plans to walk out of the [[Durban II]] speech by Iranian president [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]], for publication in the pro-Putin ''Russian Reporter'' in December 2010.<ref name="NYM20111214">{{cite news |last=Tiku |first=Nitasha |date=14 December 2011 |title=WikiLeaks May Employ an Anti-Semitic Holocaust Denier |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2010/12/wikileaks_may_employ_an_antise.html |access-date=10 January 2021 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]}}</ref><ref name=":36">{{Cite web |last=Moynihan |first=Michael |date=14 December 2010 |title=Assange's Extremist Employees |url=https://reason.com/2010/12/14/the-assange-employees/ |access-date=5 August 2022 |website=Reason.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="moscowtimes_shamir_freelance">{{cite news |last=von Twickel |first=Nikolaus |date=10 December 2010 |title=Putin Bristles Over Leaked U.S. Cables |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/putin-bristles-over-leaked-us-cables/426044.html |access-date=22 December 2010 |publisher=The [[Moscow Times]]}}</ref> Shamir has denied this accusation.<ref name="moscowtimes_shamir_freelance" />

On 29 August, WikiLeaks published over 130,000 unredacted cables.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Poulsen |first=Kim Zetter and Kevin |title=WikiLeaks Springs a Leak: Full Database of Diplomatic Cables Appears Online |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/08/wikileaks-leak/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |access-date=23 November 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=30 August 2011 |title=Australia condemns 'irresponsible' Wikileaks cable leak |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-14722030 |access-date=23 November 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – Wikileaks Statement on the 9 Month Anniversary of Cablegate: Release of 133,887 Cables |url=https://wikileaks.org/Wikileaks-Statement-on-the-9-Month.html |access-date=23 November 2022 |website=wikileaks.org}}</ref> On 31 August, WikiLeaks tweeted<ref>{{Cite web |last=WikiLeaks |date=31 August 2011 |title=ANNOUNCE: Use a "magnet" compatible Bit Torrent client to download the following encrypted |url=https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/108952065325268992 |access-date=23 November 2022 |website=[[Twitter]] |language=en}}</ref> a link to a torrent of the encrypted data.<ref name="Estes-20112">{{Cite web |last=Estes |first=Adam Clark |date=2 September 2011 |title=The End of WikiLeaks As We Know It |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2011/09/end-wikileaks-we-know-it/338353/ |access-date=23 November 2022 |website=[[The Atlantic]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Stöcker-2011a2">{{Cite news |last=Stöcker |first=Christian |date=1 September 2011 |title=Leak at WikiLeaks: A Dispatch Disaster in Six Acts |language=en |work=Der Spiegel |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/world/leak-at-wikileaks-a-dispatch-disaster-in-six-acts-a-783778.html |access-date=23 November 2022 |issn=2195-1349}}</ref> On 1 September 2011, WikiLeaks announced that an encrypted version of the un-redacted US State Department cables had been available via [[BitTorrent]] for months and that the [[Key (cryptography)|decryption key]] was available. WikiLeaks said that on 2 September it would publish the entire, unredacted archive in searchable form on its website.<ref name="Ball-2011b2" /><ref name="Stöcker-2011b2">{{cite news |last1=Stöcker |first1=Christian |date=September 2011 |title=Leak at WikiLeaks: A Dispatch Disaster in Six Acts – SPIEGEL ONLINE – News – International |newspaper=Der Spiegel |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,783778,00.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111104230036/http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,783778,00.html |archive-date=4 November 2011}}. Spiegel.de. Retrieved 5 September 2011.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – Guardian journalist negligently disclosed Cablegate passwords |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/Guardian-journalist-negligently.html |access-date=10 March 2023 |website=www.wikileaks.org}}</ref> According to Assange, Wikileaks did this so that possible targets could be informed and better defend themselves and to provide a reliable source for the leaks.<ref>{{cite news |date=25 February 2020 |title=WikiLeaks password 'leaked by journalists' – 9News |work=www.9news.com.au |agency=AAP |url=https://www.9news.com.au/world/us-pondered-poisoning-assange-court-told/919d931e-f6cf-4974-aa8c-6bcfcf9a51a8 |access-date=20 September 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Marks |first1=Paul |date=6 September 2011 |title=Assange: Why WikiLeaks was right to release raw cables |work=New Scientist |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn20869-assange-why-wikileaks-was-right-to-release-raw-cables/?ignored=irrelevant}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stöcker |first1=Christian |date=1 September 2011 |title=Leak at WikiLeaks: A Dispatch Disaster in Six Acts |language=en |work=Der Spiegel |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/0,1518,783778,00.html}}</ref> Glenn Greenwald wrote that "the best and safest course was to release all the cables in full, so that not only the world's intelligence agencies but everyone had them, so that steps could be taken to protect the sources and so that the information in them was equally available".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwald |first1=Glenn |date=2 September 2011 |title=Facts and myths in the WikiLeaks/Guardian saga |url=https://www.salon.com/2011/09/02/wikileaks_28/ |website=[[Salon.com|Salon]]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Ball |first=James |date=2 September 2011 |title=WikiLeaks publishes full cache of unredacted cables |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/02/wikileaks-publishes-cache-unredacted-cables |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref>

The US cited the release in the opening of its request for extradition of Assange, saying his actions put lives at risk.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 February 2020 |title=Julian Assange 'put lives at risk' by sharing unredacted files |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51616077}}</ref> The defence gave evidence it said would show that Assange was careful to protect lives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goodwyn |first1=Bill |title=Julian Assange held back 15,000 documents to prevent harm to US government |language=en |work=ComputerWeekly.com |url=https://www.computerweekly.com/news/252489133/Julian-Assange-held-back-15000-documents-to-prevent-harm-to-US-government}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=MacAskill |first1=Andrew |date=16 September 2020 |title=WikiLeaks' Assange was careful to protect informants, court hears |language=en |work=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/britain-assange-idUSL4N2GD2PZ}}</ref> John Young, the owner and operator of the website [[Cryptome]] testified at Assange's extradition hearing that the unredacted cables were published by Cryptome on 1 September, the day before Wikileaks. Young testified that "no US law enforcement authority has notified me that this publication of the cables is illegal, consists or contributes to a crime in any way, nor have they asked for them to be removed".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Quinn |first1=Ben |date=24 September 2020 |title=US has never asked WikiLeaks rival to remove leaked cables, court told |language=en |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2020/sep/24/us-never-asked-wikileaks-rival-cryptome-remove-leaked-cables-court-told-assange}}</ref>

The ''Guardian'' wrote that the decision to publish the cables in a searchable form was made by Assange alone, a decision that it, and its four previous media partners, condemned.<ref name="Ball-2011c2">{{Cite web |date=2 September 2011 |title=WikiLeaks publishes full cache of unredacted cables |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/02/wikileaks-publishes-cache-unredacted-cables |access-date=30 January 2023 |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name="BBCNews-20112">{{Cite news |date=2 September 2011 |title=Anger as Wikileaks releases all US cables unredacted |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-14765837 |access-date=14 October 2022}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', several thousand files in the archive were marked "strictly protect" which indicated officials thought sources could be endangered by their release.<ref name="BBCNews-20112" /><ref name="Ball-2011a2">{{Cite web |date=2 September 2011 |title=WikiLeaks publishes full cache of unredacted cables |url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/02/wikileaks-publishes-cache-unredacted-cables |access-date=14 October 2022 |website=[[The Guardian]] |language=en}}</ref> In a joint statement, ''The Guardian'', ''[[El País]]'', ''[[New York Times]]'' and ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' said they "deplore the decision of WikiLeaks to publish the unredacted state department cables, which may put sources at risk" and "we cannot defend the needless publication of the complete data – indeed, we are united in condemning it."<ref name="BBCNews-20112" /><ref name="Ball-2011a2" /> [[Le Monde]] said it would also sign the statement.<ref name="BBCNews-20112" /> In response, WikiLeaks accused ''The Guardian'' of false statements and nepotism.<ref name="BBCNews-20112" /> Out of concern for those involved, [[Reporters Without Borders]] temporarily suspended their WikiLeaks mirror.<ref name="BBCNews-20112" /><ref name=":31">{{Cite web |date=16 October 2011 |title=Reporters Without Borders temporarily suspends its WikiLeaks mirror site – Reporters Without Borders |url=https://en.rsf.org/reporters-without-borders-01-09-2011,40905.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016052151/https://en.rsf.org/reporters-without-borders-01-09-2011,40905.html |archive-date=16 October 2011 |access-date=14 October 2022}}</ref> According to ''The Guardian'', "the newly published archive" contained "more than 1,000 cables identifying individual [[Activism|activists]]; several thousand labelled with a tag used by the US to mark sources it believes could be placed in danger; and more than 150 specifically mentioning [[whistleblowers]]".<ref name="Ball-2011c2" />

According to media reports, after WikiLeaks published the unredacted cables, Ethiopian journalist Argaw Ashine was interrogated several times about a reference to him in a cable talking to a government source. The source told him about plans to arrest the editors of the critical Ethiopian weekly ''[[Addis Neger (newspaper)|Addis Neger]]'', who fled the country a month after talking to Ashine. Ashine was subjected to government harassment and intimidation and was forced to flee the country.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Simon |first=Joel |date=19 September 2011 |title=In Ethiopia case, a response to WikiLeaks |url=https://cpj.org/2011/09/in-ethiopia-case-a-response-to-wikileaks/ |access-date=26 February 2023 |website=Committee to Protect Journalists |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=15 September 2011 |title=Wikileaks cable: Ethiopia reporter Argaw Ashine 'flees' |language=en-GB |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-14929307 |access-date=26 February 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=15 September 2011 |title=WikiLeaks-named Ethiopian reporter in unredacted cable flees country in fear |language=en-GB |work=[[The Guardian]] |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/sep/15/wikileaks-named-ethiopian-reporter-flees |access-date=26 February 2023 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

The U.S. established an Information Review Task Force (IRTF) to investigate the impact of WikiLeaks' publications. According to IRTF reports, the leaks could cause "serious damage" and "the lives of cooperating Afghans, Iraqis, and other foreign interlocutors have been placed at increased risk".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Leopold |first=Jason |date=11 April 2019 |title=Here Are The Never-Before-Seen US Government Damage Reports Made In The WikiLeaks Aftermath |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/jasonleopold/here-are-the-never-before-seen-us-government-damage-reports |access-date=22 October 2023 |website=BuzzFeed News |language=en}}</ref> In 2013, the task force's head, Brigadier General Robert Carr, testified at [[Chelsea Manning]]'s sentencing hearing. Carr said under questioning from the defence counsel that the task force had no specific examples of anyone who had lost their life due to WikiLeaks' publication of material provided by Manning.<ref name=Pil13/><ref name=Hoo19>{{cite news |last1=Hooton |first1=Amanda |title=Love him or hate him or simply don't care, Julian Assange's fight for freedom concerns us all |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/love-him-or-hate-him-or-simply-don-t-care-julian-assange-s-fight-for-freedom-concerns-us-all-20191202-p53g1q.html|location=Sydney|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=Nine Group |date=7 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Carroll |first1=Lauren |title=McCain says Taliban 'murdered' people because of Chelsea Manning and WikiLeaks|date=2017|location=St. Petersburg, FL |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2017/feb/01/john-mccain/mccain-says-taliban-murdered-people-because-chelse/ |website=[[PolitiFact]] |publisher=[[Poynter Institute]]}}</ref><ref name=Mau20>{{cite news |last1=Maurizi |first1=Stephania |title=Julian Assange is the defendant, journalism is under trial |url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2020/03/02/julian-assange-is-the-defendant-journalism-is-under-trial/5722796/ |work=Il Fatto Quotidiano |date=2 March 2020 |language=it-IT}}</ref> Ed Pilkington wrote in ''The Guardian'' that Carr's testimony significantly undermined the argument that WikiLeaks' publications put lives at risk.<ref name=Pil13>{{cite web |last1=Pilkington |first1=Ed |title=Bradley Manning leak did not result in deaths by enemy forces, court hears |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/31/bradley-manning-sentencing-hearing-pentagon |website=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=1 April 2023 |date=31 July 2013}}</ref> In 2020, a lawyer for the US said that "sources, whose redacted names and other identifying information was contained in classified documents published by Wikileaks, who subsequently disappeared, although the US can't prove at this point that their disappearance was the result of being outed by Wikileaks."<ref>{{Cite news |date=24 February 2020 |title=Julian Assange 'put lives at risk' by sharing unredacted files |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51616077 |access-date=22 October 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mediapoint |first=P. A. |date=24 February 2020 |title=Julian Assange extradition: Sources 'disappeared' after names exposed by Wikileaks, court hears |url=https://pressgazette.co.uk/news/julian-assange-extradition-sources-disappeared-after-names-exposed-by-wikileaks-court-hears/ |access-date=22 October 2023 |website=Press Gazette |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Johnson |first=Jamie |date=24 February 2020 |title=Julian Assange 'put lives at risk' by publishing classified documents, court hears |language=en-GB |work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2020/02/24/julian-assange-extradition-hearing-wikileaks-founder-us/ |access-date=22 October 2023 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref>

=== 2011–2015 ===
{{Main|Guantanamo Bay files leak|Global Intelligence Files leak|Syria Files|Stratfor email leak}}

In late April 2011, files related to the Guantanamo prison were released.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Guantanamo Files - NYTimes.com |url=https://www.nytimes.com/projects/gitmo/index.html |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=www.nytimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=9 July 2013 |title=Witness: No harm to US from leaked Gitmo files |url=https://apnews.com/article/d7af3f662e7a4afd8aae2a5a6f25e25c |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=AP News |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks releases secret Guantanamo prison files |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/privacy/wikileaks-releases-secret-guantanamo-prison-files/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=CNET |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dorling |first=Philip |date=20 June 2015 |title=WikiLeaks 'Saudi Cables' reveal secret Saudi government influence in Australia |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/wikileaks-saudi-cables-reveal-secret-saudi-government-influence-in-australia-20150620-ght4kp.html |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=The Sydney Morning Herald |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wikileaks.org/gitmo/ |title=The Guantanamo Files |publisher=WikiLeaks |access-date=2 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326090615/https://wikileaks.org/gitmo/ |archive-date=26 March 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2011, WikiLeaks started to release the ''Spy Files''.<ref name=":34">{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Unveils 160 Firms' Surveillance Gear Sales Docs, Still No Submissions System |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/12/01/wikileaks-unveils-160-firms-surveillance-gear-sales-docs-still-no-submission-system/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230515202946/http://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2011/12/01/wikileaks-unveils-160-firms-surveillance-gear-sales-docs-still-no-submission-system/ |archive-date=15 May 2023 |access-date=27 January 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en }}</ref> On 27 February 2012, WikiLeaks began publishing more than five million emails from the Texas-headquartered "global intelligence" company [[Stratfor]],<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 February 2012 |title=WikiLeaks targets global risk company Stratfor |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/wikileaks-stratfor-idUSL5E8DR0120120227/ |website=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wikileaks.org/the-gifiles.html |title=The Global Intelligence Files |publisher=WikiLeaks |access-date=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110190753/http://wikileaks.org/the-gifiles.html |archive-date=10 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Fisher |first=Max |date=27 February 2012 |title=Stratfor Is a Joke and So Is Wikileaks for Taking It Seriously |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/02/stratfor-is-a-joke-and-so-is-wikileaks-for-taking-it-seriously/253681/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=The Atlantic |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Norrie |first=Justin |date=27 February 2012 |title=Wikileaks email dump exposes dark machinations of security firm Stratfor |url=http://theconversation.com/wikileaks-email-dump-exposes-dark-machinations-of-security-firm-stratfor-5588 |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=The Conversation |language=en-US}}</ref> and on 5 July 2012, WikiLeaks began publishing the [[Syria Files]], both had given to WikiLeaks by [[Anonymous (hacker group)|Anonymous]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Anonymous, hacktivists helped WikiLeaks with 'Syrian Files' |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/anonymous-hacktivists-helped-wikileaks-with-syrian-files/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/syria-files/ |title=Syria Files |publisher=WikiLeaks |access-date=5 July 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120705131002/http://wikileaks.org/syria-files/ |archive-date=5 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=5 July 2012 |title=Syria-gate? WikiLeaks' latest drop of secret files |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/syria-gate-wikileaks-latest-drop-secret-files-flna864131 |access-date=20 March 2024 |publisher=NBC News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |first1=Dell |last1=Cameron |first2=Patrick Howell |last2=O'Neill |date=9 September 2016 |title=WikiLeaks release excludes evidence of €2 billion transfer from Syria to Russia |url=https://www.dailydot.com/debug/wikileaks-syria-files-syria-russia-bank-2-billion/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=The Daily Dot |language=en-US}}</ref> Outlets reported that the Stratfor emails had malware.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Williams |first=Chris |title=Wicked WikiLeaks leaks considered harmful: Alert over malware lurking in dumped docs |url=https://www.theregister.com/2015/07/17/wikileaks_malware_warning/ |website=[[The Register]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Steier |first=Henning |date=17 July 2015 |title=Vorsicht vor Wikileaks-Dokumenten |url=https://www.nzz.ch/digital/vorsicht-vor-wikileaks-dokumenten-ld.1082 |access-date=29 January 2024 |work=Neue Zürcher Zeitung |language=de-CH |issn=0376-6829}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=1 September 2015 |title=WikiLeaks Data Dump Contains Malware Docs, Accessing Can Infect Your System |url=https://www.hackread.com/wikileaks-data-malware-documents/ |access-date=29 January 2024 |website=www.hackread.com |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=30 March 2015 |title=Wikileaks Global Intelligence File Dump is Loaded With Malicious Software |url=https://www.joshwieder.net/2015/03/wikileaks-global-intelligence-file-dump.html |access-date=29 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=31 March 2015 |title=Wikileaks Malware Analysis Continued |url=https://www.joshwieder.net/2015/03/wikileaks-malware-analysis-continued.html |access-date=29 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=13 July 2015 |title=Hector Monsegur (formerly sabu of Lulzsec) has responded to my analysis of the Wikileaks Global Intelligence Files |url=https://www.joshwieder.net/2015/07/hector-monsegur-formerly-sabu-of.html |access-date=29 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=15 July 2015 |title=Malware discovered in the Stratfor email file dump provided by Wikileaks is not limited to torrents – curated content on the Wikileaks website also infected |url=https://www.joshwieder.net/2015/07/wikileaks-stratfor-email-malware.html |access-date=29 January 2024}}</ref> On 25 October 2012, WikiLeaks began publishing The Detainee Policies, files covering the rules and procedures for detainees in US military custody.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Announces 'The Detainee Policies': A History Of U.S. Post-9/11 Military Prisoners In Leaked Documents |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2012/10/25/wikileaks-announces-the-detainee-policies-a-history-of-american-military-detainees-in-leaked-documents/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wikileaks.org/Press-Release-The-Detainee.html |title=Press Release: The Detainee Policies |publisher=Wikileaks.org |date=25 October 2012 |access-date=19 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407091518/https://wikileaks.org/Press-Release-The-Detainee.html |archive-date=7 April 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> In April 2013 WikiLeaks republished more than 1.7 million declassified US diplomatic and intelligence documents from the 1970s, including the [[Kissinger cables]], from the [[National Archives and Records Administration]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Byford |first=Sam |date=8 April 2013 |title=WikiLeaks' 'Kissinger Cables' is largest release ever with over 1.7 million diplomatic records |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/4/8/4195664/wikileaks-publishes-kissinger-cables-and-launches-plusd |access-date=12 October 2023 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref>

[[File:Secret Laws,placard in front of Ecuador embassy.jpg|thumb|Placard in front of [[Embassy of Ecuador, London|Embassy of Ecuador]], London, 22 August 2012]]In September 2013, WikiLeaks published "Spy Files 3", 250 documents from more than 90 surveillance companies.<ref name="SpyFiles3">{{cite web |url=http://www.dn.no/forsiden/utenriks/article2676194.ece |title=Wikileaks overvåket 20 overvåkningssjefer |author=DN.no |publisher=Dn.no |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010012941/http://www.dn.no/forsiden/utenriks/article2676194.ece |archive-date=10 October 2013 |url-status=live|access-date=2 March 2014}}</ref> On 13 November 2013, a draft of the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]]'s Intellectual Property Rights chapter was published by WikiLeaks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/nov/13/wikileaks-trans-pacific-partnership-chapter-secret |title=WikiLeaks publishes secret draft chapter of Trans-Pacific Partnership |first=Steven |last=Musil |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=12 November 2013 |access-date=15 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209164317/http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/nov/13/wikileaks-trans-pacific-partnership-chapter-secret |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wikileaks.org/tpp/ |title=Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) |publisher=WikiLeaks |access-date=13 November 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113130522/http://wikileaks.org/tpp/ |archive-date=13 November 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2014, WikiLeaks published files from Gamma Group International, including what WikiLeaks called "weaponised [[malware]]".<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks posts 'weaponized malware' for all to download |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/wikileaks-posts-weaponized-malware-for-all-to-download/ |access-date=21 October 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref> On 10 June 2015, WikiLeaks published the draft on the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership]]'s Transparency for Healthcare Annex, along with each country's negotiating position.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/medicines-to-cost-more-and-healthcare-will-suffer-according-to-wikileaks-documents-20150610-ghkxp0.html |website=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |title=Medicines to cost more and healthcare will suffer, according to Wikileaks documents |last=Dorling |first=Philip |date=10 June 2015 |access-date=17 April 2022}}</ref> On 19 June 2015 WikiLeaks began publishing documents from the Saudi Foreign Ministry that contain secret communications from various Saudi Embassies.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=19 June 2015 |title=WikiLeaks Just Leaked Secret Cables from Saudi Arabia |url=https://time.com/3928584/wikileaks-saudi-arabia-cables/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |magazine=TIME |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wikileaks.org/saudi-cables/press |title=The Saudi Cables |publisher=wikileaks.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=23 August 2016 |title=Private lives are exposed as WikiLeaks spills its secrets |url=https://apnews.com/article/b70da83fd111496dbdf015acbb7987fb |access-date=20 March 2024 |website=AP News |language=en}}</ref>

[[File:Londres, Reunión con Julian Assange (9504697280).jpg|thumb|WikiLeaks supporters protest in front of the [[Embassy of Ecuador, London|Ecuadorian embassy]] in London.]]
In June and July 2015, WikiLeaks published a [[List of material published by WikiLeaks#NSA spying|series of documents on NSA spying]], which showed that [[National Security Agency|NSA]] spied on the French,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Guiton |first1=Amaelle |last2=Lechenet |first2=Alexandre |last3=Manach |first3=Jean-Marc |last4=Assange |first4=Avec Julian |date=23 June 2015 |title=WikiLeaks – Chirac, Sarkozy et Hollande : trois présidents sur écoute |url=http://www.liberation.fr/monde/2015/06/23/chirac-sarkozy-et-hollande-trois-presidents-sur-ecoute_1335767 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624015443/http://www.liberation.fr/monde/2015/06/23/chirac-sarkozy-et-hollande-trois-presidents-sur-ecoute_1335767 |archive-date=24 June 2015 |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=Liberation Monde |language=French}}</ref> German,<ref>{{cite web |author=kwi |date=9 July 2015 |title=Wikileaks: Und täglich grüßt die NSA |url=https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/deutschland/wikileaks-und-taeglich-gruesst-die-nsa/12034888.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018075016/https://www.handelsblatt.com/politik/deutschland/wikileaks-und-taeglich-gruesst-die-nsa/12034888.html |archive-date=18 October 2017 |access-date=12 March 2017 |publisher=handelsblatt.com}}</ref> Brazilian<ref>{{cite web |last1=Greenwald |first1=Glenn |last2=Miranda |first2=David |date=4 July 2015 |title=NSA'S Top Brazilian Political and Financial Targets Revealed by Wikileaks Disclosure |url=https://firstlook.org/theintercept/2015/07/04/nsa-top-brazilian-political-and-financial-targets-wikileaks/ |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=The Intercept |archive-date=16 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816112647/https://firstlook.org/theintercept/2015/07/04/nsa-top-brazilian-political-and-financial-targets-wikileaks |url-status=dead }}</ref> and Japanese<ref name=":1">{{cite web |last=Dorling |first=Philip |date=31 July 2015 |title=Exclusive: US bugs Japan on trade and climate |url=https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2015/07/31/exclusive-us-bugs-japan-trade-and-climate/14383094602196 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150804075641/https://www.thesaturdaypaper.com.au/news/politics/2015/07/31/exclusive-us-bugs-japan-trade-and-climate/14383094602196 |archive-date=4 August 2015 |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=The Saturday Paper}}</ref> governments. The documents also detailed an economic espionage against French companies and associations and extensive monitoring of the Japanese economy and Japanese companies such as [[Mitsubishi]] and [[Mitsui]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{cite web |date=29 June 2015 |title=NSA soll auch französische Wirtschaft bespizelt haben |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/wikileaks-enthuellung-nsa-soll-auch-franzoesische-wirtschaft-bespitzelt-haben-a-1041268.html |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=Spiegel Ausland |language=German}}</ref>

On 29 July 2015, WikiLeaks published a top-secret letter from the [[Trans-Pacific Partnership|Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement]] (TPP) Ministerial Meeting in December 2013 which illustrated the position of negotiating countries on "[[state-owned enterprise]]s" (SOEs).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hageluken |first1=Alexander |last2=Goetz |first2=John |date=29 July 2015 |title=Kommerz statt Sozialstaat |url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/wirtschaft/usa-vs-staatsbetriebe-kommerz-statt-sozialstaat-1.2586908 |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=Sueddeutsche Zeitung |language=German}}</ref> On 21 October 2015 WikiLeaks published some of [[John O. Brennan]]'s emails, including a draft security clearance application which contained personal information.<ref>{{cite news |date=21 October 2015 |title=Wikileaks claims release of CIA boss John Brennan's emails |work=[[BBC News]] |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-34597060 |access-date=21 October 2015}}</ref>

=== 2016 ===
{{Main|Hillary Clinton email controversy|2016 Democratic National Committee email leak|Podesta emails}}
During the 2016 [[United States Democratic Party|US Democratic Party]] presidential primaries, WikiLeaks hosted [[Hillary Clinton email controversy|emails]] sent or received by presidential candidate [[Hillary Clinton]] from her personal mail server while she was [[Hillary Clinton's tenure as Secretary of State|Secretary of State]]. The emails had been released by the [[United States Department of State|US State Department]] under a [[Freedom of information in the United States|Freedom of information]] request in February 2016.<ref name=Independent4Jul2016>{{cite news|last1= Carissimo| first1=Justin| title=WikiLeaks publishes more than 1,000 Hillary Clinton war emails|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-elections/wikileaks-publishes-more-than-1000-hillary-clinton-war-emails-a7120011.html|access-date=5 July 2016|work=[[The Independent]] | location= UK |date=4 July 2016}}</ref> WikiLeaks also created a search engine to allow the public to search through Clinton's emails.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/wikileaks-publishes-searchable-archive-of-clinton-emails |title=WikiLeaks publishes searchable archive of Clinton emails |newspaper=[[Washington Examiner]] |access-date=9 May 2016 }}</ref> In July 2016, just prior to the publication of the UK government's [[Iraq Inquiry]] report, WikiLeaks published a selection of the emails referencing the [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Devaney |first1=Tim |title=Wikileaks publishes Clinton war emails |url=http://thehill.com/policy/national-security/286444-wikileaks-publishes-clinton-war-emails|access-date=5 July 2016 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=4 July 2016}}</ref>

On 19 July 2016, in response to the [[2016–present purges in Turkey|Turkish government's purges]] that followed the coup attempt,<ref name="ThReut_WikiLeaks">{{cite news |first1=Can |last1=Sezer |first2=David |last2=Dolan |first3=Raissa |last3=Kasolowsky |title=Turkey blocks access to WikiLeaks after ruling party email dump |date=20 July 2016 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security-wikileaks-idUSKCN1000H1 |access-date=21 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160721002817/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security-wikileaks-idUSKCN1000H1 |archive-date=21 July 2016 |url-status=live|newspaper=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> WikiLeaks released 294,548 emails from Turkey's ruling [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development party]] (AKP).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/wikileaks-turkey-erdogan-emails-government-coup-a7145891.html |title=Here's what's in the Wikileaks emails that Erdogan tried to ban |last=Yeung |first=Peter |date=20 July 2016 |website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=25 July 2016}}</ref> According to WikiLeaks, the material, which it said was the first batch from the "AKP Emails", was obtained a week before the [[2016 Turkish coup d'état attempt|attempted coup in the country]] and "is not connected, in any way, to the elements behind the attempted coup, or to a rival political party or state".<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Dumps 'Erdogan Emails' After Turkey's Failed Coup |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/07/wikileaks-dumps-erdogan-emails-turkeys-failed-coup/ |access-date=20 March 2024 |magazine=Wired |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/akp-emails/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722220438/https://wikileaks.org/akp-emails/| archive-date=22 July 2016| url-status=live |title=WikiLeaks – Search the AKP email database |publisher=wikileaks.org|access-date=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bora |first=Birce |title=WikiLeaks releases thousands of 'Erdogan emails' |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/7/19/turkey-wikileaks-releases-thousands-of-akp-emails |access-date=20 March 2024 |publisher=Al Jazeera English |language=en}}</ref> After WikiLeaks announced that it would release the emails, the organisation was for over 24 hours under a "sustained attack".<ref>{{Cite web|last=Musil|first=Steven|title=WikiLeaks under 'sustained attack' after announcing release of Turkey docs|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/wikileaks-under-sustained-attack-after-announcing-release-of-turkey-docs/|access-date=13 May 2021|website=CNET|language=en}}</ref> Following the leak, the Turkish government ordered the site to be blocked nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/20/turkey-blocks-access-to-wikileaks-after-erdogan-party-emails-go-online |title=Turkey blocks access to WikiLeaks after Erdoğan party emails go online |last=Shaheen |first=Kareem |date=20 July 2016 |website=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/wikileaks-emails-release-government-turkey-erdogan-block-a7145671.html |title=Turkey blocks access to WikiLeaks after release of 300,000 secret government emails |date=20 July 2016 |website=[[The Independent]]|access-date=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2016/07/20/world/europe/ap-eu-turkey-wikileaks.html |title=Access to Wikileaks Blocked in Turkey as It Releases Emails |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=20 July 2016 |work=[[The New York Times]]|issn=0362-4331|access-date=25 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security-wikileaks-idUSKCN1000H1 |title=Turkey blocks access to WikiLeaks after ruling party email dump |date=20 July 2016 |work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=25 July 2016}}</ref>

On 22 July 2016, WikiLeaks released approximately 20,000 emails and 8,000 files sent from or received by [[Democratic National Committee]] (DNC) personnel. Some of the emails contained personal information of donors, including home addresses and [[Social Security number]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last=McCarthy |first=Kieran |title=WikiLeaks fights The Man by, er, publishing ordinary people's personal information |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/07/22/wikileaks_keep_fighting_the_man_by_er_publishing_the_personal_details_of_ordinary_citizens/ |work=The Register|access-date=22 July 2016 |date=22 July 2016}}</ref> Other emails appeared to criticise [[Bernie Sanders]] or showed favouritism towards Clinton during the primaries.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Theodore|last1=Schleifer|first2=Eugene|last2=Scott|title=DNC treatment of Sanders at issue in emails leaked to Wikileaks |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/07/22/politics/dnc-wikileaks-emails/|access-date=24 July 2016 |publisher=[[CNN]]|date=24 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Peters |first1=Maquita |title=Leaked Democratic Party Emails Show Members Tried To Undercut Sanders |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2016/07/23/487179496/leaked-democratic-party-emails-show-members-tried-to-undercut-sanders|access-date=24 July 2016 |date=23 July 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, [[Debbie Wasserman Schultz]] resigned as chairwoman of the DNC because the emails released by WikiLeaks showed that the DNC was "effectively an arm of Mrs. Clinton's campaign" and had conspired to sabotage Sanders's campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |last2=Rappeport |first2=Alan |title=Debbie Wasserman Schultz to Resign D.N.C. Post |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/25/us/politics/debbie-wasserman-schultz-dnc-wikileaks-emails.html |access-date=19 April 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=24 July 2016}}</ref>

On 7 October 2016, WikiLeaks started releasing series of emails and documents sent from or received by Hillary Clinton campaign manager, [[John Podesta]], including Hillary Clinton's paid speeches to banks, including [[Goldman Sachs]]. The BBC reported that the release "is unlikely to allay fears among liberal Democrats that she is too cosy with Wall Street".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thehill.com/policy/national-security/300548-wikileaks-pumps-out-clinton-emails |title=WikiLeaks pumps out Clinton emails |last1=Bo Williams |first1=Katie |date=12 October 2016 |last2=Hattem |first2=Julian |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/wikileaks-podesta-email-release-reveals-massive-clinton-hits-file-on-sanders |title=Wikileaks' Podesta Email Release Reveals Massive Clinton 'Hits' File on Sanders |last=Derespina |first=Cody |date=10 October 2016 |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-37680411 |title=WikiLeaks: Julian Assange's Internet access 'cut' |date=18 October 2016|access-date=25 October 2016 |publisher=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> The DNC and Podesta files allegedly came from Russian state-sponsored hackers, which WikiLeaks denied. According to a spokesman for the Clinton campaign, "By dribbling these out every day WikiLeaks is proving they are nothing but a propaganda arm of the Kremlin with a political agenda doing [[Vladimir Putin]]'s dirty work to help elect Donald Trump."<ref name="Politico 80 pages">{{cite web |last=Cheney |first=Kyle |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2016/10/hillary-clinton-wall-street-speeches-podesta-emails-229689 |title=Hacked 80-page roundup of paid speeches shows Clinton 'praising Wall Street' |website=[[Politico]]|date=12 October 2016 |access-date=16 October 2016}}</ref> President Vladimir Putin said that Russia was being falsely accused.<ref name="Healy">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/13/us/politics/wikileaks-hillary-clinton-emails.html |title=Donald Trump Finds Improbable Ally in WikiLeaks |last1=Healy |first1=Patrick |date=12 October 2016 |last2=David E. |first2=Sanger |work=[[The New York Times]] |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Haberman |first3=Maggie|access-date=19 October 2016}}</ref><ref name="foxnews.com">{{Cite news |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/cia-reportedly-preparing-major-cyber-assault-against-russia-in-wake-of-hack-attacks/ |title=Cia Reportedly Preparing Major Cyber Assault Against Russia in Wake of Hack Attacks |date=15 October 2016 |publisher=[[Fox News Channel]]|access-date=19 October 2016}}</ref>

On 25 November 2016, WikiLeaks released emails and internal documents that provided details on the US military operations in [[Yemen]] from 2009 to March 2015.<ref name="yemenconflict">{{cite news |last=Mujezinovic |first=Damir |title=WikiLeaks Drops New Information Relating To Arms Industry Corruption & War in Yemen |url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5092904/wikileaks-arms-industry-corruption-war-yemen/ |work=The Inquisitr |date=28 September 2018}}</ref> In a statement accompanying the "Yemen Files", Assange said about the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen#United States|US involvement in the Yemen war]]: "Although the United States government has provided most of the bombs and is deeply involved in the conduct of the war itself reportage on the war in English is conspicuously rare".<ref name="yemenconflict"/>

In December 2016, WikiLeaks published over 57,000 emails from Erdogan's son-in-law, [[Berat Albayrak]], who was Turkey's Minister of Energy and Natural Resources. The emails show the inner workings of the Turkish government.<ref name="fp071216" /> According to WikiLeaks, the emails had been first released by [[RedHack|Redhack]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – Berat's Box |url=https://wikileaks.org/berats-box/article |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=wikileaks.org}}</ref>

=== 2017 ===

On 16 February 2017, WikiLeaks released a purported report on CIA espionage orders (marked as [[Law Enforcement Sensitive|NOFORN]]) for the [[2012 French presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liberation.fr/planete/2017/02/16/comment-la-cia-a-espionne-la-presidentielle-francaise-de-2012_1548921 |title=Comment la CIA a espionné la présidentielle française de 2012 |language=fr |website=Libération |author=Jean-Marc Manach |date=16 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lemonde.fr/pixels/article/2017/02/16/la-cia-s-est-interessee-de-pres-a-la-campagne-presidentielle-francaise-de-2012_5080891_4408996.html |title=La CIA s'est intéressée de près à la campagne présidentielle française de 2012 |newspaper=Le Monde.fr |date=16 February 2016 |language=fr}}</ref> The order called for details of party funding, internal rivalries and future attitudes toward the United States. The Associated Press noted that "the orders seemed to represent standard intelligence-gathering."<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://apnews.com/8e5094a33ad84837a7faa31c426ca909/WikiLeaks:-CIA-ordered-spying-on-French-2012-election |title=WikiLeaks: CIA ordered spying on French 2012 election |work=[[Associated Press|AP News]]|access-date=17 February 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 7 March 2017, WikiLeaks started publishing content code-named "[[Vault 7]]", describing it as containing CIA internal documentation of their "massive arsenal" of hacking tools including malware, viruses, weaponised "[[Zero-day (computing)|zero day]]" exploits and remote control systems.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/wikileaks-cia-documents-released-cyber-intelligence/ |title=WikiLeaks claims to release thousands of CIA documents |access-date=7 March 2017 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name="bbc-vault7">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-39193008 |title=Wikileaks 'reveals CIA hacking tools' |last=Kelion |first=Leo |publisher=[[BBC News]]|work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 March 2017 }}</ref><ref name="nytimes-vault7">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/07/world/europe/wikileaks-cia-hacking.html |title=WikiLeaks Releases Trove of Alleged C.I.A. Hacking Documents |website=[[The New York Times]]|date=7 March 2017 |last1=Shane |first1=Scott |last2=Rosenberg |first2=Matthew |last3=Lehren |first3=Andrew W. }}</ref> Leaked documents, dated from 2013 to 2016, detail the capabilities of the US [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) to perform electronic surveillance and [[cyber warfare]], such as the ability to compromise [[Car hacking|cars]], [[smart TV]]s,<ref name="nytimes-vault7"/> [[web browser]]s,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/2017/03/cia-can-hack-phone-pc-tv-says-wikileaks/ |title=How the CIA Can Hack Your Phone, PC, and TV (Says WikiLeaks) |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |date=7 March 2017 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/wikileaks-cia-documents-released-cyber-intelligence/ |title=WikiLeaks posts trove of CIA documents detailing mass hacking |date=7 March 2017 |work=[[CBS News]] |language=en}}</ref> and [[operating system]]s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computing.co.uk/ctg/news/3006021/vault-7-wikileaks-reveals-details-of-cias-hacks-of-android-iphone-windows-linux-macos-and-even-samsung-tvs |title=Vault 7: Wikileaks reveals details of CIA's hacks of Android, iPhone Windows, Linux, MacOS, and even Samsung TVs |website=[[Computing (magazine)|Computing]] |date=7 March 2017 |access-date=6 March 2018 |archive-date=12 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412212526/https://www.computing.co.uk/ctg/news/3006021/vault-7-wikileaks-reveals-details-of-cias-hacks-of-android-iphone-windows-linux-macos-and-even-samsung-tvs |url-status=dead }}</ref> In July 2022, [[Joshua Schulte]] was convicted of leaking the files.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Shanahan |first=Ed |date=13 July 2022 |title=Ex-C.I.A. Engineer Convicted in Biggest Theft Ever of Agency Secrets |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/13/nyregion/cia-engineer-joshua-schulte-theft-convicted.html |access-date=14 July 2022 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>

In September 2017, WikiLeaks released "[[List of material published by WikiLeaks#Spy Files Russia|Spy Files Russia]]," revealing "how a [[Saint Petersburg|St. Petersburg]]-based technology company called [[Peter-Service]] helped state entities gather detailed data on [[Mobile phone industry in Russia|Russian cellphone]] users, part of a national system of online surveillance called [[SORM|System for Operative Investigative Activities]]."<ref>{{cite news |last=Taylor |first=Adam |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2017/09/19/wikileaks-releases-files-that-appear-to-offer-details-of-russian-surveillance-system/ |title=WikiLeaks releases files that appear to offer details of Russian surveillance system |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=19 September 2017 |access-date=21 October 2017}}</ref>

=== 2019 ===

In November 2019, WikiLeaks released an email from an unnamed investigator from the [[Organisation for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons]] (OPCW) team investigating the 2018 [[Douma chemical attack|chemical attack in Douma (Syria)]]. The investigator accused the OPCW of covering up discrepancies.<ref name = cbs>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/opcw-chemical-weapons-watchdog-douma-chlorine-gas-wikileaks-russia-syria-claim-bias-today-2019-11-25/ |title=Chemical weapons watchdog OPCW defends Syria report as whistleblower claims bias |date=25 November 2019 |website=[[CBS News]] |access-date=17 April 2022}}</ref> [[Robert Fisk]] said that documents released by WikiLeaks indicated that the OPCW "suppressed or failed to publish, or simply preferred to ignore, the conclusions of up to 20 other members of its staff who became so upset at what they regarded as the misleading conclusions of the final report that they officially sought to have it changed in order to represent the truth".<ref name="independent020120">{{cite news |last1=Fisk |first1=Robert |title=The Syrian conflict is awash with propaganda – chemical warfare bodies should not be caught up in it |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/syria-war-chemical-weapons-watchdog-opcw-assad-damascus-russia-a9262336.html |access-date=3 January 2020 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=2 January 2020}}</ref> The head of OPCW, Fernando Arias, described the leak as containing "subjective views" and stood by the original conclusions.<ref name = cbs/> In April 2018, WikiLeaks had offered a $100,000 reward for confidential information about "the alleged chemical attack in Douma, Syria."<ref>{{cite tweet|number=983443098767364097|user=wikileaks|title=WikiLeaks issues a US$100,000 reward for confidential official information (intercepts, reports) showing to who is responsible for the alleged chemical attack in Douma, Syria. Send information here: https://t.co/cLRcuIiQXz|author=WikiLeaks|author-link=WikiLeaks|date=9 April 2018|access-date=19 March 2022|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220313170202/https://twitter.com/wikileaks/status/983443098767364097|archive-date=13 March 2022|url-status=live}}</ref> In a November 2020 interview with BBC, WikiLeaks' alleged source declined to say if he took money from the organisation.<ref>{{Cite web |title=BBC Radio 4 – Intrigue, Extra Episode: The Canister on the Bed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p08z33bp |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=20 November 2020 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=14 May 2021 |title=Berlin Group 21, 'Ivan's' Emails and Chemical Weapons Conspiracy Theories |url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/2021/05/14/berlin-group-21-ivans-emails-and-chemical-weapons-conspiracy-theories/ |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=bellingcat |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 12 November 2019, WikiLeaks began publishing what it called the [[Fishrot Files]] (''Icelandic: Samherjaskjölin''), a collection of thousands of documents and email communication by employees of one of Iceland's largest fish industry companies, [[Samherji]], that indicated that the company had paid hundreds of millions [[Icelandic króna]] to officials in [[Namibia]] with the objective of acquiring the country's coveted fishing quota.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Helgi |last1=Seljan |first2=Aðalsteinn |last2=Kjartansson |author3=Stefán Aðalsteinn Drengsson |title=What Samherji wanted hidden |url=https://www.ruv.is/kveikur/fishrot/ |access-date=13 November 2019 |work=[[RÚV]] |language=is}}</ref> The files were given to WikiLeaks by [[Jóhannes Stefánsson]].

=== 2021 ===

In 2021, WikiLeaks made a searchable database of 17,000 publicly available documents, which it called ''The Intolerance Network'', from the ultra-conservative Spanish Catholic organisation Hazte Oir and its international arm, [[CitizenGo]]. The documents reveal the internal workings of the organisations, their network of donors and their relationship with the [[Holy See|Vatican]]. The release also includes documents from the secret [[Roman Catholic|Catholic]] organisation [[El Yunque (organization)|El Yunque]]. The editor of WikiLeaks, [[Kristinn Hrafnsson]], said "As ultra right-wing political groups have gained strength in recent years, with increasing attacks on women's and LGBT rights, it is valuable to have access to documents from those who have lobbied for those changes on a global basis".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stefania |first1=Maurizi |title=Exclusive: Wikileaks reveals the internal documents of the ultra-conservative catholic organizations Hazte Oir and CitizenGo |url=https://www.ilfattoquotidiano.it/2021/08/06/exclusive-wikileaks-reveals-the-internal-documents-of-the-ultra-conservative-catholic-organizations-hazte-oir-and-citizengo/6284860/ |access-date=6 August 2021 |work=Il Fatto Quotidiano |date=6 August 2021 |language=it-IT}}</ref> According to WikiLeaks, the documents were first released in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks – The Intolerance Network |url=https://wikileaks.org/intolerancenetwork/press-release |access-date=13 March 2022 |website=wikileaks.org}}</ref><ref name="Gizmodo-2022a">{{Cite web |date=22 November 2022 |title=WikiLeaks' Website Is Falling Apart |url=https://gizmodo.com/wikileaks-julian-assange-1849813101 |access-date=23 November 2022 |website=Gizmodo |language=en}}</ref>

=== Authenticity and completeness ===
{{See also|List of material published by WikiLeaks#Unpublished material}}
According to ''[[The New Yorker]]'', when WikiLeaks posted its first document in December 2006, "[[Julian Assange|Assange]] and the others were uncertain of its authenticity, but they thought that readers, using [[Wikipedia]]-like features of the site, would help analyse it. ... The document's authenticity was never determined, and news about WikiLeaks quickly superseded the leak itself."<ref name="Khatchdourian" /> When someone said they were misidentified in a Julius Baer document as having a secret Swiss bank account Assange and Domscheit-Berg added a caveat to the document saying, "according to three independent sources" the information might be false or misleading. Domscheit-Berg later wrote that they made up the "three independent sources" and that the source had "included some background information he had researched about the bank's clients" that misidentified a Swiss account holder as a German man with a similar name.<ref name=":17">{{Cite magazine |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=WikiLeaks Defector Slams Assange In Tell-All Book |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/02/wikileaks-book/ |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name=":18">{{Cite book |last=Domscheit-Berg |first=Daniel |title=Inside Wikileaks : my time with Julian Assange at the world's most dangerous website |date=2011 |publisher=Crown Publishers |others=Tina Klopp, Jefferson S. Chase |isbn=978-0-307-95191-5 |location=New York |oclc=701412231}}</ref>

In 2008, the WikiLeaks website said "Wikileaks does not pass judgement on the authenticity of documents".<ref name="wikigone" /> Wired reported that in 2009, a "whistleblower" submitted fabricated documents to WikiLeaks. The documents were published and flagged by WikiLeaks as potential fakes.<ref name="WiredUK-1357" />

WikiLeaks stated in 2010 that it has never released a misattributed document and that documents are assessed before release. In response to concerns about the possibility of misleading or fraudulent leaks, WikiLeaks has stated that misleading leaks "are already well-placed in the mainstream media. WikiLeaks is of no additional assistance."<ref>{{cite news |last=Trapido |first=Michael |date=1 December 2010 |title=Wikileaks: Is Julian Assange a hero, villain or simply dangerously naïve? |work=NewsTime |place=Johannesburg |url=http://www.newstime.co.za/WorldNews/Wikileaks_:_Is_Julian_Assange_a_hero_villain_or_simply_dangerously_na%C3%AFve/16065/ |url-status=dead |access-date=18 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813024350/http://www.newstime.co.za/WorldNews/Wikileaks_%3A_Is_Julian_Assange_a_hero_villain_or_simply_dangerously_na%C3%AFve/16065/ |archive-date=13 August 2011}}</ref> The FAQ in 2010 stated that: "The simplest and most effective countermeasure is a worldwide community of informed users and editors who can scrutinise and discuss leaked documents."<ref>{{cite web |title=Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://wikileaks.org/faq-en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070701115958/https://wikileaks.org/faq-en |archive-date=1 July 2007 |access-date=17 June 2010 |publisher=WikiLeaks}}</ref> In 2010, Assange said submitted documents were vetted by five reviewers with expertise in different topics such as language or [[Computer programming|programming]], who also investigated the leaker's identity if known.<ref name="motherjones3">{{cite news |author=Kushner, David |date=6 April 2010 |title=Inside WikiLeaks' Leak Factory |work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |place=San Francisco |url=http://motherjones.com/politics/2010/04/wikileaks-julian-assange-iraq-video?page=3 |url-status=live |access-date=30 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140429130626/http://www.motherjones.com/politics/2010/04/wikileaks-julian-assange-iraq-video?page=3 |archive-date=29 April 2014}}</ref> Assange had the final say in document assessment.<ref name="motherjones3" />

Daniel Domscheit-Berg wrote that before WikiLeaks started working with media partners most verification of submissions was doing Google searches.<ref name=":17" /><ref name=":18" /> According to the [[Columbia Journalism Review]], Assange "outsourced the burden of verification" of the [[United States documents leak of the War in Afghanistan|Afghan War documents leak]], the [[Iraq War documents leak]] and [[United States diplomatic cables leak|Cablegate]] to the New York Times, The Guardian, and Der Spiegel.<ref>{{Cite web |title=How WikiLeaks Outsourced the Burden of Verification |url=https://www.cjr.org/campaign_desk/how_wikileaks_outsourced_the_b.php |access-date=8 October 2023 |website=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Renner |first=Nausicaa |title=The symbiotic relationship between WikiLeaks and the press |url=https://www.cjr.org/tow_center/wikileaks_trump_election_julian_assange.php |access-date=8 October 2023 |website=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref> [[Yulia Latynina]] alleged in ''[[The Moscow Times]]'' that WikiLeaks associate [[Israel Shamir]] concocted a [[United States diplomatic cables leak|leaked diplomatic cable]] for publication in the pro-Putin ''Russian Reporter'' in December 2010.<ref name="NYM20111214" /><ref name=":36" /><ref name="moscowtimes_shamir_freelance" /> Shamir has denied this accusation.<ref name="moscowtimes_shamir_freelance" />

In 2012, WikiLeaks released a statement about the [[Syria Files]] saying that:<blockquote>In such a large collection of information, it is not possible to verify every single email at once; however, WikiLeaks and its co-publishers have done so for all initial stories to be published. We are statistically confident that the vast majority of the data are what they purport to be.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Announces Massive Release With The 'Syria Files': 2.4 Million Emails From Syrian Officials And Companies |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2012/07/05/wikileaks-announces-its-largest-release-yet-in-the-syria-files-2-4-million-emails-from-syrian-officials-and-companies/ |access-date=2023-09-09 |website=Forbes |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Abad-Santos |first=Alexander |date=2012-07-05 |title=WikiLeaks Might Not Even Know What's In 2.4 Million Syrian E-mails |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/07/wikileaks-might-not-even-know-whats-their-24-million-syrian-e-mails/326282/ |access-date=2023-09-09 |website=The Atlantic |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Somaiya |first=Ravi |date=2012-07-05 |title=WikiLeaks Releasing Trove of Syria Documents |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/06/world/middleeast/wikileaks-releasing-trove-of-syria-documents.html |access-date=2023-09-09 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref></blockquote>Columnist Eric Zorn wrote in 2016 "So far, it's possible, even likely, that every stolen email WikiLeaks has posted has been authentic," but cautioned against assuming that future releases would be equally authentic.<ref name="Zorn">{{cite web |last=Zorn |first=Eric |date=13 October 2016 |title=The inherent peril in trusting whatever WikiLeaks dumps on us |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/opinion/zorn/ct-wikileaks-potential-hoax-zorn-perspec-1014-jm-20161013-column.html |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Writer [[Glenn Greenwald]] wrote in 2016 that WikiLeaks had a "perfect, long-standing record of only publishing authentic documents."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Greenwald |first1=Glenn |author-link=Glenn Greenwald |title=In the Democratic Echo Chamber, Inconvenient Truths Are Recast as Putin Plots |work=The Intercept |url=https://theintercept.com/2016/10/11/in-the-democratic-echo-chamber-inconvenient-truths-are-recast-as-putin-plots/}}</ref> Cybersecurity experts have said that it would be easy for a person to fabricate an email or alter it, as by changing headers and metadata.<ref name="Zorn" /> Some released emails contain [[DKIM]] headers. This allows them to be verified as genuine to some degree of certainty.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 October 2016 |title=Tech blogger finds proof DNC chief's emails weren't 'doctored' despite claims |publisher=[[Fox News]] |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/tech-blogger-finds-proof-dnc-chiefs-emails-werent-doctored-despite-claims |access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=The current source is insufficiently reliable ([[WP:FOXNEWSPOLITICS]]).|date=October 2023}}

In July 2016, the [[Aspen Institute]]'s Homeland Security Group, a bipartisan counterterrorism organisation, warned that hackers who stole authentic data might "salt the files they release with plausible forgeries."<ref name="Zorn" /> According to Douglas Perry, Russian intelligence agencies have frequently used [[disinformation]] tactics. He wrote in 2016 that "carefully faked emails might be included in the WikiLeaks dumps. After all, the best way to make false information believable is to mix it in with true information."<ref>Douglas Perry, {{cite web |last=Perry |first=Douglas |date=18 October 2016 |title=How Russian disinformation could be driving the Hillary Clinton WikiLeaks email scandal |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/today/index.ssf/2016/10/how_a_russian_disinformation_c.html |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=The Oregonian}}</ref>

In September 2016, [[The Daily Dot]] reported that WikiLeaks' [[Syria Files]] excluded "records of a €2 billion transaction between the [[Syria]]n regime and a government-owned Russian bank," citing court documents.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cameron |first=Dell |date=9 September 2016 |title=WikiLeaks release excludes evidence of €2 billion transfer from Syria to Russia |url=https://www.dailydot.com/debug/wikileaks-syria-files-syria-russia-bank-2-billion/ |access-date=7 December 2022 |website=[[The Daily Dot]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

== Reception ==
{{Main|Reception of WikiLeaks}}

=== Awards and support ===
The media and civil society organisations have commended Wikileaks for exposing state and corporate secrets, increasing transparency, assisting [[freedom of the press]], and enhancing democratic discourse while challenging powerful institutions.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kampfner, John |date=29 November 2010 |title=Wikileaks shows up our media for their docility at the feet of authority |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/john-kampfner-wikileaks-shows-up-our-media-for-their-docility-at-the-feet-of-authority-2146211.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120629145243/http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/john-kampfner-wikileaks-shows-up-our-media-for-their-docility-at-the-feet-of-authority-2146211.html |archive-date=29 June 2012 |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[The Independent]] |place=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Shafer |first=Jack |date=30 November 2010 |title=Why I Love WikiLeaks |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2276312/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113032713/http://www.slate.com/id/2276312 |archive-date=13 January 2011 |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |date=30 November 2010 |title=WikiLeaks reveals more than just government secrets |url=http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2010/11/30/wikileaks/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113112018/http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2010/11/30/wikileaks/index.html |archive-date=13 January 2011 |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gilmore |first=Dan |date=6 December 2010 |title=Defend WikiLeaks or lose free speech |url=http://www.salon.com/technology/dan_gillmor/2010/12/06/war_on_speech |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101093621/http://www.salon.com/technology/dan_gillmor/2010/12/06/war_on_speech |archive-date=1 January 2011 |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=27 December 2010 |title=First, They Came for WikiLeaks. Then ... |url=http://www.thenation.com/article/157017/first-they-came-wikileaks-then |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627055730/http://www.thenation.com/article/157017/first-they-came-wikileaks-then |archive-date=27 June 2011 |access-date=19 May 2011 |work=[[The Nation]] |place=New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Ruane, Medb |date=11 December 2010 |title=Where's the democracy in hunting Wikileaks off the Net? |url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/medb-ruane/medb-ruane-wheres-the-democracy-in-hunting-wikileaks-off-the-net-2456960.html |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=Irish Independent |place=Dublin}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Nayar, Pramod K. |date=25 December 2010 |title=WikiLeaks, the New Information Cultures and Digital Parrhesia |url=http://www.epw.in/commentary/wikileaks-new-information-cultures-and-digital-parrhesia.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512103617/http://www.epw.in/commentary/wikileaks-new-information-cultures-and-digital-parrhesia.html |archive-date=12 May 2013 |access-date=8 January 2011 |work=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |place=Mumbai}}</ref>

WikiLeaks won ''[[The Economist]]''{{'}}s New Media Award in 2008 at the Index on Censorship Awards<ref>{{cite web |title=Winners of Index on Censorship Freedom of Expression Awards Announced |url=http://www.indexoncensorship.org/2008/04/winners-of-index-on-censorship-freedom-of-expression-award-announced/ |publisher=Index on Censorship |access-date=15 December 2010 |date=22 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120723022557/http://www.indexoncensorship.org/2008/04/winners-of-index-on-censorship-freedom-of-expression-award-announced/ |archive-date=23 July 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Amnesty International]]'s UK Media Award in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Cry of Blood. Report on Extra-Judicial Killings and Disappearances |url=http://www.ediec.org/library/item/id/402/ |publisher=Kenya National Commission on Human Rights|access-date=15 December 2010 |year=2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209122323/http://www.ediec.org/library/item/id/402/ |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=usurped}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Amnesty announces Media Awards 2009 winners |url=http://amnesty.org.uk/news_details.asp?NewsID=18227 |publisher=Amnesty International UK |access-date=15 December 2010 |date=2 June 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022182928/http://amnesty.org.uk/news_details.asp?NewsID=18227 |archive-date=22 October 2013 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Julian Assange received the 2010 [[Sam Adams Award]] for Integrity in Intelligence for releasing secret U.S. military reports on the Iraq and Afghan wars<ref>{{cite web |last=Sam Adams Associates for Integrity in Intelligence |title=WikiLeaks and Assange Honored |url=http://www.consortiumnews.com/2010/102410a.html |publisher=Consortium News |access-date=22 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402104914/http://www.consortiumnews.com/2010/102410a.html |archive-date=2 April 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref> and was named the Readers' Choice for [[Time Person of the Year|''TIME's Person of the Year'']] in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Friedman |first=Megan |title=Julian Assange: Readers' Choice for TIME's Person of the Year 2010 |url=https://newsfeed.time.com/2010/12/13/julian-assange-readers-choice-for-times-person-of-the-year-2010/ |access-date=15 December 2010 |magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |place=New York |date=13 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027124723/http://newsfeed.time.com/2010/12/13/julian-assange-readers-choice-for-times-person-of-the-year-2010/ |archive-date=27 October 2013 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2010, the UN [[High Commissioner for Human Rights]] expressed concern over what they referred to as a cyber war against WikiLeaks,<ref>{{cite press release |title=UN human rights chief voices concern at reported 'cyber war' against WikiLeaks |date=9 December 2010 |publisher=United Nations |url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=37009&Cr=leaked&Cr1 |access-date=28 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420125618/http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=37009&Cr=leaked&Cr1 |archive-date=20 April 2014}}</ref> and in a joint statement with the [[Organization of American States]] the UN [[United Nations Special Rapporteur|Special Rapporteur]] called on states and others to keep international legal principles in mind.<ref>{{cite web |date=August 2009 |title=Joint Statement on WikiLeaks |url=http://www.cidh.oas.org/relatoria/showarticle.asp?artID=829&lID=1 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227073006/http://www.cidh.oas.org/relatoria/showarticle.asp?artID=829&lID=1 |archive-date=27 December 2010 |access-date=28 December 2010 |publisher=[[Organization of American States]]}}</ref> In 2010, a UK [[Information Commissioner's Office|Information Commissioner]] said that "WikiLeaks is part of the phenomenon of the online, empowered citizen",<ref>{{cite news |author=Curtis, Polly |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/dec/30/wikileaks-freedom-information-ministers-government |title=Ministers must 'wise up not clam up' after WikiLeaks disclosures |work=[[The Guardian]] |place=London |date=30 December 2010 |access-date=1 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110327023338/http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2010/dec/30/wikileaks-freedom-information-ministers-government |archive-date=27 March 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> and an [[Internet petition]] in support of WikiLeaks attracted more than six hundred thousand signatures.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/technology-news/media-says-governments-reaction-to-wikileaks-troubling-20101214-18vrb.html |title=Media says government's reaction to WikiLeaks 'troubling' |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |access-date=28 December 2010 |date=14 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209151331/http://www.smh.com.au/technology/technology-news/media-says-governments-reaction-to-wikileaks-troubling-20101214-18vrb.html |archive-date=9 February 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref>

On 16 April 2019, [[Mairead Maguire]] accepted the 2019 [[European United Left–Nordic Green Left|GUE/NGL]] Award for Journalists, Whistleblowers & Defenders of the Right to Information on Julian Assange's behalf.<ref>{{cite news|first=Alan|last=Jones|work=Canberra Times|title=Julian Assange wins EU journalism award|date=17 April 2019|access-date=20 April 2019|url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/story/6065261/julian-assange-wins-eu-journalism-award/}}</ref>

==== Improving government and corporate transparency ====
During the early years of WikiLeaks, members of the media and academia commended it for exposing state and corporate secrets, increasing transparency, assisting [[freedom of the press]], and enhancing democratic discourse while challenging powerful institutions.<ref>{{cite news |author=Kampfner, John |title=Wikileaks shows up our media for their docility at the feet of authority |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/john-kampfner-wikileaks-shows-up-our-media-for-their-docility-at-the-feet-of-authority-2146211.html |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=29 November 2010 |place=London |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120629145243/http://www.independent.co.uk/opinion/commentators/john-kampfner-wikileaks-shows-up-our-media-for-their-docility-at-the-feet-of-authority-2146211.html |archive-date=29 June 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Shafer |first=Jack |title=Why I Love WikiLeaks |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2276312/ |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |date=30 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113032713/http://www.slate.com/id/2276312 |archive-date=13 January 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |title=WikiLeaks reveals more than just government secrets |url=http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2010/11/30/wikileaks/index.html |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=30 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110113112018/http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/2010/11/30/wikileaks/index.html |archive-date=13 January 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gilmore |first=Dan |title=Defend WikiLeaks or lose free speech |url=http://www.salon.com/technology/dan_gillmor/2010/12/06/war_on_speech |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=6 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110101093621/http://www.salon.com/technology/dan_gillmor/2010/12/06/war_on_speech |archive-date=1 January 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=First, They Came for WikiLeaks. Then ... |url=http://www.thenation.com/article/157017/first-they-came-wikileaks-then |access-date=19 May 2011 |work=[[The Nation]] |place=New York |date=27 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110627055730/http://www.thenation.com/article/157017/first-they-came-wikileaks-then |archive-date=27 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Where's the democracy in hunting Wikileaks off the Net? |url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/medb-ruane/medb-ruane-wheres-the-democracy-in-hunting-wikileaks-off-the-net-2456960.html |access-date=19 December 2010 |work=Irish Independent |place=Dublin |date=11 December 2010 |author=Ruane, Medb}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.epw.in/commentary/wikileaks-new-information-cultures-and-digital-parrhesia.html |title=WikiLeaks, the New Information Cultures and Digital Parrhesia |work=[[Economic and Political Weekly]] |author=Nayar, Pramod K. |place=Mumbai |date=25 December 2010 |access-date=8 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130512103617/http://www.epw.in/commentary/wikileaks-new-information-cultures-and-digital-parrhesia.html |archive-date=12 May 2013}}</ref>

In 2010, the UN [[High Commissioner for Human Rights]] expressed concern over what they referred to as a cyber war against WikiLeaks,<ref>{{cite press release |title=UN human rights chief voices concern at reported 'cyber war' against WikiLeaks |date=9 December 2010 |publisher=United Nations |url=https://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=37009&Cr=leaked&Cr1|access-date=28 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420125618/http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID=37009&Cr=leaked&Cr1 |archive-date=20 April 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and in a joint statement with the [[Organization of American States]] the UN [[United Nations Special Rapporteur|Special Rapporteur]] called on states and others to keep international legal principles in mind.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cidh.oas.org/relatoria/showarticle.asp?artID=829&lID=1 |title=Joint Statement on WikiLeaks |publisher=[[Organization of American States]] |access-date=28 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101227073006/http://www.cidh.oas.org/relatoria/showarticle.asp?artID=829&lID=1 |archive-date=27 December 2010 |url-status=dead |date=August 2009 }}</ref>

=== Criticism ===
{{See also|Reception of WikiLeaks#Criticism of Wikileaks}}
Since 2011,<ref>{{Cite web |date=13 February 2011 |title=The Guardian's David Leigh Talks About Julian Assange and Wikileaks |url=https://techcrunch.com/2011/02/12/the-guardians-david-leigh-talks-about-julian-assange-and-wikileaks/ |website=[[TechCrunch]]}}</ref> WikiLeaks has faced [[Reception of WikiLeaks#Allegations of association with Russian government|allegations of association with the Russian government]] which peaked during the 2016 U.S. presidential election. WikiLeaks said it had no connection with Russia.<ref name="ufge">{{cite web |last1=Sciutto |first1=Jim |last2=Gaouette |first2=Nicole |last3=Browne |first3=Ryan |date=14 October 2016 |title=US finds growing evidence Russia feeding emails to WikiLeaks |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/10/13/politics/russia-us-election/ |access-date=17 April 2022 |website=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Several associates of WikiLeaks including Julian Assange,<ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks founder charged with conspiring with Anonymous and LulzSec hackers |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/wikileaks-founder-charged-with-conspiring-with-anonymous-and-lulzsec-hackers/ |access-date=9 September 2023 |website=ZDNET |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Leigh |first=David |title=Wikileaks : inside Julian Assange's war on secrecy |date=2011 |publisher=Public Affairs |others=Luke Harding, Edward Pilkington, Robert Booth, Charles Arthur |isbn=978-1-61039-062-0 |location=New York |oclc=708581074}}</ref><ref name=":16">{{Cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Andrew |date=6 March 2014 |title=Ghosting |language=en |volume=36 |work=London Review of Books |issue=5 |url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/the-paper/v36/n05/andrew-o-hagan/ghosting |access-date=2 May 2023 |issn=0260-9592}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=21 December 2017 |title=Margaret Atwood and Andrew O'Hagan on Trump, the Internet, and Our Dark Future |url=https://lithub.com/margaret-atwood-and-andrew-ohagan-on-trump-the-internet-and-our-dark-future/ |access-date=1 November 2023 |website=Literary Hub |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Smári McCarthy]],<ref name=":7">{{Cite magazine |last=Zetter |first=Kim |title=WikiLeaks Volunteer Hacked a Reporter, Assange Autobiography Reveals |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/09/unauthorized-assange-memoir/ |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028 |access-date=26 March 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Assange |first=Julian |title=Julian Assange : the unauthorised autobiography |date=2011 |publisher=Canongate |isbn=978-0-85786-384-3 |location=Edinburgh |oclc=755073172}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Brooke |first=Heather |title=The revolution will be digitised : dispatches from the information war |date=2011 |publisher=William Heinemann |isbn=978-0-434-02090-4 |location=London |oclc=751665465}}</ref> and [[Sigurdur Thordarson]] have faced [[Reception of WikiLeaks#Allegations of hacking|allegations related to hacking]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Olson |first=Parmy |title=We are anonymous: inside the hacker world of LulzSec, Anonymous, and the Global Cyber Insurgency |date=2012 |publisher=Little, Brown |isbn=978-0-316-21354-7 |location=New York |author-link=Parmy Olson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Anderson |first=Nate |date=30 May 2012 |title=New book: WikiLeaks wanted LulzSec's help to hack Iceland |url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2012/05/new-book-wikileaks-wanted-lulzsecs-help-to-hack-iceland/ |access-date=9 September 2023 |website=Ars Technica |language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=30 May 2012 |title=Link Between WikiLeaks And Hacker Group Revealed |language=en |work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |url=https://www.rferl.org/a/as-assange-awaits-uk-verdict-link-between-wikileaks-hacker-group-lulzsec-revealed/24596950.html |access-date=9 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Hicks |first=Jesse |date=7 June 2012 |title=Inside Anonymous: an interview with Parmy Olson |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/6/7/3070945/parmy-olson-inside-anonymous-five-minutes-on-the-verge |access-date=9 September 2023 |website=The Verge |language=en-US}}</ref> WikiLeaks has been criticised for making [[Reception of WikiLeaks#Exaggerated and misleading descriptions of the contents of leaks|misleading claims about the contents of its leaks]],<ref name="Tufekci-2017">{{Cite news |last=Tufekci |first=Zeynep |date=9 March 2017 |title=The Truth About the WikiLeaks C.I.A. Cache |work=[[The New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/opinion/the-truth-about-the-wikileaks-cia-cache.html |access-date=10 March 2017 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="Singal-2023">{{Cite web |last=Singal |first=Jesse |date=27 July 2016 |title=Why Did WikiLeaks Help Dox Most of Turkey's Adult Female Population? |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2016/07/why-did-wikileaks-help-dox-most-of-turkeys-adult-female-population.html |access-date=5 January 2023 |website=[[New York (magazine)|New York Intelligencer]] |language=en-us}}</ref> including the [[Stratfor email leak]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Fisher |first=Max |date=27 February 2012 |title=Stratfor Is a Joke and So Is Wikileaks for Taking It Seriously |newspaper=The Atlantic |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2012/02/stratfor-is-a-joke-and-so-is-wikileaks-for-taking-them-seriously/253681/ |access-date=5 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Drezner |first=Daniel W. |date=27 February 2012 |title=Wake me when WikiLeaks publishes the Illuminati e-mails |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2012/02/27/wake-me-when-wikileaks-publishes-the-illuminati-e-mails/ |access-date=10 September 2023 |website=Foreign Policy |language=en-US}}</ref> the AKP emails<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Dumps 'Erdogan Emails' After Turkey's Failed Coup |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2016/07/wikileaks-dumps-erdogan-emails-turkeys-failed-coup/ |access-date=6 January 2023 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=1 May 2021 |title=Private lives are exposed as WikiLeaks spills its secrets |url=https://apnews.com/article/ap-top-news-international-news-technology-wikileaks-africa-b70da83fd111496dbdf015acbb7987fb |access-date=5 January 2023 |website=[[Associated Press|AP News]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Turkey Blocks WikiLeaks After Dump of Government Emails |url=https://www.vice.com/en/article/turkey-erdogan-blocks-wikileaks-after-dump-of-government-akp-emails/ |access-date=5 January 2023 |website=Vice.com |date=20 July 2016 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Vault 7]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Biddle |first=Sam |author-link=Sam Biddle |date=24 March 2017 |title=Apple Says It Fixed CIA Vulnerabilities Years Ago |url=https://theintercept.com/2017/03/24/apple-says-it-fixed-cia-vulnerabilities-years-ago/ |access-date=2 January 2023 |website=The Intercept |language=en}}</ref> The group was criticised for attempting to auction information<ref name="Singel-1059">{{Cite magazine |last=Singel |first=Ryan |title=Latest Wikileaks Prize for Sale to the Highest Bidder – Update |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/08/wikileaks-aucti/ |access-date=13 March 2022 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref><ref name="WiredUK-1357" /> and drew intense criticism from supporters including [[Anonymous (hacker group)|Anonymous]] for putting the [[2012–13 Stratfor email leak|Global Intelligence files]] behind a paywall.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |title=WikiLeaks Angers Supporters With Donation 'Paywall' For Leaked Material |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andygreenberg/2012/10/10/wikileaks-angers-supporters-with-donation-paywall-for-leaked-material/ |access-date=2 May 2022 |website=[[Forbes]]|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks loses Anonymous allies over paywall dispute |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/wikileaks-loses-anonymous-allies-over-paywall-dispute-flna1C6443490 |access-date=2 May 2022 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=13 October 2012 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Osborne |first=Charlie |title=Anonymous declares war on Wikileaks |url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/anonymous-declares-war-on-wikileaks/ |access-date=2 May 2022 |website=ZDNet |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Kravets |first=David |title=WikiLeaks Goes Behind Paywall, Anonymous Cries Foul |language=en-US |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/2012/10/wikileaks-paywall-anonymous/ |access-date=2 May 2022 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref> WikiLeaks has drawn criticism for [[Reception of WikiLeaks#Inadequate curation and violations of personal privacy|inadequate curation and violations of personal privacy]]<ref name="Satter-2016" /> from [[Transparency (behavior)|transparency]] advocates such as [[Edward Snowden]],<ref name="Peterson-2016" /> [[Glenn Greenwald]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Chotiner |first=Isaac |date=28 July 2016 |title=Is the Attempt to Link Trump and Putin a New McCarthyism? |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2016/07/glenn-greenwald-on-donald-trump-the-dnc-hack-and-a-new-mccarthyism.html |access-date=15 September 2022 |website=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |language=en}}</ref> [[Amnesty International]],<ref>{{Cite news |last=Whalen |first=Jeanne |date=9 August 2010 |title=Human Rights Groups Press WikiLeaks Over Data - WSJ.com |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703428604575419580947722558 |access-date=1 December 2010}}</ref> [[Reporters Without Borders]],<ref name="RSF-Julliard-2010b" /><ref name="BBCNews-20112" /><ref name=":31" /> the [[Sunlight Foundation]]<ref name="Howard-2016">{{cite web |last1=Howard |first1=Alex |last2=Wonderlich |first2=John |date=28 July 2016 |title=On weaponized transparency |url=https://sunlightfoundation.com/2016/07/28/on-weaponized-transparency/ |publisher=Sunlight Foundation}}</ref> and the [[Federation of American Scientists]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Aftergood |first=Steven |author-link=Steven Aftergood |date=28 June 2010 |title=Wikileaks Fails "Due Diligence" Review |url=https://fas.org/blog/secrecy/2010/06/wikileaks_review.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217213849/http://www.fas.org/blog/secrecy/2010/06/wikileaks_review.html |archive-date=17 December 2010 |access-date=18 December 2010 |work=Secrecy News |publisher=[[Federation of American Scientists]]}}</ref><ref name="Brustein-2016" />

==== Internal conflicts and lack of transparency ====
{{See also|WikiLeaks#2010 internal dissent}}
WikiLeaks has often been criticised for demanding absolute secrecy about its activities, but openness in others.<ref name="Fow20Traf" />

In 2010, former advisory board member [[Cryptome|John Young]] accused the organisation of a lack of transparency regarding its fundraising and financial management. He stated his belief that WikiLeaks could not guarantee whistleblowers the anonymity or confidentiality it said it did and that he "would not trust them with information if it had any value, or if it put me at risk or anyone that I cared about at risk."<ref>{{Cite web |last=McCullagh |first=Declan |date=20 July 2010 |title=Wikileaks' estranged co-founder becomes a critic (Q&A) &#124; Privacy Inc. – CNET News |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-31921_3-20011106-281.html |access-date=1 December 2010 |publisher=News.cnet.com |archive-date=30 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130065550/http://news.cnet.com/8301-31921_3-20011106-281.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> He later became supportive of the organisation again.<ref name="WiredUK-1357" />

[[File:Assange Domscheit-Berg.jpg|thumb|Julian Assange (left) with Daniel Domscheit-Berg who was ejected from WikiLeaks and started a rival "[[whistleblower]]" organisation named OpenLeaks]]Those working for WikiLeaks are reportedly required to sign sweeping [[non-disclosure agreement]]s covering all conversations, conduct, and material, with Assange having sole power over disclosure.<ref name="BuzzFeed-2016">{{Cite news |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/jamesball/heres-what-i-learned-about-julian-assange |title=Here's What I Learned About Julian Assange While Working Alongside Him |work=[[BuzzFeed News]]|access-date=23 October 2016}}</ref> The penalty for non-compliance in one such agreement was reportedly £12 million.<ref name="BuzzFeed-2016" /> WikiLeaks has been challenged for this practice, as it is seen to be hypocritical for an organisation dedicated to transparency to limit the transparency of its inner workings and limit the [[accountability]] of powerful individuals in the organisation.<ref name="BuzzFeed-2016" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/05/nda-wikileaks/ |title=WikiLeaks Threatens Its Own Leakers With $20 Million Penalty |last=Poulsen |first=Kevin |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|access-date=23 October 2016 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/may/12/wikileaks-confidentiality-agreement-julian-assange |title=WikiLeaks, get out of the gagging game |date=12 May 2011 |work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=23 October 2016 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

[[File:Bilbao - Ribera de Deusto 04.JPG|thumb|upright=.75|[[Graffiti]] in [[Bilbao]] "We want to know."]]

=== Public positions taken by United States politicians concerning WikiLeaks ===

In 2010, after WikiLeaks' release of classified U.S. government documents leaked by [[Chelsea Manning]], then [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice-president]] [[Joe Biden]] said that he "would argue it is closer to being a high-tech terrorist than the [[Pentagon Papers]]". Biden said Assange "has done things that have damaged and put in jeopardy the lives and occupations of people in other parts of the world."<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/dec/19/assange-high-tech-terrorist-biden | title=Julian Assange like a hi-tech terrorist, says Joe Biden | first=Ewen | last=MacAskill | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=19 December 2010 | access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/assange-is-a-hi-tech-terrorist-says-biden-2164988.html | work=[[The Independent]] | title=Assange is a 'hi-tech terrorist', says Biden | first=David | last=Usborne | date=20 December 2010 | access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/503474636dab425d80eab46f7bc655fa | title=Analysis: WikiLeaks founder unlikely to be extradited soon | first=Raphael | last=Satter | date=11 April 2019 | access-date=23 April 2019}}</ref> Representative [[Pete Hoekstra]] called for decisive action against WikiLeaks.<ref name="Weigel-2017">{{Cite news |last1=Weigel |first1=David |last2=Warrick |first2=Joby |date=4 January 2017 |title=How Julian Assange evolved from pariah to paragon |language=en-US |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-julian-assange-evolved-from-pariah-to-paragon/2017/01/04/2a3ea6e6-d2b8-11e6-9cb0-54ab630851e8_story.html |access-date=30 January 2023 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Senators [[Joseph Lieberman]] and [[John McCain]] called WikiLeaks publications the "most damaging security breach in the history of this country" and Representative [[Peter T. King]] said WikiLeaks should be designated a [[terrorist organisation]].<ref name="Weigel-2017" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=King, Lieberman Condemn Latest WikiLeaks Disclosure |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/newyork/news/king-and-lieberman-condemn-latest-wikileaks-disclosure/ |access-date=30 January 2023 |website=www.cbsnews.com |date=29 November 2010 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=McCullagh |first=Declan |title=Congressman wants WikiLeaks listed as terrorist group |url=https://www.cnet.com/tech/tech-industry/congressman-wants-wikileaks-listed-as-terrorist-group/ |access-date=30 January 2023 |website=CNET |language=en}}</ref> [[Sarah Palin]], [[Bill Kristol|William Kristol]] and [[Rick Santorum]] compared WikiLeaks to a terrorist group.<ref>{{Cite news |title=WikiLeaks' Julian Assange: Does Sarah Palin think CIA should 'neutralize' him? |work=Christian Science Monitor |url=https://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/The-Vote/2010/1130/WikiLeaks-Julian-Assange-Does-Sarah-Palin-think-CIA-should-neutralize-him |access-date=11 September 2023 |issn=0882-7729}}</ref> Senator [[John Ensign]] proposed amending the Espionage Act to target WikiLeaks.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McCullagh |first=Declan |title=GOP senator proposes law targeting WikiLeaks 'cowards' |url=https://www.cnet.com/tech/tech-industry/gop-senator-proposes-law-targeting-wikileaks-cowards/ |access-date=30 January 2023 |website=CNET |language=en}}</ref>

An internal U.S. government review in found that the redacted diplomatic cables leak was embarrassing but caused only limited damage to U.S. interests abroad. In January 2011, a congressional official said they thought the Obama administration felt compelled to say publicly that the release caused severe damage in order to bolster legal efforts to shut down the WikiLeaks website and bring charges against the leakers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hosenball |first1=Mark |title=US officials privately say WikiLeaks damage limited |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/wikileaks-damage-idUSN1816319120110118 |website=[[Reuters]] |access-date=21 February 2023 |language=en |date=18 January 2011}}</ref> In 2012, Representative Ron Paul defended WikiLeaks in a floor speech.<ref name="Weigel-2017" />

In 2015, Representative [[Mac Thornberry]] said WikiLeaks publications had done "enormous" damage and helped the country's "primary adversaries".<ref name="Weigel-2017" /> In 2016, former U.S. representative [[Connie Mack IV|Connie Mack]] said the U.S. public has "a right to know" the contents of the diplomatic documents and said criticism of WikiLeaks was a way of distracting from the revelations contained in WikiLeaks' publications.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rep. Mack once again stands up for WikiLeaks: News. Politics. Media {{!}} Florida Independent 🌈 |url=https://floridaindependent.com/rep-mack-once-again-stands-up-for-wikileaks-news-politics-media/ |website=Florida Independent |access-date=26 March 2023 |date=19 January 2016}}</ref>

Several Republicans who had once been highly critical of WikiLeaks and Julian Assange began to speak fondly of him after WikiLeaks published the DNC leaks and started to regularly criticise Hillary Clinton and the Democratic Party.<ref name="Chait-2017">{{Cite news |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/01/trump-assange-and-the-control-of-the-republican-mind.html |title=Donald Trump, Julian Assange, and the Control of the Republican Mind |last=Chait |first=Jonathan |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York Intelligencer]]|access-date=6 January 2017}}</ref><ref name="washingtonpost.com">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2017/01/04/how-some-republicans-learned-to-stop-worrying-and-love-julian-assange/ |title=How some Republicans learned to stop worrying and love Julian Assange |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=6 January 2017}}</ref> Having called WikiLeaks "disgraceful" in 2010, President-elect Donald Trump praised WikiLeaks in October 2016, saying, "I love WikiLeaks."<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/presidential-races/300327-trump-i-love-wikileaks |title=Trump: 'I love WikiLeaks' |last=Master |first=Cyra |date=10 October 2016 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=6 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/04/politics/kfile-trump-wikileaks/index.html |title=Trump in 2010: WikiLeaks 'disgraceful,' there 'should be like death penalty or something' |first=Andrew |last=Kaczynski |publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=6 January 2017}}</ref> In 2019, Trump said "I know nothing about WikiLeaks. It's not my thing."<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.democracynow.org/2019/4/12/headlines/trump_claims_i_know_nothing_about_wikileaks_despite_praising_site_repeatedly_in_2016 |title = Trump Claims "I Know Nothing About WikiLeaks" Despite Praising Site Repeatedly in 2016|website = [[Democracy Now!]]}}</ref> [[Newt Gingrich]], who called for Assange to be "treated as an enemy combatant" in 2010, praised him as a "down to Earth, straight forward interviewee" in 2017.<ref name="Chait-2017" /> Sarah Palin, who had described Assange as an "anti-American operative with blood on his hands" in 2010, praised Assange in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/04/politics/donald-trump-julian-assange-sarah-palin/index.html |title=Trump, Palin break with GOP, warm up to Assange |first1=David |last1=Wright |first2=Eugene |last2=Scott |publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=6 January 2017}}</ref>

In 2019, [[Tulsi Gabbard]] spoke of the "chilling effect on investigative journalism", first of the US government's reclassification of WikiLeaks from "news organization" to "hostile intelligence service", then of Assange's arrest.<ref name="auto">{{cite news|work=[[CNN]]|title=2020 Democrat says Assange arrest is 'slippery slope' for journalists, Americans|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/04/11/politics/tulsi-gabbard-julian-assange-cnntv/index.html|first=Katie|last=Bernard|date=11 April 2019|access-date=21 April 2019}}</ref> The [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020]] said that "It is the [[sense of Congress]] that WikiLeaks and the senior leadership of WikiLeaks resemble a non-state hostile intelligence service often abetted by state actors and should be treated as such a service by the United States".<ref>{{cite web |date=11 August 2020 |title=H.R.2500 – National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2020 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/2500/}}</ref>

=== Cultural references ===

* Wikileaks: The Game, a 2010 video game by Sebastiaan Moeys that was played by more than a million people.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 December 2010 |title='Wikileaks: The Video Game' Stars Assange and Obama |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/wikileaks-video-game-assange-obama-star-video-game/story?id=12402189 |website=[[ABC News (United States)|ABC News]]}}</ref>
* ''War, Lies and Videotape'' is a documentary by French directors [[Paul Moreira]] and Luc Hermann from press agency Premieres Lignes. The film was released in France in 2011 and then broadcast worldwide.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Keslassy |first1=Elsa |date=8 April 2011 |title=Zodiak sells 'WikiLeaks' docu |url=https://variety.com/2011/tv/news/zodiak-sells-wikileaks-docu-1118035194/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407161600/http://variety.com/2011/tv/news/zodiak-sells-wikileaks-docu-1118035194/ |archive-date=7 April 2014}}</ref>
* ''[[Underground: The Julian Assange Story]]'' is a [[biographical film]] of the early life of Julian Assange directed by [[Robert Connolly]].
* ''[[Mediastan]]'' is a documentary released in 2013 directed by [[Johannes Wahlström]], produced by [[Ken Loach]]'s company Sixteen Films and featuring the people behind WikiLeaks.<ref name="Mediastan">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wikileaks.org/Watch-MEDIASTAN.html|title=WikiLeaks – Watch MEDIASTAN|website=www.wikileaks.org}}</ref>{{Self-published source|date=March 2024}} The film debuted at the [[Raindance Film Festival]].
* The documentary ''[[We Steal Secrets: The Story of WikiLeaks]]'' by director [[Alex Gibney]] premiered at the 2013 [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref name="We Steal Secrets">{{cite web |title=We Steal Secrets: The Story of WikiLeaks |url=http://filmguide.sundance.org/film/13040/we_steal_secrets_the_story_of_wikileaks |publisher=[[Sundance Film Festival]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820153734/http://filmguide.sundance.org/film/13040/we_steal_secrets_the_story_of_wikileaks |archive-date=20 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>
* ''[[The Fifth Estate (film)|The Fifth Estate]]'' is a film directed by [[Bill Condon]], starring [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] as Assange. The film is based on [[Daniel Domscheit-Berg|Daniel Domscheit-Berg's]] book ''Inside WikiLeaks: My Time with Julian Assange and the World's Most Dangerous Website'', as well as ''[[WikiLeaks: Inside Julian Assange's War on Secrecy]]'' by David Leigh and Luke Harding.<ref>{{cite news|author= Brooks, Xan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/mar/02/spielberg-assange-wikileaks-guardian |title=DreamWorks lines up WikiLeaks film based on Guardian book |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=2 March 2011 |access-date=29 March 2013 |location=London}}</ref>
* ''[[The Source (oratorio)|The Source]]'' is a 2014 [[oratorio]] by [[Ted Hearne]], with a libretto by Mark Doten that features WikiLeaks document disclosures by Chelsea Manning.<ref name="nytimes-24oct2014">{{cite news |first=Zachary |last=Woolfe |title=Shadowed, Clamoring, Blurry. And With Reason. |author-link=Zachary Woolfe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/25/arts/the-source-an-oratorio-about-chelsea-mannings-leaks.html|access-date=25 February 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=24 October 2014}}</ref>
* ''The War on Journalism: The Case of Julian Assange'' is a 2020 documentary by Juan Passarelli.<ref>{{cite web |title=Watch: The War on Journalism: The Case of Julian Assange |url=https://consortiumnews.com/2020/08/28/watch-the-war-on-journalism-the-case-of-julian-assange/ |publisher=Consortium News |access-date=4 February 2021 |date=28 August 2020}}</ref>
* ''A Secret Australia: Revealed by the WikiLeaks Exposés''<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Ruby |editor1-first=Felicity |editor2-last=Cronau |editor2-first=Peter |title=A Secret Australia Revealed by the WikiLeaks Exposés |work=Monash University Publishing - The discussion starts here |date=December 2020 |publisher=Monash University Publishing |isbn=9781925835939 |url=https://publishing.monash.edu/product/a-secret-australia/ |access-date=15 February 2021}}</ref> was published in December 2020. The book contains 18 essays by [[Julian Burnside]], [[Antony Loewenstein]], [[Scott Ludlam]], [[Helen Razer]] and others about how WikiLeaks has affected the Australian media and the Australian government's connections to the US intelligence and military industries.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tu |first1=Jessie |title=What Assange and WikiLeaks said about Australia |url=https://www.smh.com.au/culture/books/what-assange-and-wikileaks-said-about-australia-20210129-p56xyo.html |access-date=15 February 2021 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=3 February 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

== Spin-offs ==
Release of United States diplomatic cables was followed by the creation of a number of other organisations based on the WikiLeaks model. WikiLeaks spokesman Kristinn Hrafnsson responded to the idea positively, saying that having more organisations like WikiLeaks was good.<ref>{{Cite news |date=1 December 2010 |title=Dissatisfaction with Assange: Former WikiLeaks Activists to Launch New Whistleblowing Site |language=en |work=Der Spiegel |url=https://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/dissatisfaction-with-assange-former-wikileaks-activists-to-launch-new-whistleblowing-site-a-732212.html |access-date=7 February 2023 |issn=2195-1349}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=WikiLeaks rival plans Monday launch after internal split, founders say |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/TECH/web/12/12/wikileaks.rival/index.html |access-date=7 February 2023 |website=CNN |language=en}}</ref> In 2012, Andy Greenberg said there were more than 50 spin-offs including BaltiLeaks, BritiLeaks, BrusselsLeaks, Corporate Leaks, CrowdLeaks, EnviroLeaks, [[Mediapart|FrenchLeaks]], [[GlobaLeaks]], [[Indoleaks]], IrishLeaks, IsraeliLeaks, Jumbo Leaks, KHLeaks, LeakyMails, Localeaks, MapleLeaks, MurdochLeaks, Office Leaks, [[Porn Wikileaks|Porn WikiLeaks]], PinoyLeaks, PirateLeaks, QuebecLeaks, RuLeaks, ScienceLeaks, TradeLeaks, and UniLeaks.<ref name="Perlroth-2012" /><ref>{{cite news |author=Piven, Ben |date=17 December 2010 |title=Copycat WikiLeaks sites make waves&nbsp;– Features |publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]] |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/indepth/features/2010/12/20101216194828514847.html |url-status=live |access-date=18 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108150656/http://english.aljazeera.net/indepth/features/2010/12/20101216194828514847.html |archive-date=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref name="Greenberg-2013" />

* BalkanLeaks was created in December 2010 and published transcripts of wiretaps in a bribery case against Bulgarian officials, and criminal complaints and trial transcripts of Bulgarian prosecutors.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Greenberg |first=Andy |date=27 September 2012 |title=The WikiLeaks Copycat That Worked |language=en-US |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |url=https://slate.com/technology/2012/09/this-machine-kills-secrets-excerpt-how-two-bulgarian-journalists-created-a-copycat-site-that-actually-worked.html |access-date=7 February 2023 |issn=1091-2339}}</ref>
* RuLeaks was launched in December 2010 to translate and mirror publications by WikiLeaks. In January 2011, it started to publish its own content as well.<ref>{{cite news |author=Razumovskaya, Olga |date=21 January 2011 |title=Russia's Own WikiLeaks Takes Off |work=The Moscow Times |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2011/01/20/russias-own-wikileaks-takes-off-a4391 |url-status=live |access-date=21 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140209151358/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/russias-own-wikileaks-takes-off/429370.html |archive-date=9 February 2014}}</ref>
* [[OpenLeaks]] was created by a former WikiLeaks spokesperson. [[Daniel Domscheit-Berg]] said the intention was to be more transparent than WikiLeaks. OpenLeaks was supposed to start public operations in early 2011 but despite much media coverage, {{as of|2013|April|lc=y}} it is not operating.<ref>{{cite web |date=14 December 2018 |title=Official (inactive) Web site, for OpenLeaks |url=http://www.openleaks.org/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110221164331/http://www.openleaks.org/ |archive-date=21 February 2011 |access-date=14 December 2018 |publisher=OpenLeaks}}</ref>
* Leakymails is a project designed to obtain and publish relevant documents exposing corruption of the political class and the powerful in [[Argentina]].<ref>{{cite news |date=11 August 2011 |title=Argentina: Judge orders all ISPs to block corruption reporting website |url=http://www.indexoncensorship.org/2011/08/argentina-judge-orders-all-isps-to-block-corruption-reporting-website/ |url-status=live |access-date=11 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127154425/http://www.indexoncensorship.org/2011/08/argentina-judge-orders-all-isps-to-block-corruption-reporting-website/ |archive-date=27 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=11 August 2011 |title=Argentina: Judge orders all ISPs to block the sites LeakyMails.com and Leakymails.blogspot.com |url=http://opennet.net/blog/2011/08/argentina-judge-orders-all-isps-block-sites-leakymailscom-and-leakymailsblogspotcom/ |url-status=live |access-date=11 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105224031/https://opennet.net/blog/2011/08/argentina-judge-orders-all-isps-block-sites-leakymailscom-and-leakymailsblogspotcom |archive-date=5 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=19 August 2011 |title=Argentine ISPs Use Bazooka to Kill Fly |url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2011/08/argentina-isps-ip-overblocking |url-status=live |access-date=19 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105224323/https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2011/08/argentina-isps-ip-overblocking |archive-date=5 November 2013}}</ref>
* On 9 September 2013<ref>{{cite web |title=Vanaf vandaag: anoniem lekken naar media via doorgeefluik Publeaks |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2694/Tech-Media/article/detail/3506349/2013/09/09/Vanaf-vandaag-anoniem-lekken-naar-media-via-doorgeefluik-Publeaks.dhtml |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131008173321/http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2694/Tech-Media/article/detail/3506349/2013/09/09/Vanaf-vandaag-anoniem-lekken-naar-media-via-doorgeefluik-Publeaks.dhtml |archive-date=8 October 2013 |access-date=22 February 2014 |website=De Volkskrant}}</ref> a number of major Dutch media outlets supported the launch of Publeaks, which provides a secure website for people to leak documents to the media using the [[GlobaLeaks]] whistleblowing software.<ref>{{cite web |title=Handling ethical problems in counterterrorism An inventory of methods to support ethical decisionmaking |url=https://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/research_reports/RR200/RR251/RAND_RR251.pdf |access-date=24 February 2014 |publisher=RAND Corporation}}</ref>
* [[Distributed Denial of Secrets]] is a [[whistleblower]] site founded in 2018. Sometimes referred to as an alternative to WikiLeaks, it is best known for its publication of a large collection of internal police documents, known as [[BlueLeaks]]. The site has also published data on [[Russian oligarch]]s, fascist groups, [[Shell corporation|shell companies]], [[tax haven]]s, banking in the Caymans and the [[Parler#Content scraping|Parler leak]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=A new group devoted to transparency is exposing secrets Wikileaks chose to keep |url=https://www.cjr.org/tow_center/emma-best-ddosecrets.php |access-date=26 February 2021 |website=Columbia Journalism Review |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=An Embattled Group of Leakers Picks Up the WikiLeaks Mantle |language=en-us |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |url=https://www.wired.com/story/ddosecrets-blueleaks-wikileaks/ |access-date=26 February 2021 |issn=1059-1028}}</ref>

